{"title_page": "Modern Monetary Theory", "text_new": "{{short description|also known as neo-chartalism, a macroeconomic theory}}\n{{Macroeconomics sidebar}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n[[File:M2 Money Stock.png|thumb|260px|M2 Money Stock (United States)|alt=]]\n[[File:Money supply growth vs inflation rates.png|260px|thumb|Money supply growth vs inflation rates]]\n[[File:M2 as a % of GDP.png|thumb|260px|M2 as a % of GDP]]\n\n'''Modern Monetary Theory''' or '''Modern Money Theory''' ('''MMT''') or '''Modern Monetary Theory and Practice''' ('''MMTP''') is a [[macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] theory and practice that describes the practical uses of [[fiat currency]] in a public monopoly from the issuing authority, normally the government's [[central bank]]. Effects on employment are used as evidence that a currency monopolist is overly restricting the supply of the financial assets needed to pay taxes and satisfy savings desires.<ref>Warren Mosler, [http://www00.unibg.it/dati/corsi/910003/64338-Warren%20Mosler%20Bergamo%20paper%20March%2010.pdf ME/MMT: The Currency as a Public Monopoly]</ref><ref name=\"MMTreply\">\u00c9ric Tymoigne and L. Randall Wray, [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_778.pdf \"Modern Money Theory 101: A Reply to Critics,\"] Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, Working Paper No. 778 (November 2013).</ref> MMT is an evolution of [[chartalism]] and is sometimes referred to as '''neo-chartalism'''. Its macroeconomic policy prescriptions have been described as being a version of [[Abba Lerner]]'s theory of [[functional finance]].\n\nMMT advocates argue that the government could use [[fiscal policy]] to achieve [[NAIBER|full employment]], [[Money creation|creating new money]] to fund government purchases. According to advocates, the primary risk once the economy reaches full employment is inflation, which can be addressed by raising and gathering taxes and issuing bonds to reduce money and the [[velocity of money]] in the system.<ref name=\"Wray2015\">{{cite book | last=Wray | first=L. Randall | title=Modern Money Theory : A Primer on Macroeconomics for Sovereign Monetary Systems | publisher=Palgrave Macmillan | location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire New York, NY | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-137-53990-8 | pages=137\u2013141, 199\u2013206}}</ref> MMT is debated, with active dialogues <ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\" /> about its theoretical usefulness, the clear useful real world practical applications and implications, together with the varying effectiveness of its targetted use and varying challenges of its policy prescriptions.\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 325\n | footer = \n | image1 = Money supply increases.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = U.S. money supply change from a year ago ($ Billions).\n | image2 = M2 money supply increases.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Percent change in U.S. [[Monetary policy of the United States|money supply]] vs. year ago.  Money supply increases about 6% per year. \n }}\n\nMMT's main tenets are that a government that issues its own fiat money:\n# Can pay for goods, services, and financial assets without a need to collect money in the form of taxes or debt issuance in advance of such purchases; \n# Cannot be forced to default on debt denominated in its own currency;\n#Is only limited in its money creation and purchases by [[inflation]], which accelerates once the real resources (labour, capital and natural resources) of the economy are utilized at [[NAIBER|full employment]];\n# Can control [[demand-pull inflation]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2019/03/01/1551434402000/An-MMT-response-on-what-causes-inflation/ |title=An MMT response on what causes inflation |last1=Fullwiler |first1=Scott |last2=Grey |first2=Rohan |last3=Tankus |first3=Nathan |publisher=The Financial Times Ltd |date=1 March 2019 |website=FT Alphaville |access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref> by taxation and bond issuance, which remove excess money from circulation (although the political will to do so may not always exist);\n# Does not need to compete with the private sector for scarce savings by issuing bonds.\n\nThese tenets challenge the [[mainstream economics]] view that government spending is funded by taxes and debt issuance.<ref name=\"Kelton1\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-03-01/paul-krugman-s-four-questions-about-mmt? Bloomberg-Stephanie Kelton-Paul Krugman Asked Me About Modern Monetary Theory-1 March 2019]</ref><ref name=\"Kelton2\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-03-04/krugman-s-macroeconomics-is-no-match-for-mmt? Bloomberg-Stephanie Kelton-The Clock Runs Down on Mainstream Keynesianism-4 March 2019]</ref><ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-03-21/modern-monetary-theory-beginner-s-guide Bloomberg-Coy, Dmitrieva & Boesler-A Beginner's Guide to MMT-21 March 2019]</ref> The first four MMT tenets do not conflict with mainstream economics understanding of how money creation and inflation works. For example, as former Fed Chair [[Alan Greenspan]] said, \"The United States can pay any debt it has because we can always print money to do that. So there is zero probability of default.\"<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/44051683 No Chance of Default, US Can Print Money: Greenspan CNBC-No Chance of Default, US Can Print Money: Greenspan-7 August 2011]</ref> However, MMT economists disagree with mainstream economics about the fifth tenet, on the impact of government deficits on interest rates.<ref name=\"Bell2000\" /><ref name=\"Sharpe2013\">Sharpe, Timothy P. (2013) \"A Modern Money Perspective On Financial Crowding Out\", Review of Political Economy, 25:4, 586-606</ref><ref name=\"policydebate1\" /><ref name=\"Fullwiler2016\">Fullwiler, Scott T. (2016) \"The Debt Ratio and Sustainable Macroeconomic Policy\", World Economic Review 7:12-42</ref><ref name=Lavoie />\n\nA 2019 survey of leading economists by the [[University of Chicago Booth School of Business|University of Chicago Booth]]'s [[Initiative on Global Markets]] showed a unanimous rejection of assertions that the survey attributes to modern monetary theory.\n\n==History==\nMMT synthesizes ideas from the ''State Theory of Money'' of [[Georg Friedrich Knapp]] (also known as [[Chartalism]]) and ''Credit Theory of Money'' of [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]], the ''[[functional finance]]'' proposals of [[Abba Lerner]], [[Hyman Minsky]]'s views on the ''banking system''<ref name=\"Minsky, Hyman 2008\">Minsky, Hyman: ''Stabilizing an Unstable Economy'', McGraw-Hill, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-07-159299-4}}</ref> and [[Wynne Godley]]'s ''[[Sectoral balances]]'' approach.<ref name=\"policydebate1\">{{citation|first1=Scott |last1= Fullwiler| first2=Stephanie |last2= Kelton | first3=L. Randall | last3= Wray |contribution = Modern Money Theory : A Response to Critics|title= Working Paper Series: Modern Monetary Theory - A Debate| pages=17\u201326|publisher = [[Political Economy Research Institute]] |location=Amherst, MA |number = 279 | date = January 2012 | accessdate= 7 May 2015 | url= http://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/working_papers/working_papers_251-300/WP279.pdf }}</ref>\n\n[[Georg Friedrich Knapp|Knapp]], writing in 1905, argued that \"money is a creature of law\" rather than a [[commodity money|commodity]].<ref name=\"George Friedrich Knapp 1924\">{{Citation|title=Staatilche Theorie des Geldes|author=Knapp, George Friedrich|year=1905|publisher= Verlag von Duncker & Humblot}}</ref> Knapp contrasted his state theory of money with the [[Gold Standard]] view of \"[[metallism]]\", where the value of a unit of currency depends on the quantity of precious metal it contains or for which it may be exchanged. He argued that the state can create pure paper money and make it exchangeable by recognizing it as [[legal tender]], with the criterion for the money of a state being \"that which is accepted at the public pay offices\".<ref name=\"George Friedrich Knapp 1924\" />\n\nThe prevailing view of money was that it had evolved from systems of [[barter]] to become a [[medium of exchange]] because it represented a durable [[commodity money|commodity]] which had some [[use value]],<ref>Karl Marx, Capital I, Chapter 1, two paragraphs starting \"The utility of a thing makes it a use value.\" http://www.efm.bris.ac.uk/het/marx/cap1/chap01 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923234227/http://www.efm.bris.ac.uk/het/marx/cap1/chap01 |date=23 September 2015 }} accessed 18 May 2009.</ref> but proponents of MMT such as Randall Wray and Mathew Forstater argue that more general statements appearing to support a [[Chartalism|chartalist]] view of tax-driven paper money appear in the earlier writings of many classical economists,<ref name=\"wray2000\" /> including [[Adam Smith]], [[Jean-Baptiste Say]], [[J.S. Mill]], [[Karl Marx]], and [[William Stanley Jevons]].<ref name=forstater>{{citation | title=Tax-Driven Money: Additional Evidence from the History of Thought, Economic History, and Economic Policy | author=Forstater, Mathew |year=2004 |url=http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp-pdf/WP35-Forstater.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]], writing in 1914, argued that money exists not as a [[medium of exchange]] but as a [[standard of deferred payment]], with government money being debt the government may reclaim through taxation.<ref name=\"Innes\">{{cite journal | author=Mitchell-Innes, Alfred |title=The Credit Theory of Money |journal= The Banking Law Journal | year=1914 |volume=31 |url=https://www.community-exchange.org/docs/The%20Credit%20Theoriy%20of%20Money.htm}}</ref> Innes argued:\n{{Quotation|Whenever a tax is imposed, each taxpayer becomes responsible for the redemption of a small part of the debt which the government has contracted by its issues of money, whether coins, certificates, notes, drafts on the treasury, or by whatever name this money is called. He has to acquire his portion of the debt from some holder of a coin or certificate or other form of government money, and present it to the Treasury in liquidation of his legal debt. He has to redeem or cancel that portion of the debt...The redemption of government debt by taxation is the basic law of coinage and of any issue of government \u2018money\u2019 in whatever form.|Alfred Mitchell-Innes|The Credit Theory of Money|The Banking Law Journal|}}\n\nKnapp and \"chartalism\" are referenced by [[John Maynard Keynes]] in the opening pages of his 1930 ''[[A Treatise on Money|Treatise on Money]]''<ref>Keynes, John Maynard: ''A Treatise on Money'', 1930, pp. 4, 6</ref> and appear to have influenced [[Keynesian]] ideas on the role of the state in the economy.<ref name=\"wray2000\">{{Citation |title=The Neo-Chartalist Approach to Money |last=Wray |first=L. Randall |issue=Working Paper No. 10 |year=2000 |url= http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp/wp10.html |publisher=[[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City|UMKC]] Center for Full Employment and Price Stability}}</ref>\n\nBy 1947, when Abba Lerner wrote his article ''Money as a Creature of the State'', economists had largely abandoned the idea that the value of money was closely linked to gold.<ref name=Lerner /> Lerner argued that responsibility for avoiding inflation and depressions lay with the state because of its ability to create or tax away money.<ref name=\"Lerner\">{{cite journal|last=Lerner|first=Abba P.|date=May 1947|title=Money as a Creature of the State|url=|journal=The American Economic Review|volume=37|pages=|via=|number=2}}</ref>\n\nEconomists [[Warren Mosler]], [[L. Randall Wray]], [[Stephanie Kelton]],<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Bill Mitchell (economist)|Bill Mitchell]] and [[Pavlina R. Tcherneva]] are largely responsible for reviving the idea of chartalism as an explanation of [[money creation]]; Wray refers to this revived formulation as ''Neo-Chartalism''.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/node/21542174 The Economist, 31 December 2011, \"Marginal revolutionaries\"] neo-chartalism, sometimes called \"Modern Monetary Theory\"</ref>\n\nBill Mitchell, Professor of Economics and Director of the Centre of Full Employment and Equity or [[Centre of Full Employment and Equity|CofFEE]],\nat the [[University of Newcastle, Australia|University of Newcastle]], [[New South Wales]], refers to an increasing related theoretical work as ''{{visible anchor|Modern Monetary Theory}}''.\n\nPavlina R. Tcherneva has developed the first mathematical framework for MMT<ref>{{cite web|url=https://modernmoneynetwork.org/sites/default/files/biblio/Pavlina_2007.pdf|title=Monopoly Money: The State as a Price Setter |author=Tcherneva, Pavlina R. |website=www.modernmoneynetwork.org |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> and has largely focused on developing the idea of the [[Job Guarantee]].\n\nScott Fullwiler has added detailed technical analysis of the banking and monetary systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=444041 |title=Author Page for Scott T. Fullwiler :: SSRN |website=Papers.ssrn.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-28}}</ref>\n\nRodger Malcolm Mitchell's book ''Free Money''<ref>Mitchell, Rodger Malcolm: ''Free Money \u2013 Plan for Prosperity'', PGM International, Inc., paperback 2005, {{ISBN|978-0-9658323-1-1}}</ref> (1996) describes in layman's terms the essence of chartalism.\n\nSome contemporary proponents, such as Wray, place MMT within [[post-Keynesian economics]], while MMT has been proposed as an alternative or complementary theory to [[monetary circuit theory]], both being forms of [[endogenous money]], i.e. money created within the economy, as by government deficit spending or bank lending, rather than from outside, as by gold. In the complementary view, MMT explains the \"vertical\" (government-to-private and vice versa) interactions, while circuit theory is a model of the \"horizontal\" (private-to-private) interactions.<ref name=def1013>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=381 \"Deficit Spending 101 \u2013 Part 3\"]  Bill Mitchell, 2 March 2009</ref><ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=5199 \"In the spirit of debate...my reply\"] Bill Mitchell, 28 September 2009</ref>\n\n[[Hyman Minsky]] seemed to favor a chartalist approach to understanding money creation in his ''Stabilizing an Unstable Economy'',<ref name=\"Minsky, Hyman 2008\"/> while [[Basil Moore (economist)|Basil Moore]], in his book ''Horizontalists and Verticalists'',<ref>Moore, Basil J.: ''Horizontalists and Verticalists: The Macroeconomics of Credit Money'', Cambridge University Press, 1988, {{ISBN|978-0-521-35079-2}}</ref> lists the differences between bank money and state money.\n\n[[James K. Galbraith]] supports MMT and wrote the foreword for Mosler's book ''Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds of Economic Policy'' in 2010.<ref>Mosler, Warren: ''Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds of Economic Policy'', Valance Co., 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-692-00959-8}}; also available in [http://www.moslereconomics.com/wp-content/powerpoints/7DIF2.doc .DOC]</ref>\n\nSteven Hail of the [[University of Adelaide]] is another well known MMT economist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qBpm5sVmGYc|title=Steven Hail's presentation on modern money and the \"budget emergency\"|last=|first=|date=2014-08-31|website=|publisher=|access-date=|author=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"abc.jg\">{{Cite web |title=The case for offering every Australian a government-funded job |last=Wood |first=Patrick |publisher=ABC News |date= 20 November 2018|access-date=14 May 2019 |url= https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-21/stephanie-kelton-on-modern-monetary-theory-and-a-job-guarantee/10510758 |quote=University of Adelaide economics lecturer Steven Hail is an expert in MMT and regularly speaks on the topic. }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the first academic textbook based on the theory was published.<ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\"/>\n\n==Theoretical approach==\nIn sovereign financial systems, banks can create money but these \"horizontal\" transactions do not increase net [[financial assets]] as assets are offset by liabilities. According to MMT adherents, \"The balance sheet of the government does not include any domestic monetary instrument on its asset side; it owns no money. All monetary instruments issued by the government are on its liability side and are created and destroyed with spending and taxing/bond offerings, respectively.\"<ref name=\"MMTreply\"/> In MMT, \"vertical money\" enters circulation through [[government spending]]. [[Taxation]] and its [[legal tender]] enable power to discharge debt and establish the [[fiat money]] as currency, giving it value by creating demand for it in the form of a private tax obligation that must be met. In addition, fines, fees and licenses create demand for the currency. This can be a currency issued by the domestic government, or a foreign currency.<ref>[[Warren Mosler|Mosler, Warren]]. [http://moslereconomics.com/mandatory-readings/soft-currency-economics/ \"Soft Currency Economics\"], January 1994</ref><ref>[[Pavlina R. Tcherneva|Tcherneva Pavlina R.]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=TPa22fYkDSsC&pg=PA69 \"Chartalism and the tax-driven approach to money\"], in ''A Handbook of Alternative Monetary Economics'', edited by Philip Arestis & Malcolm C. Sawyer, Elgar Publishing (2007), {{ISBN|978-1-84376-915-6}}</ref> An ongoing tax obligation, in concert with private confidence and acceptance of the currency, maintains its value. Because the government can issue its own currency at will, MMT maintains that the level of taxation relative to government spending (the government's [[deficit spending]] or [[budget surplus]]) is in reality a policy tool that regulates inflation and [[unemployment]], and not a means of funding the government's activities by itself. The approach of MMT typically reverses theories of governmental [[austerity]]. The policy implications of the two are likewise typically opposed.\n\n===Vertical transactions===\n[[File:Sectoral balances circuit diagram.png|thumb|400px|Illustration of the [[saving identity]] with the three sectors, the computation of the surplus or deficit balances for each and the flows between them<ref name=\"CBO_Aug2018\">[https://www.cbo.gov/publication/54318 CBO-An Update to the Economic Outlook: 2018 to 2028-Retrieved November 12, 2018]</ref>]]\n{{Further|Sectoral balances}}\nMMT labels any transactions between the government, or public sector, and the non-government, or private sector, as a \"vertical transaction\". The government sector is considered to include the treasury and the [[central bank]]. The non-government sector includes domestic and foreign private individuals and firms (including the private banking system) and foreign buyers and sellers of the currency.<ref name=\"Mitchelletal2019\">Mitchell, William; Wray, L. Randall; Watts, Martin: ''Macroeconomics'', Red Globe Press, 2019, {{ISBN|978-1137610669}}. pp.84-87</ref>\n\n==Interaction between government and the banking sector==\nMMT is based on an account of the \"operational realities\" of interactions between the government and its central bank, and the commercial banking sector, with proponents like Scott Fullwiler arguing that understanding reserve accounting is critical to understanding monetary policy options.<ref name=FullPrimer>Scott T. Fullwiler, [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1723198 \"Modern Monetary Theory\u2014A Primer on the Operational Realities of the Monetary System,\"] Wartburg College; Bard College - The Levy Economics Institute (30 August 2010).</ref>\n\nA sovereign government typically has an operating account with the country's central bank. From this account, the government can spend and also receive taxes and other inflows.<ref name=def1013 /> Each commercial bank also has an account with the central bank, by means of which it manages its reserves (that is, money for clearing and settling interbank transactions).<ref name=\"Meulendyke\">Meulendyke, A.M. (1998) U.S. Monetary Policy and Financial Markets. New York: Federal\nReserve Bank of New York.</ref>\n\nWhen the government spends money, the treasury debits its operating account at the central bank, and deposits this money into private bank accounts (and hence into the commercial banking system). This money adds to the total deposits in the commercial bank sector. Taxation works exactly in reverse; private bank accounts are debited, and hence deposits in the commercial banking sector fall. In the United States, a portion of tax receipts are deposited in the treasury operating account, and a portion in commercial banks' designated [[Treasury Tax and Loan]] accounts.<ref name=\"Bell2000\" /><ref name=\"NYFed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkfed.org/aboutthefed/fedpoint/fed21.html|title=Treasury and Tax and Loan Program|accessdate=16 June 2016|publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of New York|date=April 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Government bonds and interest rate maintenance===\n[[File:U.S. Treasuries.png|thumb|right|350px|The Federal Reserve raising the [[Federal Funds Rate]] above [[United States Treasury security|U.S. Treasury]] interest rates creates an [[inverted yield curve]], which is a predictor of recessions.]]\nVirtually all central banks set an interest rate target, and conduct [[open market operations]] to ensure base interest rates remain at that target level. According to MMT, the issuing of government bonds is best understood as an operation to ''offset'' government spending rather than a requirement to ''finance'' it.<ref name=\"FullPrimer\" />\n\nIn most countries, commercial banks\u2019 reserve accounts with the central bank must have a positive balance at the end of every day; in some countries, the amount is specifically set as a proportion of the liabilities a bank has (i.e. its customer deposits). This is known as a [[reserve requirement]].\nAt the end of every day, a commercial bank will have to examine the status of their reserve accounts. Those that are in deficit have the option of borrowing the required funds from the central bank, where they may be charged a ''lending rate'' (sometimes known as a ''[[discount window|discount rate]]'') on the amount they borrow. On the other hand, the banks that have excess reserves can simply leave them with the central bank and earn a ''support rate'' from the central bank. Some countries, such as [[Economy of Japan|Japan]], have a support rate of zero.<ref name=\"bis.org\">[http://www.bis.org/publ/work292.pdf?noframes=1 \"Unconventional monetary policies: an appraisal\"] by Claudio Borio and Piti Disyatat, Bank for International Settlements, November 2009</ref>\n\nBanks with more reserves than they need will be willing to lend to banks with a reserve shortage on the [[interbank lending market]]. The surplus banks will want to earn a higher rate than the support rate that the central bank pays on reserves; whereas the deficit banks will want to pay a lower interest rate than the discount rate the central bank charges for borrowing. Thus they will lend to each other until each bank has reached their reserve requirement. In a balanced system, where there are just enough total reserves for all the banks to meet requirements, the short-term interbank lending rate will be in between the support rate and the discount rate.<ref name=\"bis.org\"/>\n\nUnder an MMT framework where government spending injects new reserves into the commercial banking system, and taxes withdraw them from the banking system,<ref name=\"Bell2000\" /> government activity would have an instant effect on interbank lending. If on a particular day, the government spends more than it taxes, reserves have been added to the banking system (see [[#Vertical transactions|vertical transactions]]). This will typically lead to a system-wide surplus of reserves, with competition between banks seeking to lend their excess reserves forcing the short-term interest rate down to the support rate (or alternately, to zero if a support rate is not in place). At this point banks will simply keep their reserve surplus with their central bank and earn the support rate.<ref name=\"Fullwiler2005\">Fullwiler, Scott T. (2005) \"Paying Interest on Reserve Balances: It\u2019s More Significant Than You Think\" (Working Paper No. 38), Wartburg College and the UMKC Center for Full Employment and Price Stability</ref>\n\nThe alternate case is where the government receives more taxes on a particular day than it spends. In this case, there may be a system-wide deficit of reserves. As a result, surplus funds will be in demand on the interbank market, and thus the short-term interest rate will rise towards the discount rate. Thus, if the central bank wants to maintain a target interest rate somewhere between the support rate and the discount rate, it must manage the liquidity in the system to ensure that the correct amount of reserves is on hand in the banking system.<ref name=\"Bell2000\">Bell, Stephanie, (2000), \"Do Taxes and Bonds Finance Government Spending?\", Journal of Economic Issues, 34, issue 3, p. 603-620</ref>\n\nCentral banks manage this by buying and selling government bonds on the open market. On a day where there are excess reserves in the banking system, the central bank sells bonds and therefore removes reserves from the banking system, as private individuals pay for the bonds. On a day where there are not enough reserves in the system, the central bank buys government bonds from the private sector, and therefore adds reserves to the banking system.\n\nIt is important to note that the central bank buys bonds by simply creating money \u2014 it is not financed in any way.<ref name=\"Bell287\">Bell, Stephanie (1999), \"Functional Finance: What, Why, and How?\" (Working Paper No. 287), UMKC Center for Full Employment and Price Stability</ref> It is a net injection of reserves into the banking system. If a central bank is to maintain a target interest rate, then it must necessarily buy and sell government bonds on the open market in order to maintain the correct amount of reserves in the system.<ref name=\"Fullwiler2007\">Fullwiler, Scott T. (2007) \"Interest Rates and Fiscal Sustainability\", Journal of Economic Issues, 41:4, 1003-1042</ref>\n\n==Horizontal transactions==\n{{Further|Monetary circuit theory}}\nMMT economists describe any transactions within the private sector as \"horizontal\" transactions, including the expansion of the [[broad money]] supply through the extension of credit by banks.\n\nMMT economists regard the concept of the [[money multiplier]], where a bank is completely constrained in lending through the deposits it holds and its capital requirement, as misleading.<ref name=\"Wray1990\">Wray, L Randall: ''Money and Credit in Capitalist Economies: The Endogenous Money Approach'', Edward Elgar Publishing, 1990 {{ISBN|1-85278-356-7}} pp.149,179</ref><ref name=\"Lavoie2006\">Lavoie, Marc: ''Introduction to Post-Keynesian Economics'', Palgrave MacMillan, 2006 {{ISBN|9780230626300}} pp.60-73</ref> Rather than being a practical limitation on lending, the cost of borrowing funds from the interbank market (or the central bank) represents a ''profitability consideration'' when the private bank lends in excess of its reserve and/or capital requirements (see [[#Interaction between government and the banking sector|interaction between government and the banking sector]]).\n\nAccording to MMT, bank credit should be regarded as a \"leverage\" of the [[monetary base]] and should not be regarded as increasing the net financial assets held by an economy: only the government or central bank is able to issue high-powered money with no corresponding liability.<ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=1623 \"Money multiplier and other myths\"] Bill Mitchell, 21 April 2009</ref> Stephanie Kelton argues that bank money is generally accepted in settlement of debt and taxes because of state guarantees, but that state-issued high-powered money sits atop a \"hierarchy of money\".<ref name=bell>{{citation|first=Stephanie (Bell)| last=Kelton|year=2001|title=The Role of the State and the Hierarchy of Money|journal=[[Cambridge Journal of Economics]]| number=25|pages=149\u2013163|url=http://cas.umkc.edu/economics/people/facultyPages/wray/courses/Econ601%202012/readings/Bell%20The%20Role%20of%20the%20State%20and%20the%20Hierarchy%20of%20Money.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign sector==\n===Imports and exports===\n\nMMT proponents such as [[Warren Mosler]] argue that trade deficits need not be unsustainable and are beneficial to the standard of living in the short run.<ref name=\"Mosler\">{{cite book|last=Mosler|first=Warren|title=Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds|year=2010|publisher=Valance|isbn=978-0-692-00959-8|pages=60\u201362|url=http://moslereconomics.com/wp-content/powerpoints/7DIF.pdf}}</ref> Imports are an economic benefit to the importing nation because they provide the nation with real goods it can consume, that it otherwise would not have had. Exports, on the other hand, are an economic cost to the exporting nation because it is losing real goods that it could have consumed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=10389 \"Do current account deficits matter?\"] Bill Mitchell, 22 June 2010</ref> Currency transferred to foreign ownership, however, represents a future claim over goods of that nation.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nCheap imports may also cause the failure of local firms providing similar goods at higher prices, and hence unemployment but MMT commentators label that consideration as a subjective value-based one, rather than an economic-based one: it is up to a nation to decide whether it values the benefit of cheaper imports more than it values employment in a particular industry.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Similarly a nation overly dependent on imports may face a supply shock if the exchange rate drops significantly, though central banks can and do trade on the FX markets to avoid sharp shocks to the exchange rate.<ref>[http://www.rba.gov.au/statistics/tables/xls/a04hist.xls Foreign Exchange Transactions and Holdings of Official Reserve Assets], Reserve Bank of Australia</ref>\n\n===Foreign sector and government===\nMMT argues that as long as there is a demand for the issuer's currency, whether the bond holder is foreign or not, governments can never be insolvent when the debt obligations are in their own currency; this is because the government is not constrained in creating its own fiat currency (although the bond holder may affect the exchange rate by converting to local currency).<ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=10554 \"Modern monetary theory and inflation \u2013 Part 1\"] Bill Mitchell, 7 July 2010</ref>\n\nMMT does agree with mainstream economics, that debt denominated in a foreign currency certainly is a fiscal risk to governments, since the indebted government cannot create foreign currency. In this case the only way the government can sustainably repay its foreign debt is to ensure that its currency is continually in high demand by foreigners over the period that it wishes to repay the debt \u2013 an exchange rate collapse would potentially multiply the debt many times over asymptotically, making it impossible to repay. In that case, the government can default, or attempt to shift to an export-led strategy or raise interest rates to attract foreign investment in the currency. Either one has a negative effect on the economy.<ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=11854 \"There is no financial crisis so deep that cannot be dealt with by public spending \u2013 still!\"] Bill Mitchell, 11 October 2010</ref>\n\n==Policy implications==\n{{Further|NAIBER}}\n\nEconomist [[Stephanie Kelton]] explained several policy claims made by MMT in March 2019:\n*Under MMT, [[fiscal policy]] (i.e., government taxing and spending decisions) is the primary means of achieving full employment, establishing the budget deficit at the level necessary to reach that goal. In mainstream economics, [[monetary policy]] (i.e., central bank adjustment of interest rates and its balance sheet) is the primary mechanism, assuming there is some interest rate low enough to achieve full employment. Kelton claims that cutting interest rates is ineffective in a slump, because businesses expecting weak profits and few customers will not invest at even very low interest rates.\n*Government interest expenses are proportional to interest rates, so raising rates is a form of stimulus (it increases the budget deficit and injects money into the private sector, other things equal), while cutting rates is a form of austerity.\n*Achieving full employment can be administered via a federally funded [[job guarantee]], which acts as an [[automatic stabilizer]]. When private sector jobs are plentiful, the government spending on guaranteed jobs is lower, and vice versa.\n*Under MMT, expansionary fiscal policy (i.e., money creation to fund purchases) can increase bank reserves, which can lower interest rates. In mainstream economics, expansionary fiscal policy (i.e., debt issuance and spending) can result in higher interest rates, crowding out economic activity.<ref name=\"Kelton1\"/><ref name=\"Kelton2\"/>\n\nEconomist [[John T. Harvey]] explained several of the premises of MMT and their policy implications in March 2019:\n*The private sector treats labor as a cost to be minimized, so it cannot be expected to achieve full employment without government creating jobs as well, such as through a job guarantee.\n*The public sector's deficit is the private sector's surplus and vice-versa, by accounting identity, a reason why private sector debt increased during the Clinton-era budget surpluses.\n*Idle resources (mainly labor) can be activated by money creation. Not acting to do so is immoral.\n*Demand can be insensitive to interest rate changes, so a key mainstream assumption, that lower interest rates lead to higher demand, is questionable.\n*When the economy is below full employment, there is a \"free lunch\" in creating money to fund government expenditure to achieve full employment. Unemployment is a burden; full employment is not.\n*Creating money alone does not cause inflation; spending it when the economy is at or above full employment can.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/johntharvey/2019/03/05/mmt-sense-or-nonsense/#37c9928b5852 Forbes-John T. Harvey-MMT: Sense or Nonsense?-5 March 2019]</ref>\n\nMMT claims that the word \"borrowing\" is a misnomer when it comes to a sovereign government's fiscal operations, because what the government is doing is accepting back its own [[IOU]]s, and nobody can borrow back their own debt instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4J0j5VwnD7I |title=Q:Why does government issue bonds? Randall Wray: Sovereign government really can't borrow, because what it is doing is accepting back its own IOUs. If you have given your IOU to your neighbour because you borrowed some sugar, could you borrow it back? No, you can't borrow back your own IOUs.|website=Youtube.com|accessdate=2016-07-28}}</ref> Sovereign government goes into debt by issuing its own liabilities that are financial wealth to the private sector. \"Private debt is debt, but government debt is ''financial wealth'' to the private sector.\"<ref>Yeva Nersisyan & L. Randall Wray, [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_603.pdf \"Does Excessive Sovereign Debt Really Hurt Growth? A Critique of ''This Time Is Different'', by Reinhart and Rogoff,\"] Levy Economics Institute (June 2010), p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn this theory, sovereign government is not ''financially'' constrained in its ability to spend; it is argued that the government can afford to buy anything that is for sale in currency that it issues (there may be political constraints, like a [[debt ceiling]] law). The only constraint is that excessive spending by any sector of the economy (whether households, firms, or public) could cause inflationary pressures.\n\nMMT economists advocate a government-funded [[job guarantee]] scheme to eliminate [[involuntary unemployment]]. Proponents argue that this can be consistent with [[price stability]] as it targets unemployment directly rather than attempting to increase private sector job creation indirectly through a much larger economic stimulus, and maintains a \"buffer stock\" of labor that can readily switch to the private sector when jobs become available. A job guarantee program could also be considered an [[automatic stabilizer]] to the economy, expanding when private sector activity cools down and shrinking in size when private sector activity heats up.<ref name=\"elrJobGuarantee\">L. Randal Wray, [http://neweconomicperspectives.org/2009/08/job-guarantee.html \"Job Guarantee,\"] ''New Economic Perspectives'' (23 August 2009).</ref>\n\n==Comparison of MMT with mainstream Keynesian economics==\nMMT can be compared and contrasted with mainstream Keynesian economics in a variety of ways:<ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\"/><ref name=\"Kelton1\"/><ref name=\"Kelton2\"/> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Topic\n! Mainstream Keynesian\n! MMT\n|-\n| Funding government spending\n| Advocates taxation and issuing bonds (debt) as preferred methods for funding government spending.\n| Emphasizes that taxation and debt issuance are not required to fund spending.\n|-\n| Purpose of taxation\n| Fund government spending and address inequality.\n| Primarily to drive demand for the currency. Secondary uses of taxation include addressing inflation, addressing income inequality, and discouraging bad behaviour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://neweconomicperspectives.org/2014/05/taxes-mmt-approach.html |title=WHAT ARE TAXES FOR? THE MMT APPROACH |last=Wray |first=L. Randall }}</ref>\n|-\n| Achieving full employment\n| Main strategy uses [[monetary policy]]; Fed has \"dual mandate\" of maximum employment and stable prices, but these goals are not always compatible. For example, much higher interest rates used to reduce inflation also caused high unemployment in the early 1980s.<ref name=\"Dual_Mandate1\"/>\n| Main strategy uses [[fiscal policy]]; running a budget deficit large enough to achieve full employment through a [[job guarantee]].\n|-\n| Inflation control\n| Driven by monetary policy; Fed sets interest rates consistent with a stable price level, sometimes setting a [[Inflation targeting#United States|target inflation rate]].<ref name=\"Dual_Mandate1\"/>\n| Driven by fiscal policy; government increases taxes or issues bonds to remove money from private sector. A job guarantee also provides a [[NAIBER]], which acts as an inflation control mechanism.\n|-\n| Setting interest rates\n| Managed by Fed to achieve \"dual mandate\" of maximum employment and stable prices.<ref name=\"Dual_Mandate1\">[https://www.richmondfed.org/publications/research/economic_brief/2011/eb_11-12 \"FRB Richmond-Aaron Steelman-The Federal Reserves Dual Mandate: The Evolution of an Idea\"-December 2011]</ref>\n| Emphasizes that an interest rate target is not a potent policy.<ref name=\"Kelton1\"/> The government may choose to maintain a [[zero interest-rate policy]] by not issuing public debt at all.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=31715 |title=There is no need to issue public debt |last=Mitchell |first=William |date=3 September 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Budget deficit impact on interest rates\n| At full employment, higher budget deficit can [[crowding out (economics)|crowd-out]] investment.\n| Deficit spending can drive down interest rates, encouraging investment and thus \"crowding-in\" economic activity.<ref name=\"Kelton_3\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-02-21/modern-monetary-theory-is-not-a-recipe-for-doom Bloomberg-Stephanie Kelton-Modern Monetary Theory Is Not a Recipe for Doom-21 February 2019]</ref>\n|-\n| Automatic stabilizers\n| Primary stabilizers are [[Unemployment benefits#United States|unemployment insurance]] and [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program|food stamps]], which increase budget deficits in a downturn.\n| In addition to the other stabilizers, a job guarantee would increase deficits in a downturn.<ref name=\"elrJobGuarantee\" />\n|}\n\n==Criticisms==\n\nA 2019 survey of leading economists by the [[University of Chicago Booth School of Business|University of Chicago Booth]]'s [[Initiative on Global Markets]] showed a unanimous rejection of assertions that the survey attributes to modern monetary theory: \"Countries that borrow in their own currency should not worry about government deficits because they can always create money to finance their debt\" and \"Countries that borrow in their own currency can finance as much real government spending as they want by creating money\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/modern-monetary-theory|title=Modern Monetary Theory|last=|first=|date=2019|website=www.igmchicago.org|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/economist-survey-alexandria-ocasio-cortez-modern-monetary-theory-2019-3|title=A new survey shows that zero top US economists agreed with the basic principles of an economic theory supported by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez|last=Bryan|first=Bob|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-03-15|date=14 March 2019}}</ref> Directly responding to the survey, MMT economist William K. Black said \"MMT scholars do not make or support either claim.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://neweconomicperspectives.org/2019/03/the-day-orthodox-economists-lost-their-minds-and-integrity.html |title=The Day Orthodox Economists Lost Their Minds and Integrity |date=2019 |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> Multiple MMT academics regard the attribution of these claims as a smear.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=41823 |title=Fake surveys and Groupthink in the economics profession |date=2019-03-19 |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe [[post-Keynesian]] economist [[Thomas Palley]] argues that MMT is largely a restatement of elementary [[Keynesian economics]], but prone to \"over-simplistic analysis\" and understating the risks of its policy implications.<ref name=\"palley\">{{citation |author=Thomas Palley |title=Money, fiscal policy, and interest rates: A critique of Modern Monetary Theory |url=http://www.thomaspalley.com/docs/articles/macro_theory/mmt.pdf}}</ref> Palley denies the MMT claim that standard Keynesian analysis does not fully capture the accounting identities and financial restraints on a government that can issue its own money. He argues that these insights are well captured by standard Keynesian stock-flow consistent [[IS-LM model]]s, and have been well understood by Keynesian economists for decades. He also criticizes MMT for \"assum[ing] away the problem of fiscal\u2013monetary conflict\"<ref name=\"palley2\"/> \u2014 that is, that the governmental body that creates the spending budget (e.g. Congress) may refuse to cooperate with the governmental body that controls the money supply (e.g. the [[Federal Reserve]]). In Palley's view the policies proposed by MMT proponents would cause serious financial instability in an open economy with [[Floating exchange rate|flexible exchange rates]], while using [[Fixed exchange-rate system|fixed exchange rates]] would restore hard financial constraints on the government and \"undermines MMT\u2019s main claim about sovereign money freeing governments from standard market disciplines and financial constraints\". He also argues that MMT lacks a plausible [[Monetary inflation|theory of inflation]], particularly in the context of full employment in the [[employer of last resort]] policy first proposed by [[Hyman Minsky]] and advocated by [[Bill Mitchell (economist)|Bill Mitchell]] and other MMT theorists; of a lack of appreciation of the financial instability that could be caused by permanently zero interest rates; and of overstating the importance of government created money. Palley concludes that MMT provides no new insights about monetary theory, while making unsubstantiated claims about macroeconomic policy, and that MMT has only received attention recently due to it being a \"policy polemic for depressed times.\"<ref name=\"palley2\">{{cite web |author=Thomas Palley |title=Modern money theory (MMT): the emperor still has no clothes |date=February 2014 |url=http://www.thomaspalley.com/docs/articles/macro_theory/mmt_response_to_wray.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Marc Lavoie]] argues that whilst the neochartalist argument is \"essentially correct\", many of its counter-intuitive claims depend on a \"confusing\" and \"fictitious\" consolidation of government and central banking operations<ref name=Lavoie>{{cite web |author=Marc Lavoie |title=The monetary and fiscal nexus of neo-chartalism |url=http://www.boeckler.de/pdf/v_2011_10_27_lavoie.pdf}}</ref> \u2014 again what Palley calls \"the problem of fiscal\u2013monetary conflict.\"<ref name=\"palley2\"/>\n\n[[New Keynesian economics|New Keynesian]] economist and Nobel laureate [[Paul Krugman]] argues that MMT goes too far in its support for government budget deficits and ignores the inflationary implications of maintaining budget deficits when the economy is growing.<ref name=krugman>{{cite news |author=Paul Krugman |title=Deficits and the Printing Press (Somewhat Wonkish) |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date =2011-03-25 |url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/25/deficits-and-the-printing-press-somewhat-wonkish/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326161843/http://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/25/deficits-and-the-printing-press-somewhat-wonkish/ |archivedate=2011-03-26 |url-status=live |accessdate=2011-07-17|author-link=Paul Krugman }}</ref> Krugman described MMT devotees as engaging in \"[[Calvin and Hobbes#Calvinball|calvinball]]\" \u2014 a game from the comic strip ''[[Calvin and Hobbes]]'' in which the players change the rules at whim.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2019/03/12/is-modern-monetary-theory-nutty-or-essential |title=Is modern monetary theory nutty or essential? |date=2019-03-12 |work=The Economist |access-date=2019-03-12 |issn=0013-0613}}</ref> [[Austrian School]] economist [[Robert P. Murphy]] states that MMT is \"dead wrong\" and that \"the MMT worldview doesn't live up to its promises.\"<ref name=\"murphy\"/> He observes that MMT's claim that cutting government deficits erodes private saving is true \"only for the portion of private saving that is not invested\" and argues that the national accounting identities used to explain this aspect of MMT could equally be used to support arguments that government deficits \"crowd out\" private sector investment.<ref name=murphy>{{Cite news |author=Robert P. Murphy |title=The Upside-Down World of MMT |publisher=[[Ludwig von Mises Institute]] |date=2011-05-09 |url=https://mises.org/daily/5260/The-UpsideDown-World-of-MMT |accessdate=2011-07-17|author-link=Robert P. Murphy }}</ref>\n\nThe [[chartalist]] view of money itself, and the MMT emphasis on the importance of taxes in driving money, is also a source of criticism.<ref name=\"Lavoie\"/> Economist [[Eladio Febrero]] argues that modern money draws its value from its ability to cancel (private) bank debt, particularly as [[legal tender]], rather than to pay government taxes.<ref>{{Citation |author=Eladio Febrero |title=Three difficulties with Neo-Chartalism |journal=Jornadas de Econom\u00eda Cr\u00edtica |volume=11 |date=2008-03-27 |url=http://www.ucm.es/info/ec/ecocri/cas/Febrero.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{cols|colwidth=21em}}\n*[[Deficit spending]]\n*[[Demand for money]]\n*[[Functional finance]]\n*[[History of macroeconomic thought]]\n*[[History of money]]\n*[[Job guarantee]]\n*[[NAIBER]]\n*[[People's Quantitative Easing]]\n*[[Credit theory of money]]\n*[[Quantity theory of money]]\n*[[Fiscal theory of the price level]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=Macroeconomics\n|first=Bill\n|last=Mitchell\n|date=February 2019\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pPmGDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]\n|isbn=9781137610676\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|url=http://www.moslereconomics.com/mandatory-readings/what-is-money/\n|title=What is Money?\n|authorlink=Alfred Mitchell-Innes\n|first=A. Mitchell\n|last=Innes\n|year=1913\n|journal=The Banking Law Journal\n|access-date=28 January 2009\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022220006/http://moslereconomics.com/mandatory-readings/what-is-money/\n|archive-date=22 October 2016\n|url-status=dead\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|authorlink=Abba P. Lerner\n|first=Abba P.\n|last=Lerner\n|year=1947\n|title=Money as a Creature of the State\n|journal=[[American Economic Review]]\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=The Neo-Chartalist Approach to Money\n|last=Wray\n|first=L. Randall\n|authorlink=L. Randall Wray\n|issue=Working Paper No. 10\n|year=2000\n|url=http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp/wp10.html\n|publisher=[[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City|UMKC]] Center for Full Employment and Price Stability\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=The Endogenous Money Approach\n|last=Wray\n|first=L. Randall\n|issue=Working Paper No. 17\n|year=2001\n|url=http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp/wp17.html\n|publisher=[[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City|UMKC]] Center for Full Employment and Price Stability\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=Three difficulties with neo-chartalism\n|last=Febrero\n|first=Eladio\n|url=http://www.ucm.es/info/ec/ecocri/cas/Febrero.pdf\n|journal=Journal of Post Keynesian Economics\n|volume=31\n|year=2009\n|issue=3\n|pages=523\u2013541\n|doi=10.2753/PKE0160-3477310308\n|citeseerx=10.1.1.564.8770\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|first=Bill\n|last=Mitchell\n|authorlink=Bill Mitchell (economist)\n|year=2009\n|title=The fundamental principles of modern monetary economics\n|postscript=in [http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/2009/09/27/it%e2%80%99s-hard-being-a-bear-part-sixgood-alternative-theory/ \"It\u2019s Hard Being a Bear (Part Six)? Good Alternative Theory?\"] ([http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/HardBeingABear06AlternativeTheory.pdf PDF])\n}}. Introduction to modern (as of 2009) Chartalism.\n* {{Citation\n|title=Money\n|last=Wray\n|first=L. Randall\n|issue=Working Paper No. 647\n|date=December 2010\n|url=http://www.levyinstitute.org/files/download.php?file=wp_647.pdf&pubid=1344\n|publisher=[[Levy Economics Institute|Levy Economics Institute of Bard College]]\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=ME/MMT: The Currency as a Public Monopoly\n|authorlink=Warren Mosler\n|first=Warren\n|last=Mosler\n|date=March 2014\n|url=http://www00.unibg.it/dati/corsi/910003/64338-Warren%20Mosler%20Bergamo%20paper%20March%2010.pdf\n|publisher=[[University of Bergamo]]\n}}\n* {{cite book \n|last=Wray \n|first=L. Randall \n|title=Modern Money Theory : A Primer on Macroeconomics for Sovereign Monetary Systems \n|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan \n|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire New York, NY \n|year=2015 \n|isbn=978-1-137-53990-8 \n|pages=137\u2013141, 199\u2013206}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=Macroeconomics\n|first=Bill\n|last=Mitchell\n|date=February 2019\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pPmGDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]\n|isbn=9781137610676\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q496647|c=Category:Modern Monetary Theory|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|species=no|q=no}}\n* [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_778.pdf Modern Money Theory 101: A Reply to Critics\u2014Working Paper No. 778] (\u00c9ric Tymoigne and L. Randall Wray; Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, P.O. Box 5000, Annandale-on-Hudson, NY 12504-5000, www.levyinstitute.org)\n* [http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/ Bill Mitchell's blog] (Chartalism is denoted as \"Modern Monetary Theory\", there)\n* [http://www.moslereconomics.com Warren Mosler's blog]\n* [http://neweconomicperspectives.org/ New Economic Perspectives website]\n* [http://econviz.org/macroeconomic-balance-sheet-visualizer/ Macroeconomic Balance Sheet Visualizer], visualizing and understanding important concepts in macroeconomics\n* [https://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/working_papers/working_papers_251-300/WP279.pdf Modern Monetary Theory: A Debate] (Brett Fiebiger critiques and Scott Fullwiler, Stephanie Kelton, L. Randall Wray respond; Political Economy Research Institute, Amherst, MA)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161023062110/https://www.creditwritedowns.com/2011/03/on-modern-money.html Credit Writedowns], news and opinion site, from the MMT perspective\n* [http://larspsyll.wordpress.com/2012/06/30/knut-wicksell-and-the-origins-of-modern-monetary-theory/ Knut Wicksell and origins of modern monetary theory-Lars P\u00e5lsson Syll]\n* [https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1_41kF_QUgyvePUqlPObIRKw3SYNMzqrvAmNPbxeOpHo/ Evolution of Selected Economic Schools], a simplified diagram\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180106205925/http://www.modernmoneynetwork.org/?q=about%2Forganization Modern Money Network]\n\n{{Microeconomics}}\n{{Macroeconomics}}\n{{Economics}}\n\n[[Category:Modern monetary theory| ]]\n[[Category:Schools of economic thought]]\n[[Category:Post-Keynesian economics]]\n[[Category:Macroeconomic theories]]\n[[Category:Ideologies of capitalism]]\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|also known as neo-chartalism, a macroeconomic theory}}\n{{Macroeconomics sidebar}}\n[[File:M2 Money Stock.png|thumb|260px|M2 Money Stock (United States)|alt=]]\n[[File:Money supply growth vs inflation rates.png|260px|thumb|Money supply growth vs inflation rates]]\n[[File:M2 as a % of GDP.png|thumb|260px|M2 as a % of GDP]]\n\n'''Modern Monetary Theory''' or '''Modern Money Theory''' ('''MMT''') or '''Modern Monetary Theory and Practice''' ('''MMTP''') is a [[macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] theory and practice that describes the practical uses of [[fiat currency]] in a public monopoly from the issuing authority, normally the government's [[central bank]]. Effects on employment are used as evidence that a currency monopolist is overly restricting the supply of the financial assets needed to pay taxes and satisfy savings desires.<ref>Warren Mosler, [http://www00.unibg.it/dati/corsi/910003/64338-Warren%20Mosler%20Bergamo%20paper%20March%2010.pdf ME/MMT: The Currency as a Public Monopoly]</ref><ref name=\"MMTreply\">\u00c9ric Tymoigne and L. Randall Wray, [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_778.pdf \"Modern Money Theory 101: A Reply to Critics,\"] Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, Working Paper No. 778 (November 2013).</ref> MMT is an evolution of [[chartalism]] and is sometimes referred to as '''neo-chartalism'''. Its macroeconomic policy prescriptions have been described as being a version of [[Abba Lerner]]'s theory of [[functional finance]].\n\nMMT advocates argue that the government could use [[fiscal policy]] to achieve [[NAIBER|full employment]], [[Money creation|creating new money]] to fund government purchases. According to advocates, the primary risk once the economy reaches full employment is inflation, which can be addressed by raising and gathering taxes and issuing bonds to reduce money and the [[velocity of money]] in the system.<ref name=\"Wray2015\">{{cite book | last=Wray | first=L. Randall | title=Modern Money Theory : A Primer on Macroeconomics for Sovereign Monetary Systems | publisher=Palgrave Macmillan | location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire New York, NY | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-137-53990-8 | pages=137\u2013141, 199\u2013206}}</ref> MMT is debated, with active dialogues <ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\" /> about its theoretical usefulness, the clear useful real world practical applications and implications, together with the varying effectiveness of its targetted use and varying challenges of its policy prescriptions.\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 325\n | footer = \n | image1 = Money supply increases.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = U.S. money supply change from a year ago ($ Billions).\n | image2 = M2 money supply increases.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Percent change in U.S. [[Monetary policy of the United States|money supply]] vs. year ago.  Money supply increases about 6% per year. \n }}\n\nMMT's main tenets are that a government that issues its own fiat money:\n# Can pay for goods, services, and financial assets without a need to collect money in the form of taxes or debt issuance in advance of such purchases; \n# Cannot be forced to default on debt denominated in its own currency;\n#Is only limited in its money creation and purchases by [[inflation]], which accelerates once the real resources (labour, capital and natural resources) of the economy are utilized at [[NAIBER|full employment]];\n# Can control [[demand-pull inflation]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2019/03/01/1551434402000/An-MMT-response-on-what-causes-inflation/ |title=An MMT response on what causes inflation |last1=Fullwiler |first1=Scott |last2=Grey |first2=Rohan |last3=Tankus |first3=Nathan |publisher=The Financial Times Ltd |date=1 March 2019 |website=FT Alphaville |access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref> by taxation and bond issuance, which remove excess money from circulation (although the political will to do so may not always exist);\n# Does not need to compete with the private sector for scarce savings by issuing bonds.\n\nThese tenets challenge the [[mainstream economics]] view that government spending is funded by taxes and debt issuance.<ref name=\"Kelton1\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-03-01/paul-krugman-s-four-questions-about-mmt? Bloomberg-Stephanie Kelton-Paul Krugman Asked Me About Modern Monetary Theory-1 March 2019]</ref><ref name=\"Kelton2\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-03-04/krugman-s-macroeconomics-is-no-match-for-mmt? Bloomberg-Stephanie Kelton-The Clock Runs Down on Mainstream Keynesianism-4 March 2019]</ref><ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-03-21/modern-monetary-theory-beginner-s-guide Bloomberg-Coy, Dmitrieva & Boesler-A Beginner's Guide to MMT-21 March 2019]</ref> The first four MMT tenets do not conflict with mainstream economics understanding of how money creation and inflation works. For example, as former Fed Chair [[Alan Greenspan]] said, \"The United States can pay any debt it has because we can always print money to do that. So there is zero probability of default.\"<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/44051683 No Chance of Default, US Can Print Money: Greenspan CNBC-No Chance of Default, US Can Print Money: Greenspan-7 August 2011]</ref> However, MMT economists disagree with mainstream economics about the fifth tenet, on the impact of government deficits on interest rates.<ref name=\"Bell2000\" /><ref name=\"Sharpe2013\">Sharpe, Timothy P. (2013) \"A Modern Money Perspective On Financial Crowding Out\", Review of Political Economy, 25:4, 586-606</ref><ref name=\"policydebate1\" /><ref name=\"Fullwiler2016\">Fullwiler, Scott T. (2016) \"The Debt Ratio and Sustainable Macroeconomic Policy\", World Economic Review 7:12-42</ref><ref name=Lavoie />\n\nA 2019 survey of leading economists by the [[University of Chicago Booth School of Business|University of Chicago Booth]]'s [[Initiative on Global Markets]] showed a unanimous rejection of assertions that the survey attributes to modern monetary theory.\n\n==History==\nMMT synthesizes ideas from the ''State Theory of Money'' of [[Georg Friedrich Knapp]] (also known as [[Chartalism]]) and ''Credit Theory of Money'' of [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]], the ''[[functional finance]]'' proposals of [[Abba Lerner]], [[Hyman Minsky]]'s views on the ''banking system''<ref name=\"Minsky, Hyman 2008\">Minsky, Hyman: ''Stabilizing an Unstable Economy'', McGraw-Hill, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-07-159299-4}}</ref> and [[Wynne Godley]]'s ''[[Sectoral balances]]'' approach.<ref name=\"policydebate1\">{{citation|first1=Scott |last1= Fullwiler| first2=Stephanie |last2= Kelton | first3=L. Randall | last3= Wray |contribution = Modern Money Theory : A Response to Critics|title= Working Paper Series: Modern Monetary Theory - A Debate| pages=17\u201326|publisher = [[Political Economy Research Institute]] |location=Amherst, MA |number = 279 | date = January 2012 | accessdate= 7 May 2015 | url= http://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/working_papers/working_papers_251-300/WP279.pdf }}</ref>\n\n[[Georg Friedrich Knapp|Knapp]], writing in 1905, argued that \"money is a creature of law\" rather than a [[commodity money|commodity]].<ref name=\"George Friedrich Knapp 1924\">{{Citation|title=Staatilche Theorie des Geldes|author=Knapp, George Friedrich|year=1905|publisher= Verlag von Duncker & Humblot}}</ref> Knapp contrasted his state theory of money with the [[Gold Standard]] view of \"[[metallism]]\", where the value of a unit of currency depends on the quantity of precious metal it contains or for which it may be exchanged. He argued that the state can create pure paper money and make it exchangeable by recognizing it as [[legal tender]], with the criterion for the money of a state being \"that which is accepted at the public pay offices\".<ref name=\"George Friedrich Knapp 1924\" />\n\nThe prevailing view of money was that it had evolved from systems of [[barter]] to become a [[medium of exchange]] because it represented a durable [[commodity money|commodity]] which had some [[use value]],<ref>Karl Marx, Capital I, Chapter 1, two paragraphs starting \"The utility of a thing makes it a use value.\" http://www.efm.bris.ac.uk/het/marx/cap1/chap01 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923234227/http://www.efm.bris.ac.uk/het/marx/cap1/chap01 |date=23 September 2015 }} accessed 18 May 2009.</ref> but proponents of MMT such as Randall Wray and Mathew Forstater argue that more general statements appearing to support a [[Chartalism|chartalist]] view of tax-driven paper money appear in the earlier writings of many classical economists,<ref name=\"wray2000\" /> including [[Adam Smith]], [[Jean-Baptiste Say]], [[J.S. Mill]], [[Karl Marx]], and [[William Stanley Jevons]].<ref name=forstater>{{citation | title=Tax-Driven Money: Additional Evidence from the History of Thought, Economic History, and Economic Policy | author=Forstater, Mathew |year=2004 |url=http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp-pdf/WP35-Forstater.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]], writing in 1914, argued that money exists not as a [[medium of exchange]] but as a [[standard of deferred payment]], with government money being debt the government may reclaim through taxation.<ref name=\"Innes\">{{cite journal | author=Mitchell-Innes, Alfred |title=The Credit Theory of Money |journal= The Banking Law Journal | year=1914 |volume=31 |url=https://www.community-exchange.org/docs/The%20Credit%20Theoriy%20of%20Money.htm}}</ref> Innes argued:\n{{Quotation|Whenever a tax is imposed, each taxpayer becomes responsible for the redemption of a small part of the debt which the government has contracted by its issues of money, whether coins, certificates, notes, drafts on the treasury, or by whatever name this money is called. He has to acquire his portion of the debt from some holder of a coin or certificate or other form of government money, and present it to the Treasury in liquidation of his legal debt. He has to redeem or cancel that portion of the debt...The redemption of government debt by taxation is the basic law of coinage and of any issue of government \u2018money\u2019 in whatever form.|Alfred Mitchell-Innes|The Credit Theory of Money|The Banking Law Journal|}}\n\nKnapp and \"chartalism\" are referenced by [[John Maynard Keynes]] in the opening pages of his 1930 ''[[A Treatise on Money|Treatise on Money]]''<ref>Keynes, John Maynard: ''A Treatise on Money'', 1930, pp. 4, 6</ref> and appear to have influenced [[Keynesian]] ideas on the role of the state in the economy.<ref name=\"wray2000\">{{Citation |title=The Neo-Chartalist Approach to Money |last=Wray |first=L. Randall |issue=Working Paper No. 10 |year=2000 |url= http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp/wp10.html |publisher=[[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City|UMKC]] Center for Full Employment and Price Stability}}</ref>\n\nBy 1947, when Abba Lerner wrote his article ''Money as a Creature of the State'', economists had largely abandoned the idea that the value of money was closely linked to gold.<ref name=Lerner /> Lerner argued that responsibility for avoiding inflation and depressions lay with the state because of its ability to create or tax away money.<ref name=\"Lerner\">{{cite journal|last=Lerner|first=Abba P.|date=May 1947|title=Money as a Creature of the State|url=|journal=The American Economic Review|volume=37|pages=|via=|number=2}}</ref>\n\nEconomists [[Warren Mosler]], [[L. Randall Wray]], [[Stephanie Kelton]],<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Bill Mitchell (economist)|Bill Mitchell]] and [[Pavlina R. Tcherneva]] are largely responsible for reviving the idea of chartalism as an explanation of [[money creation]]; Wray refers to this revived formulation as ''Neo-Chartalism''.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/node/21542174 The Economist, 31 December 2011, \"Marginal revolutionaries\"] neo-chartalism, sometimes called \"Modern Monetary Theory\"</ref>\n\nBill Mitchell, Professor of Economics and Director of the Centre of Full Employment and Equity or [[Centre of Full Employment and Equity|CofFEE]],\nat the [[University of Newcastle, Australia|University of Newcastle]], [[New South Wales]], refers to an increasing related theoretical work as ''{{visible anchor|Modern Monetary Theory}}''.\n\nPavlina R. Tcherneva has developed the first mathematical framework for MMT<ref>{{cite web|url=https://modernmoneynetwork.org/sites/default/files/biblio/Pavlina_2007.pdf|title=Monopoly Money: The State as a Price Setter |author=Tcherneva, Pavlina R. |website=www.modernmoneynetwork.org |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> and has largely focused on developing the idea of the [[Job Guarantee]].\n\nScott Fullwiler has added detailed technical analysis of the banking and monetary systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=444041 |title=Author Page for Scott T. Fullwiler :: SSRN |website=Papers.ssrn.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-28}}</ref>\n\nRodger Malcolm Mitchell's book ''Free Money''<ref>Mitchell, Rodger Malcolm: ''Free Money \u2013 Plan for Prosperity'', PGM International, Inc., paperback 2005, {{ISBN|978-0-9658323-1-1}}</ref> (1996) describes in layman's terms the essence of chartalism.\n\nSome contemporary proponents, such as Wray, place MMT within [[post-Keynesian economics]], while MMT has been proposed as an alternative or complementary theory to [[monetary circuit theory]], both being forms of [[endogenous money]], i.e. money created within the economy, as by government deficit spending or bank lending, rather than from outside, as by gold. In the complementary view, MMT explains the \"vertical\" (government-to-private and vice versa) interactions, while circuit theory is a model of the \"horizontal\" (private-to-private) interactions.<ref name=def1013>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=381 \"Deficit Spending 101 \u2013 Part 3\"]  Bill Mitchell, 2 March 2009</ref><ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=5199 \"In the spirit of debate...my reply\"] Bill Mitchell, 28 September 2009</ref>\n\n[[Hyman Minsky]] seemed to favor a chartalist approach to understanding money creation in his ''Stabilizing an Unstable Economy'',<ref name=\"Minsky, Hyman 2008\"/> while [[Basil Moore (economist)|Basil Moore]], in his book ''Horizontalists and Verticalists'',<ref>Moore, Basil J.: ''Horizontalists and Verticalists: The Macroeconomics of Credit Money'', Cambridge University Press, 1988, {{ISBN|978-0-521-35079-2}}</ref> lists the differences between bank money and state money.\n\n[[James K. Galbraith]] supports MMT and wrote the foreword for Mosler's book ''Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds of Economic Policy'' in 2010.<ref>Mosler, Warren: ''Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds of Economic Policy'', Valance Co., 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-692-00959-8}}; also available in [http://www.moslereconomics.com/wp-content/powerpoints/7DIF2.doc .DOC]</ref>\n\nSteven Hail of the [[University of Adelaide]] is another well known MMT economist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qBpm5sVmGYc|title=Steven Hail's presentation on modern money and the \"budget emergency\"|last=|first=|date=2014-08-31|website=|publisher=|access-date=|author=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"abc.jg\">{{Cite web |title=The case for offering every Australian a government-funded job |last=Wood |first=Patrick |publisher=ABC News |date= 20 November 2018|access-date=14 May 2019 |url= https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-21/stephanie-kelton-on-modern-monetary-theory-and-a-job-guarantee/10510758 |quote=University of Adelaide economics lecturer Steven Hail is an expert in MMT and regularly speaks on the topic. }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, the first academic textbook based on the theory was published.<ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\"/>\n\n==Theoretical approach==\nIn sovereign financial systems, banks can create money but these \"horizontal\" transactions do not increase net [[financial assets]] as assets are offset by liabilities. According to MMT adherents, \"The balance sheet of the government does not include any domestic monetary instrument on its asset side; it owns no money. All monetary instruments issued by the government are on its liability side and are created and destroyed with spending and taxing/bond offerings, respectively.\"<ref name=\"MMTreply\"/> In MMT, \"vertical money\" enters circulation through [[government spending]]. [[Taxation]] and its [[legal tender]] enable power to discharge debt and establish the [[fiat money]] as currency, giving it value by creating demand for it in the form of a private tax obligation that must be met. In addition, fines, fees and licenses create demand for the currency. This can be a currency issued by the domestic government, or a foreign currency.<ref>[[Warren Mosler|Mosler, Warren]]. [http://moslereconomics.com/mandatory-readings/soft-currency-economics/ \"Soft Currency Economics\"], January 1994</ref><ref>[[Pavlina R. Tcherneva|Tcherneva Pavlina R.]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=TPa22fYkDSsC&pg=PA69 \"Chartalism and the tax-driven approach to money\"], in ''A Handbook of Alternative Monetary Economics'', edited by Philip Arestis & Malcolm C. Sawyer, Elgar Publishing (2007), {{ISBN|978-1-84376-915-6}}</ref> An ongoing tax obligation, in concert with private confidence and acceptance of the currency, maintains its value. Because the government can issue its own currency at will, MMT maintains that the level of taxation relative to government spending (the government's [[deficit spending]] or [[budget surplus]]) is in reality a policy tool that regulates inflation and [[unemployment]], and not a means of funding the government's activities by itself. The approach of MMT typically reverses theories of governmental [[austerity]]. The policy implications of the two are likewise typically opposed.\n\n===Vertical transactions===\n[[File:Sectoral balances circuit diagram.png|thumb|400px|Illustration of the [[saving identity]] with the three sectors, the computation of the surplus or deficit balances for each and the flows between them<ref name=\"CBO_Aug2018\">[https://www.cbo.gov/publication/54318 CBO-An Update to the Economic Outlook: 2018 to 2028-Retrieved November 12, 2018]</ref>]]\n{{Further|Sectoral balances}}\nMMT labels any transactions between the government, or public sector, and the non-government, or private sector, as a \"vertical transaction\". The government sector is considered to include the treasury and the [[central bank]]. The non-government sector includes domestic and foreign private individuals and firms (including the private banking system) and foreign buyers and sellers of the currency.<ref name=\"Mitchelletal2019\">Mitchell, William; Wray, L. Randall; Watts, Martin: ''Macroeconomics'', Red Globe Press, 2019, {{ISBN|978-1137610669}}. pp.84-87</ref>\n\n==Interaction between government and the banking sector==\nMMT is based on an account of the \"operational realities\" of interactions between the government and its central bank, and the commercial banking sector, with proponents like Scott Fullwiler arguing that understanding reserve accounting is critical to understanding monetary policy options.<ref name=FullPrimer>Scott T. Fullwiler, [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1723198 \"Modern Monetary Theory\u2014A Primer on the Operational Realities of the Monetary System,\"] Wartburg College; Bard College - The Levy Economics Institute (30 August 2010).</ref>\n\nA sovereign government typically has an operating account with the country's central bank. From this account, the government can spend and also receive taxes and other inflows.<ref name=def1013 /> Each commercial bank also has an account with the central bank, by means of which it manages its reserves (that is, money for clearing and settling interbank transactions).<ref name=\"Meulendyke\">Meulendyke, A.M. (1998) U.S. Monetary Policy and Financial Markets. New York: Federal\nReserve Bank of New York.</ref>\n\nWhen the government spends money, the treasury debits its operating account at the central bank, and deposits this money into private bank accounts (and hence into the commercial banking system). This money adds to the total deposits in the commercial bank sector. Taxation works exactly in reverse; private bank accounts are debited, and hence deposits in the commercial banking sector fall. In the United States, a portion of tax receipts are deposited in the treasury operating account, and a portion in commercial banks' designated [[Treasury Tax and Loan]] accounts.<ref name=\"Bell2000\" /><ref name=\"NYFed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkfed.org/aboutthefed/fedpoint/fed21.html|title=Treasury and Tax and Loan Program|accessdate=16 June 2016|publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of New York|date=April 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Government bonds and interest rate maintenance===\n[[File:U.S. Treasuries.png|thumb|right|350px|The Federal Reserve raising the [[Federal Funds Rate]] above [[United States Treasury security|U.S. Treasury]] interest rates creates an [[inverted yield curve]], which is a predictor of recessions.]]\nVirtually all central banks set an interest rate target, and conduct [[open market operations]] to ensure base interest rates remain at that target level. According to MMT, the issuing of government bonds is best understood as an operation to ''offset'' government spending rather than a requirement to ''finance'' it.<ref name=\"FullPrimer\" />\n\nIn most countries, commercial banks\u2019 reserve accounts with the central bank must have a positive balance at the end of every day; in some countries, the amount is specifically set as a proportion of the liabilities a bank has (i.e. its customer deposits). This is known as a [[reserve requirement]].\nAt the end of every day, a commercial bank will have to examine the status of their reserve accounts. Those that are in deficit have the option of borrowing the required funds from the central bank, where they may be charged a ''lending rate'' (sometimes known as a ''[[discount window|discount rate]]'') on the amount they borrow. On the other hand, the banks that have excess reserves can simply leave them with the central bank and earn a ''support rate'' from the central bank. Some countries, such as [[Economy of Japan|Japan]], have a support rate of zero.<ref name=\"bis.org\">[http://www.bis.org/publ/work292.pdf?noframes=1 \"Unconventional monetary policies: an appraisal\"] by Claudio Borio and Piti Disyatat, Bank for International Settlements, November 2009</ref>\n\nBanks with more reserves than they need will be willing to lend to banks with a reserve shortage on the [[interbank lending market]]. The surplus banks will want to earn a higher rate than the support rate that the central bank pays on reserves; whereas the deficit banks will want to pay a lower interest rate than the discount rate the central bank charges for borrowing. Thus they will lend to each other until each bank has reached their reserve requirement. In a balanced system, where there are just enough total reserves for all the banks to meet requirements, the short-term interbank lending rate will be in between the support rate and the discount rate.<ref name=\"bis.org\"/>\n\nUnder an MMT framework where government spending injects new reserves into the commercial banking system, and taxes withdraw them from the banking system,<ref name=\"Bell2000\" /> government activity would have an instant effect on interbank lending. If on a particular day, the government spends more than it taxes, reserves have been added to the banking system (see [[#Vertical transactions|vertical transactions]]). This will typically lead to a system-wide surplus of reserves, with competition between banks seeking to lend their excess reserves forcing the short-term interest rate down to the support rate (or alternately, to zero if a support rate is not in place). At this point banks will simply keep their reserve surplus with their central bank and earn the support rate.<ref name=\"Fullwiler2005\">Fullwiler, Scott T. (2005) \"Paying Interest on Reserve Balances: It\u2019s More Significant Than You Think\" (Working Paper No. 38), Wartburg College and the UMKC Center for Full Employment and Price Stability</ref>\n\nThe alternate case is where the government receives more taxes on a particular day than it spends. In this case, there may be a system-wide deficit of reserves. As a result, surplus funds will be in demand on the interbank market, and thus the short-term interest rate will rise towards the discount rate. Thus, if the central bank wants to maintain a target interest rate somewhere between the support rate and the discount rate, it must manage the liquidity in the system to ensure that the correct amount of reserves is on hand in the banking system.<ref name=\"Bell2000\">Bell, Stephanie, (2000), \"Do Taxes and Bonds Finance Government Spending?\", Journal of Economic Issues, 34, issue 3, p. 603-620</ref>\n\nCentral banks manage this by buying and selling government bonds on the open market. On a day where there are excess reserves in the banking system, the central bank sells bonds and therefore removes reserves from the banking system, as private individuals pay for the bonds. On a day where there are not enough reserves in the system, the central bank buys government bonds from the private sector, and therefore adds reserves to the banking system.\n\nIt is important to note that the central bank buys bonds by simply creating money \u2014 it is not financed in any way.<ref name=\"Bell287\">Bell, Stephanie (1999), \"Functional Finance: What, Why, and How?\" (Working Paper No. 287), UMKC Center for Full Employment and Price Stability</ref> It is a net injection of reserves into the banking system. If a central bank is to maintain a target interest rate, then it must necessarily buy and sell government bonds on the open market in order to maintain the correct amount of reserves in the system.<ref name=\"Fullwiler2007\">Fullwiler, Scott T. (2007) \"Interest Rates and Fiscal Sustainability\", Journal of Economic Issues, 41:4, 1003-1042</ref>\n\n==Horizontal transactions==\n{{Further|Monetary circuit theory}}\nMMT economists describe any transactions within the private sector as \"horizontal\" transactions, including the expansion of the [[broad money]] supply through the extension of credit by banks.\n\nMMT economists regard the concept of the [[money multiplier]], where a bank is completely constrained in lending through the deposits it holds and its capital requirement, as misleading.<ref name=\"Wray1990\">Wray, L Randall: ''Money and Credit in Capitalist Economies: The Endogenous Money Approach'', Edward Elgar Publishing, 1990 {{ISBN|1-85278-356-7}} pp.149,179</ref><ref name=\"Lavoie2006\">Lavoie, Marc: ''Introduction to Post-Keynesian Economics'', Palgrave MacMillan, 2006 {{ISBN|9780230626300}} pp.60-73</ref> Rather than being a practical limitation on lending, the cost of borrowing funds from the interbank market (or the central bank) represents a ''profitability consideration'' when the private bank lends in excess of its reserve and/or capital requirements (see [[#Interaction between government and the banking sector|interaction between government and the banking sector]]).\n\nAccording to MMT, bank credit should be regarded as a \"leverage\" of the [[monetary base]] and should not be regarded as increasing the net financial assets held by an economy: only the government or central bank is able to issue high-powered money with no corresponding liability.<ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=1623 \"Money multiplier and other myths\"] Bill Mitchell, 21 April 2009</ref> Stephanie Kelton argues that bank money is generally accepted in settlement of debt and taxes because of state guarantees, but that state-issued high-powered money sits atop a \"hierarchy of money\".<ref name=bell>{{citation|first=Stephanie (Bell)| last=Kelton|year=2001|title=The Role of the State and the Hierarchy of Money|journal=[[Cambridge Journal of Economics]]| number=25|pages=149\u2013163|url=http://cas.umkc.edu/economics/people/facultyPages/wray/courses/Econ601%202012/readings/Bell%20The%20Role%20of%20the%20State%20and%20the%20Hierarchy%20of%20Money.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Foreign sector==\n===Imports and exports===\n\nMMT proponents such as [[Warren Mosler]] argue that trade deficits need not be unsustainable and are beneficial to the standard of living in the short run.<ref name=\"Mosler\">{{cite book|last=Mosler|first=Warren|title=Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds|year=2010|publisher=Valance|isbn=978-0-692-00959-8|pages=60\u201362|url=http://moslereconomics.com/wp-content/powerpoints/7DIF.pdf}}</ref> Imports are an economic benefit to the importing nation because they provide the nation with real goods it can consume, that it otherwise would not have had. Exports, on the other hand, are an economic cost to the exporting nation because it is losing real goods that it could have consumed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=10389 \"Do current account deficits matter?\"] Bill Mitchell, 22 June 2010</ref> Currency transferred to foreign ownership, however, represents a future claim over goods of that nation.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nCheap imports may also cause the failure of local firms providing similar goods at higher prices, and hence unemployment but MMT commentators label that consideration as a subjective value-based one, rather than an economic-based one: it is up to a nation to decide whether it values the benefit of cheaper imports more than it values employment in a particular industry.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Similarly a nation overly dependent on imports may face a supply shock if the exchange rate drops significantly, though central banks can and do trade on the FX markets to avoid sharp shocks to the exchange rate.<ref>[http://www.rba.gov.au/statistics/tables/xls/a04hist.xls Foreign Exchange Transactions and Holdings of Official Reserve Assets], Reserve Bank of Australia</ref>\n\n===Foreign sector and government===\nMMT argues that as long as there is a demand for the issuer's currency, whether the bond holder is foreign or not, governments can never be insolvent when the debt obligations are in their own currency; this is because the government is not constrained in creating its own fiat currency (although the bond holder may affect the exchange rate by converting to local currency).<ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=10554 \"Modern monetary theory and inflation \u2013 Part 1\"] Bill Mitchell, 7 July 2010</ref>\n\nMMT does agree with mainstream economics, that debt denominated in a foreign currency certainly is a fiscal risk to governments, since the indebted government cannot create foreign currency. In this case the only way the government can sustainably repay its foreign debt is to ensure that its currency is continually in high demand by foreigners over the period that it wishes to repay the debt \u2013 an exchange rate collapse would potentially multiply the debt many times over asymptotically, making it impossible to repay. In that case, the government can default, or attempt to shift to an export-led strategy or raise interest rates to attract foreign investment in the currency. Either one has a negative effect on the economy.<ref>[http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=11854 \"There is no financial crisis so deep that cannot be dealt with by public spending \u2013 still!\"] Bill Mitchell, 11 October 2010</ref>\n\n==Policy implications==\n{{Further|NAIBER}}\n\nEconomist [[Stephanie Kelton]] explained several policy claims made by MMT in March 2019:\n*Under MMT, [[fiscal policy]] (i.e., government taxing and spending decisions) is the primary means of achieving full employment, establishing the budget deficit at the level necessary to reach that goal. In mainstream economics, [[monetary policy]] (i.e., central bank adjustment of interest rates and its balance sheet) is the primary mechanism, assuming there is some interest rate low enough to achieve full employment. Kelton claims that cutting interest rates is ineffective in a slump, because businesses expecting weak profits and few customers will not invest at even very low interest rates.\n*Government interest expenses are proportional to interest rates, so raising rates is a form of stimulus (it increases the budget deficit and injects money into the private sector, other things equal), while cutting rates is a form of austerity.\n*Achieving full employment can be administered via a federally funded [[job guarantee]], which acts as an [[automatic stabilizer]]. When private sector jobs are plentiful, the government spending on guaranteed jobs is lower, and vice versa.\n*Under MMT, expansionary fiscal policy (i.e., money creation to fund purchases) can increase bank reserves, which can lower interest rates. In mainstream economics, expansionary fiscal policy (i.e., debt issuance and spending) can result in higher interest rates, crowding out economic activity.<ref name=\"Kelton1\"/><ref name=\"Kelton2\"/>\n\nEconomist [[John T. Harvey]] explained several of the premises of MMT and their policy implications in March 2019:\n*The private sector treats labor as a cost to be minimized, so it cannot be expected to achieve full employment without government creating jobs as well, such as through a job guarantee.\n*The public sector's deficit is the private sector's surplus and vice-versa, by accounting identity, a reason why private sector debt increased during the Clinton-era budget surpluses.\n*Idle resources (mainly labor) can be activated by money creation. Not acting to do so is immoral.\n*Demand can be insensitive to interest rate changes, so a key mainstream assumption, that lower interest rates lead to higher demand, is questionable.\n*When the economy is below full employment, there is a \"free lunch\" in creating money to fund government expenditure to achieve full employment. Unemployment is a burden; full employment is not.\n*Creating money alone does not cause inflation; spending it when the economy is at or above full employment can.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/johntharvey/2019/03/05/mmt-sense-or-nonsense/#37c9928b5852 Forbes-John T. Harvey-MMT: Sense or Nonsense?-5 March 2019]</ref>\n\nMMT claims that the word \"borrowing\" is a misnomer when it comes to a sovereign government's fiscal operations, because what the government is doing is accepting back its own [[IOU]]s, and nobody can borrow back their own debt instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4J0j5VwnD7I |title=Q:Why does government issue bonds? Randall Wray: Sovereign government really can't borrow, because what it is doing is accepting back its own IOUs. If you have given your IOU to your neighbour because you borrowed some sugar, could you borrow it back? No, you can't borrow back your own IOUs.|website=Youtube.com|accessdate=2016-07-28}}</ref> Sovereign government goes into debt by issuing its own liabilities that are financial wealth to the private sector. \"Private debt is debt, but government debt is ''financial wealth'' to the private sector.\"<ref>Yeva Nersisyan & L. Randall Wray, [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_603.pdf \"Does Excessive Sovereign Debt Really Hurt Growth? A Critique of ''This Time Is Different'', by Reinhart and Rogoff,\"] Levy Economics Institute (June 2010), p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn this theory, sovereign government is not ''financially'' constrained in its ability to spend; it is argued that the government can afford to buy anything that is for sale in currency that it issues (there may be political constraints, like a [[debt ceiling]] law). The only constraint is that excessive spending by any sector of the economy (whether households, firms, or public) could cause inflationary pressures.\n\nMMT economists advocate a government-funded [[job guarantee]] scheme to eliminate [[involuntary unemployment]]. Proponents argue that this can be consistent with [[price stability]] as it targets unemployment directly rather than attempting to increase private sector job creation indirectly through a much larger economic stimulus, and maintains a \"buffer stock\" of labor that can readily switch to the private sector when jobs become available. A job guarantee program could also be considered an [[automatic stabilizer]] to the economy, expanding when private sector activity cools down and shrinking in size when private sector activity heats up.<ref name=\"elrJobGuarantee\">L. Randal Wray, [http://neweconomicperspectives.org/2009/08/job-guarantee.html \"Job Guarantee,\"] ''New Economic Perspectives'' (23 August 2009).</ref>\n\n==Comparison of MMT with mainstream Keynesian economics==\nMMT can be compared and contrasted with mainstream Keynesian economics in a variety of ways:<ref name=\"MMT_Beginners_Guide\"/><ref name=\"Kelton1\"/><ref name=\"Kelton2\"/> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Topic\n! Mainstream Keynesian\n! MMT\n|-\n| Funding government spending\n| Advocates taxation and issuing bonds (debt) as preferred methods for funding government spending.\n| Emphasizes that taxation and debt issuance are not required to fund spending.\n|-\n| Purpose of taxation\n| Fund government spending and address inequality.\n| Primarily to drive demand for the currency. Secondary uses of taxation include addressing inflation, addressing income inequality, and discouraging bad behaviour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://neweconomicperspectives.org/2014/05/taxes-mmt-approach.html |title=WHAT ARE TAXES FOR? THE MMT APPROACH |last=Wray |first=L. Randall }}</ref>\n|-\n| Achieving full employment\n| Main strategy uses [[monetary policy]]; Fed has \"dual mandate\" of maximum employment and stable prices, but these goals are not always compatible. For example, much higher interest rates used to reduce inflation also caused high unemployment in the early 1980s.<ref name=\"Dual_Mandate1\"/>\n| Main strategy uses [[fiscal policy]]; running a budget deficit large enough to achieve full employment through a [[job guarantee]].\n|-\n| Inflation control\n| Driven by monetary policy; Fed sets interest rates consistent with a stable price level, sometimes setting a [[Inflation targeting#United States|target inflation rate]].<ref name=\"Dual_Mandate1\"/>\n| Driven by fiscal policy; government increases taxes or issues bonds to remove money from private sector. A job guarantee also provides a [[NAIBER]], which acts as an inflation control mechanism.\n|-\n| Setting interest rates\n| Managed by Fed to achieve \"dual mandate\" of maximum employment and stable prices.<ref name=\"Dual_Mandate1\">[https://www.richmondfed.org/publications/research/economic_brief/2011/eb_11-12 \"FRB Richmond-Aaron Steelman-The Federal Reserves Dual Mandate: The Evolution of an Idea\"-December 2011]</ref>\n| Emphasizes that an interest rate target is not a potent policy.<ref name=\"Kelton1\"/> The government may choose to maintain a [[zero interest-rate policy]] by not issuing public debt at all.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=31715 |title=There is no need to issue public debt |last=Mitchell |first=William |date=3 September 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Budget deficit impact on interest rates\n| At full employment, higher budget deficit can [[crowding out (economics)|crowd-out]] investment.\n| Deficit spending can drive down interest rates, encouraging investment and thus \"crowding-in\" economic activity.<ref name=\"Kelton_3\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-02-21/modern-monetary-theory-is-not-a-recipe-for-doom Bloomberg-Stephanie Kelton-Modern Monetary Theory Is Not a Recipe for Doom-21 February 2019]</ref>\n|-\n| Automatic stabilizers\n| Primary stabilizers are [[Unemployment benefits#United States|unemployment insurance]] and [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program|food stamps]], which increase budget deficits in a downturn.\n| In addition to the other stabilizers, a job guarantee would increase deficits in a downturn.<ref name=\"elrJobGuarantee\" />\n|}\n\n==Criticisms==\n\nA 2019 survey of leading economists by the [[University of Chicago Booth School of Business|University of Chicago Booth]]'s [[Initiative on Global Markets]] showed a unanimous rejection of assertions that the survey attributes to modern monetary theory: \"Countries that borrow in their own currency should not worry about government deficits because they can always create money to finance their debt\" and \"Countries that borrow in their own currency can finance as much real government spending as they want by creating money\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/modern-monetary-theory|title=Modern Monetary Theory|last=|first=|date=2019|website=www.igmchicago.org|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/economist-survey-alexandria-ocasio-cortez-modern-monetary-theory-2019-3|title=A new survey shows that zero top US economists agreed with the basic principles of an economic theory supported by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez|last=Bryan|first=Bob|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-03-15|date=14 March 2019}}</ref> Directly responding to the survey, MMT economist William K. Black said \"MMT scholars do not make or support either claim.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://neweconomicperspectives.org/2019/03/the-day-orthodox-economists-lost-their-minds-and-integrity.html |title=The Day Orthodox Economists Lost Their Minds and Integrity |date=2019 |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> Multiple MMT academics regard the attribution of these claims as a smear.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=41823 |title=Fake surveys and Groupthink in the economics profession |date=2019-03-19 |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe [[post-Keynesian]] economist [[Thomas Palley]] argues that MMT is largely a restatement of elementary [[Keynesian economics]], but prone to \"over-simplistic analysis\" and understating the risks of its policy implications.<ref name=\"palley\">{{citation |author=Thomas Palley |title=Money, fiscal policy, and interest rates: A critique of Modern Monetary Theory |url=http://www.thomaspalley.com/docs/articles/macro_theory/mmt.pdf}}</ref> Palley denies the MMT claim that standard Keynesian analysis does not fully capture the accounting identities and financial restraints on a government that can issue its own money. He argues that these insights are well captured by standard Keynesian stock-flow consistent [[IS-LM model]]s, and have been well understood by Keynesian economists for decades. He also criticizes MMT for \"assum[ing] away the problem of fiscal\u2013monetary conflict\"<ref name=\"palley2\"/> \u2014 that is, that the governmental body that creates the spending budget (e.g. Congress) may refuse to cooperate with the governmental body that controls the money supply (e.g. the [[Federal Reserve]]). In Palley's view the policies proposed by MMT proponents would cause serious financial instability in an open economy with [[Floating exchange rate|flexible exchange rates]], while using [[Fixed exchange-rate system|fixed exchange rates]] would restore hard financial constraints on the government and \"undermines MMT\u2019s main claim about sovereign money freeing governments from standard market disciplines and financial constraints\". He also argues that MMT lacks a plausible [[Monetary inflation|theory of inflation]], particularly in the context of full employment in the [[employer of last resort]] policy first proposed by [[Hyman Minsky]] and advocated by [[Bill Mitchell (economist)|Bill Mitchell]] and other MMT theorists; of a lack of appreciation of the financial instability that could be caused by permanently zero interest rates; and of overstating the importance of government created money. Palley concludes that MMT provides no new insights about monetary theory, while making unsubstantiated claims about macroeconomic policy, and that MMT has only received attention recently due to it being a \"policy polemic for depressed times.\"<ref name=\"palley2\">{{cite web |author=Thomas Palley |title=Modern money theory (MMT): the emperor still has no clothes |date=February 2014 |url=http://www.thomaspalley.com/docs/articles/macro_theory/mmt_response_to_wray.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Marc Lavoie]] argues that whilst the neochartalist argument is \"essentially correct\", many of its counter-intuitive claims depend on a \"confusing\" and \"fictitious\" consolidation of government and central banking operations<ref name=Lavoie>{{cite web |author=Marc Lavoie |title=The monetary and fiscal nexus of neo-chartalism |url=http://www.boeckler.de/pdf/v_2011_10_27_lavoie.pdf}}</ref> \u2014 again what Palley calls \"the problem of fiscal\u2013monetary conflict.\"<ref name=\"palley2\"/>\n\n[[New Keynesian economics|New Keynesian]] economist and Nobel laureate [[Paul Krugman]] argues that MMT goes too far in its support for government budget deficits and ignores the inflationary implications of maintaining budget deficits when the economy is growing.<ref name=krugman>{{cite news |author=Paul Krugman |title=Deficits and the Printing Press (Somewhat Wonkish) |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date =2011-03-25 |url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/25/deficits-and-the-printing-press-somewhat-wonkish/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326161843/http://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/25/deficits-and-the-printing-press-somewhat-wonkish/ |archivedate=2011-03-26 |url-status=live |accessdate=2011-07-17|author-link=Paul Krugman }}</ref> Krugman described MMT devotees as engaging in \"[[Calvin and Hobbes#Calvinball|calvinball]]\" \u2014 a game from the comic strip ''[[Calvin and Hobbes]]'' in which the players change the rules at whim.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2019/03/12/is-modern-monetary-theory-nutty-or-essential |title=Is modern monetary theory nutty or essential? |date=2019-03-12 |work=The Economist |access-date=2019-03-12 |issn=0013-0613}}</ref> [[Austrian School]] economist [[Robert P. Murphy]] states that MMT is \"dead wrong\" and that \"the MMT worldview doesn't live up to its promises.\"<ref name=\"murphy\"/> He observes that MMT's claim that cutting government deficits erodes private saving is true \"only for the portion of private saving that is not invested\" and argues that the national accounting identities used to explain this aspect of MMT could equally be used to support arguments that government deficits \"crowd out\" private sector investment.<ref name=murphy>{{Cite news |author=Robert P. Murphy |title=The Upside-Down World of MMT |publisher=[[Ludwig von Mises Institute]] |date=2011-05-09 |url=https://mises.org/daily/5260/The-UpsideDown-World-of-MMT |accessdate=2011-07-17|author-link=Robert P. Murphy }}</ref>\n\nThe [[chartalist]] view of money itself, and the MMT emphasis on the importance of taxes in driving money, is also a source of criticism.<ref name=\"Lavoie\"/> Economist [[Eladio Febrero]] argues that modern money draws its value from its ability to cancel (private) bank debt, particularly as [[legal tender]], rather than to pay government taxes.<ref>{{Citation |author=Eladio Febrero |title=Three difficulties with Neo-Chartalism |journal=Jornadas de Econom\u00eda Cr\u00edtica |volume=11 |date=2008-03-27 |url=http://www.ucm.es/info/ec/ecocri/cas/Febrero.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{cols|colwidth=21em}}\n*[[Deficit spending]]\n*[[Demand for money]]\n*[[Functional finance]]\n*[[History of macroeconomic thought]]\n*[[History of money]]\n*[[Job guarantee]]\n*[[NAIBER]]\n*[[People's Quantitative Easing]]\n*[[Credit theory of money]]\n*[[Quantity theory of money]]\n*[[Fiscal theory of the price level]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=Macroeconomics\n|first=Bill\n|last=Mitchell\n|date=February 2019\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pPmGDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]\n|isbn=9781137610676\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|url=http://www.moslereconomics.com/mandatory-readings/what-is-money/\n|title=What is Money?\n|authorlink=Alfred Mitchell-Innes\n|first=A. Mitchell\n|last=Innes\n|year=1913\n|journal=The Banking Law Journal\n|access-date=28 January 2009\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022220006/http://moslereconomics.com/mandatory-readings/what-is-money/\n|archive-date=22 October 2016\n|url-status=dead\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|authorlink=Abba P. Lerner\n|first=Abba P.\n|last=Lerner\n|year=1947\n|title=Money as a Creature of the State\n|journal=[[American Economic Review]]\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=The Neo-Chartalist Approach to Money\n|last=Wray\n|first=L. Randall\n|authorlink=L. Randall Wray\n|issue=Working Paper No. 10\n|year=2000\n|url=http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp/wp10.html\n|publisher=[[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City|UMKC]] Center for Full Employment and Price Stability\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=The Endogenous Money Approach\n|last=Wray\n|first=L. Randall\n|issue=Working Paper No. 17\n|year=2001\n|url=http://www.cfeps.org/pubs/wp/wp17.html\n|publisher=[[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City|UMKC]] Center for Full Employment and Price Stability\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=Three difficulties with neo-chartalism\n|last=Febrero\n|first=Eladio\n|url=http://www.ucm.es/info/ec/ecocri/cas/Febrero.pdf\n|journal=Journal of Post Keynesian Economics\n|volume=31\n|year=2009\n|issue=3\n|pages=523\u2013541\n|doi=10.2753/PKE0160-3477310308\n|citeseerx=10.1.1.564.8770\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|first=Bill\n|last=Mitchell\n|authorlink=Bill Mitchell (economist)\n|year=2009\n|title=The fundamental principles of modern monetary economics\n|postscript=in [http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/2009/09/27/it%e2%80%99s-hard-being-a-bear-part-sixgood-alternative-theory/ \"It\u2019s Hard Being a Bear (Part Six)? Good Alternative Theory?\"] ([http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/HardBeingABear06AlternativeTheory.pdf PDF])\n}}. Introduction to modern (as of 2009) Chartalism.\n* {{Citation\n|title=Money\n|last=Wray\n|first=L. Randall\n|issue=Working Paper No. 647\n|date=December 2010\n|url=http://www.levyinstitute.org/files/download.php?file=wp_647.pdf&pubid=1344\n|publisher=[[Levy Economics Institute|Levy Economics Institute of Bard College]]\n}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=ME/MMT: The Currency as a Public Monopoly\n|authorlink=Warren Mosler\n|first=Warren\n|last=Mosler\n|date=March 2014\n|url=http://www00.unibg.it/dati/corsi/910003/64338-Warren%20Mosler%20Bergamo%20paper%20March%2010.pdf\n|publisher=[[University of Bergamo]]\n}}\n* {{cite book \n|last=Wray \n|first=L. Randall \n|title=Modern Money Theory : A Primer on Macroeconomics for Sovereign Monetary Systems \n|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan \n|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire New York, NY \n|year=2015 \n|isbn=978-1-137-53990-8 \n|pages=137\u2013141, 199\u2013206}}\n* {{Citation\n|title=Macroeconomics\n|first=Bill\n|last=Mitchell\n|date=February 2019\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pPmGDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]\n|isbn=9781137610676\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q496647|c=Category:Modern Monetary Theory|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|species=no|q=no}}\n* [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_778.pdf Modern Money Theory 101: A Reply to Critics\u2014Working Paper No. 778] (\u00c9ric Tymoigne and L. Randall Wray; Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, P.O. Box 5000, Annandale-on-Hudson, NY 12504-5000, www.levyinstitute.org)\n* [http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/ Bill Mitchell's blog] (Chartalism is denoted as \"Modern Monetary Theory\", there)\n* [http://www.moslereconomics.com Warren Mosler's blog]\n* [http://neweconomicperspectives.org/ New Economic Perspectives website]\n* [http://econviz.org/macroeconomic-balance-sheet-visualizer/ Macroeconomic Balance Sheet Visualizer], visualizing and understanding important concepts in macroeconomics\n* [https://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/working_papers/working_papers_251-300/WP279.pdf Modern Monetary Theory: A Debate] (Brett Fiebiger critiques and Scott Fullwiler, Stephanie Kelton, L. Randall Wray respond; Political Economy Research Institute, Amherst, MA)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161023062110/https://www.creditwritedowns.com/2011/03/on-modern-money.html Credit Writedowns], news and opinion site, from the MMT perspective\n* [http://larspsyll.wordpress.com/2012/06/30/knut-wicksell-and-the-origins-of-modern-monetary-theory/ Knut Wicksell and origins of modern monetary theory-Lars P\u00e5lsson Syll]\n* [https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1_41kF_QUgyvePUqlPObIRKw3SYNMzqrvAmNPbxeOpHo/ Evolution of Selected Economic Schools], a simplified diagram\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180106205925/http://www.modernmoneynetwork.org/?q=about%2Forganization Modern Money Network]\n\n{{Microeconomics}}\n{{Macroeconomics}}\n{{Economics}}\n\n[[Category:Modern monetary theory| ]]\n[[Category:Schools of economic thought]]\n[[Category:Post-Keynesian economics]]\n[[Category:Macroeconomic theories]]\n[[Category:Ideologies of capitalism]]\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "repair template damage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_Monetary_Theory"}
{"title_page": "Ludger Lemieux", "text_new": "{{Infobox architect\n|name= Ludger Lemieux\n|image= [[File:Ludger Lemieux.jpg]]\n|caption= \n|nationality= [[Canadians|Canadian]] \n|birth_date= February 9, 1872\n|birth_place=  [[Farnham, Quebec]] [[Canada]] \n|death_date=October 27, 1953\n|death_place= [[Montreal]] [[Quebec]], Canada\n|alma_mater= [[McGill University]]  \n|practice= 1897-1953\n|significant_buildings=[[Saint-Henri Fire Station]], [[Atwater Market]] \n|significant_projects=\n|significant_design=\n|awards= \n}}\n\n[[File:AtwaterMarket.jpg|thumb|upright|Atwater Market.]]\n[[File:Caserne St-Henri.jpg|thumb|upright|Saint-Henri fire hall.]]\n'''Ludger Lemieux''' (February 9, 1872&ndash;October 27, 1953) was a [[Quebec]] [[architect]] who designed a number of notable [[Art deco]] structures in [[Montreal]]'s [[Saint-Henri]] district.<ref name=\"CCA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cca.qc.ca/en/exhibitions/39-trois-architectes-trois-quartiers-ludger-lemieux-st-henri|title=Trois architectes, trois quartiers : Ludger Lemieux (St. Henri), Ernest Cormier (Cit\u00e9 universitaire), Ernest Isbell Barott (St. Antoine)|publisher=[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]|accessdate=2009-11-16|location=Montreal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716102941/http://www.cca.qc.ca/en/exhibitions/39-trois-architectes-trois-quartiers-ludger-lemieux-st-henri|archive-date=2011-07-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> While he often worked in partnership with [[Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff]], his best-known structure, the [[Atwater Market]], was designed not with MacDuff but with his son Paul M. Lemieux.<ref name=\"dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org\">http://www.dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/node/2010</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Farnham, Quebec]] to parents  Mo\u00efse Lemieux and Marie Melanie Serre.<ref>https://www.ancestry.com/genealogy/records/ludger-lemieux_105641845</ref> He studied at [[McGill University]]<ref name=\"Insites\">{{cite web|url=http://www.memorablemontreal.com/print/en/batiments_menu.php?quartier=13&batiment=234&section=Array&menu=batisseurs|title=Montreal Insites|publisher=Heritage Montreal|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> before his architectural practice after 1897.\n\nHe was married to [[Marie Louise Pare]] and had six children including Paul Marie Lemieux.\n\nHe worked with Macduff from 1897 to 1918, then on his own until 1931 when his son Paul M. Lemieux (1902-1968) joined to work with father.<ref name=\"dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org\"/>\n\n==Projects==\n\nLemieux, his partner as well as his sons were involved in 500 projects from the late 19th Century to mid 20th Century:<ref>http://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/379526</ref>\n\n* [[Atwater Market]] (1938 avenue Atwater) 1933\n* \u00c9glise Saint-Vincent-Ferrier (301 rue Jarry est) 1931<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise-Saint-Vincent-Ferrier.php</ref>\n*  [[Saint-Henri Fire Station]] (Caserne de Pompiers 23 - 521-523 Place Saint-Henri) 1930 <ref name=\"Insites\"/><ref name=\"Images\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Caserne-23.php|title=Saint-Henri Fire Station|work=Images Montreal|accessdate=2009-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"UQAM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.milieuxdefavorises.org/serie_B/23.html|title=Station de pompiers N o 23|work=Footnotes|publisher=Centre de formation sur l\u2019enseignement en milieux d\u00e9favoris\u00e9s|language=French|accessdate=2009-11-16|location=Montreal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727083318/http://www.milieuxdefavorises.org/serie_B/23.html|archive-date=2011-07-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* \u00c9glise Saint-Vincent-de-Paul (2310 rue Sainte-Catherine est) 1928<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Saint-Vincent-de-Paul_cat.php</ref>\n* \u00c9glise Saint-Zotique (4565 rue Notre-Dame ouest) 1927 - with [[Ren\u00e9 Charbonneau (architect)|Ren\u00e9 Charbonneau]], the architect of the [[Outremont Theatre]].\n* 831 avenue Rockland 1914<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Le-381-Rockland.php</ref> with Joseph-Rom\u00e9o Gadbois et Jean-Julien Perrault\n* \u00c9glise Sainte-\u00c9lisabeth-de-Portugale (670 rue de Courcelle) 1912<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise_Sainte-elisabeth-de-Portugale.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff; replaced in 1957-1958<ref>http://www.patrimoine-culturel.gouv.qc.ca/rpcq/detail.do?methode=consulter&id=170345&type=bien#.Wacu9LpFzIU</ref> and now demolished\n* Wilder Store (282-288 rue Sainte-Catherine ouest) 1912 <ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/image.php?id=2609</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Maison Camille Legault (557 rue Cote-Sainte-Catherine) 1912<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Maison_Camille_Legault.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Grovers Building (Tooke Brothers Limited factory) (640-644 rue de Courcelle) 1907-1912<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/image.php?id=2621</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Workman Building 1907\n* \u00c9glise Sainte-Ir\u00e9n\u00e9e (3030 rue de Delisle & avenue Atwater next to Atwater Market) 1904<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise-Saint-Irenee.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* \u00c9glise St. Charles Church (2115 rue Centre) 1899<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise-Saint-Charles.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Maison Albert Holmes (4286 rue de Maisonneuve Boulevard ouest) 1899<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Maison_Alert_Holmes.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Saint-Jeanne-de-Chantal school\n* Bibliotheque Notre Dame (4707 rue de Notre-Dame ouest) 1898 - formerly Caserne de pompiers 24 <ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Bibliotheque_Notre-Dame.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n\n==Other==\n\nLudger is a bar in Saint-Henri named after Lemieux.<ref>https://montrealgazette.com/life/urban-expressions/new-bar-ludger-in-st-henri</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379526/ludger-and-paul-m-lemieux-fonds Ludger and Paul M. Lemieux fonds] at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada.\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemieux, Ludger}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian architects]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architects]]\n[[Category:People from Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:French Quebecers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox architect\n|name= Ludger Lemieux\n|image= [[File:Ludger Lemieux.jpg]]\n|caption= \n|nationality= [[Canadians|Canadian]] \n|birth_date= February 9, 1872\n|birth_place=  [[Farnham, Quebec]] [[Canada]] \n|death_date=October 27, 1953\n|death_place= [[Montreal]] [[Quebec]], Canada\n|alma_mater= [[McGill University]]  \n|practice= 1897-1953\n|significant_buildings=[[Saint-Henri Fire Station]], [[Atwater Market]] \n|significant_projects=\n|significant_design=\n|awards= \n}}\n\n[[File:AtwaterMarket.jpg|thumb|upright|Atwater Market.]]\n[[File:Caserne St-Henri.jpg|thumb|upright|Saint-Henri fire hall.]]\n'''Ludger Lemieux''' (February 9, 1872&ndash;October 27, 1953) was a [[Quebec]] [[architect]] who designed a number of notable [[Art deco]] structures in [[Montreal]]'s [[Saint-Henri]] district.<ref name=\"CCA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cca.qc.ca/en/exhibitions/39-trois-architectes-trois-quartiers-ludger-lemieux-st-henri|title=Trois architectes, trois quartiers : Ludger Lemieux (St. Henri), Ernest Cormier (Cit\u00e9 universitaire), Ernest Isbell Barott (St. Antoine)|publisher=[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]|accessdate=2009-11-16|location=Montreal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716102941/http://www.cca.qc.ca/en/exhibitions/39-trois-architectes-trois-quartiers-ludger-lemieux-st-henri|archive-date=2011-07-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> While he often worked in partnership with [[Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff]], his best-known structure, the [[Atwater Market]], was designed not with MacDuff but with his son Paul M. Lemieux.<ref name=\"dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org\">http://www.dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/node/2010</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Farnham, Quebec]] to parents  Mo\u00efse Lemieux and Marie Melanie Serre.<ref>https://www.ancestry.com/genealogy/records/ludger-lemieux_105641845</ref> He studied at [[McGill University]]<ref name=\"Insites\">{{cite web|url=http://www.memorablemontreal.com/print/en/batiments_menu.php?quartier=13&batiment=234&section=Array&menu=batisseurs|title=Montreal Insites|publisher=Heritage Montreal|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> before his architectural practice after 1897.\n\nHe was married to [[Marie Louise Pare]] and had six children including Paul Marie Lemieux.\n\nHe worked with Macduff from 1897 to 1918, then on his own until 1931 when his son Paul M. Lemieux (1902-1968) joined to work with father.<ref name=\"dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org\"/>\n\n==Projects==\n\nLemieux, his partner as well as his sons were involved in 500 projects from the late 19th Century to mid 20th Century:<ref>http://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/379526</ref>\n\n* [[Atwater Market]] (1938 avenue Atwater) 1933\n* \u00c9glise Saint-Vincent-Ferrier (301 rue Jarry est) 1931<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise-Saint-Vincent-Ferrier.php</ref>\n*  [[Saint-Henri Fire Station]] (Caserne de Pompiers 23 - 521-523 Place Saint-Henri) 1930 <ref name=\"Insites\"/><ref name=\"Images\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Caserne-23.php|title=Saint-Henri Fire Station|work=Images Montreal|accessdate=2009-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"UQAM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.milieuxdefavorises.org/serie_B/23.html|title=Station de pompiers N o 23|work=Footnotes|publisher=Centre de formation sur l\u2019enseignement en milieux d\u00e9favoris\u00e9s|language=French|accessdate=2009-11-16|location=Montreal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727083318/http://www.milieuxdefavorises.org/serie_B/23.html|archive-date=2011-07-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* \u00c9glise Saint-Vincent-de-Paul (2310 rue Sainte-Catherine est) 1928<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Saint-Vincent-de-Paul_cat.php</ref>\n* \u00c9glise Saint-Zotique (4565 rue Notre-Dame ouest) 1927 - with [[Ren\u00e9 Charbonneau (architect)|Ren\u00e9 Charbonneau]], the architect of the [[Outremont Theatre]].\n* 831 avenue Rockland 1914<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Le-381-Rockland.php</ref> with Joseph-Rom\u00e9o Gadbois et Jean-Julien Perrault\n* \u00c9glise Sainte-\u00c9lisabeth-de-Portugale (670 rue de Courcelle) 1912<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise_Sainte-elisabeth-de-Portugale.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff; replaced in 1957-1958<ref>http://www.patrimoine-culturel.gouv.qc.ca/rpcq/detail.do?methode=consulter&id=170345&type=bien#.Wacu9LpFzIU</ref> and now demolished\n* Wilder Store (282-288 rue Sainte-Catherine ouest) 1912 <ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/image.php?id=2609</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Maison Camille Legault (557 rue Cote-Sainte-Catherine) 1912<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Maison_Camille_Legault.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Grovers Building (Tooke Brothers Limited factory) (640-644 rue de Courcelle) 1907-1912<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/image.php?id=2621</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Workman Building 1907\n* \u00c9glise Sainte-Ir\u00e9n\u00e9e (3030 rue de Delisle & avenue Atwater next to Atwater Market) 1904<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise-Saint-Irenee.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* \u00c9glise St. Charles Church (2115 rue Centre) 1899<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/eglise-Saint-Charles.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Maison Albert Holmes (4286 rue de Maisonneuve Boulevard ouest) 1899<ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Maison_Alert_Holmes.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n* Saint-Jeanne-de-Chantal school\n* Bibliotheque Notre Dame (4707 rue de Notre-Dame ouest) 1898 - formerly Caserne de pompiers 24 <ref>http://www.imtl.org/montreal/building/Bibliotheque_Notre-Dame.php</ref> with Joseph-Honor\u00e9 MacDuff\n\n==Other==\n\nLudger is a bar in Saint-Henri named after Lemieux.<ref>https://montrealgazette.com/life/urban-expressions/new-bar-ludger-in-st-henri</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lemieux, Ludger}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian architects]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architects]]\n[[Category:People from Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:French Quebecers]]\n", "name_user": "Veranam", "label": "safe", "comment": "External links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludger_Lemieux"}
{"title_page": "Paul's Case", "text_new": "{{original research|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox short story <!--See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]]-->\n| name                = Paul's Case\n| author              = [[Willa Cather]]\n| country             = United States\n| language            = English\n| genre               = Fiction\n| publihing_date       = 1905\n| published_in           = ''[[McClure's Magazine]]''\n| english_pub_date    = 1905\n}}\n\"'''Paul's Case\"''' is a short story by [[Willa Cather]]. It was first published in ''[[McClure's Magazine]]'' in 1905 under the title \"Paul's Case: A Study in Temperament\" and was later shortened.<ref>''Willa Cather's Collected Short Fiction'', University of Nebraska Press; revised edition, November 1, 1970, p. 261</ref> It also appeared in a collection of Cather's stories, ''[[The Troll Garden]]'' (1905).  For many years \"Paul's Case\" was the only one of her stories that Cather allowed to be [[anthologized]].<ref>Acocella, Joan. ''Willa Cather and the Politics of Criticism''. Lincoln, NE.: University of Nebraska Press, 2000, p. 27.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[New York City]] was known to be a place that one can escape to. It was the center of fine living and society, and \u201cthe symbol of ultimate glamour and cosmopolitan sophistication at that time.\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rubin|first=Larry|year=1975|title=The Homosexual Motif in Willa Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|url=|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=12|pages=5|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe symbol of the [[New York City|New York]] lifestyle in \"Paul's Case\" is the luxurious [[Waldorf Astoria Hotel]]. The descriptions of New York City contrast the descriptions of Paul's home, [[Pittsburgh]], which he despises.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Summers|first=Claude J.|date=2009-01-01|title=\"A Losing Game in the End\": Aestheticism and Homosexuality in Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|journal=MFS Modern Fiction Studies|volume=36|issue=1|pages=103\u2013119|doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0369|issn=1080-658X}}</ref>\n\nPaul, a [[Pittsburgh]] high school student, is frustrated with his mundane, middle-class life. This frustration mixed with a desire of luxury makes Paul anxious to make a perfect way of living. This causes him to purposely separate himself from everyone else leading to feelings of isolation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sirridge|first1=Marjorie|title=Paul's Case|url=http://medhum.med.nyu.edu/view/1227|website=NYU School of Medicine|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> While his appreciation of the arts is more social and superficial than aesthetic, he dreams of another life in which he would attend concerts and theater. For example, he enjoys a symphony concert not so much for the music, but for the atmosphere: \"the lights danced before his eyes and the concert hall blazed into unimaginable splendor.\" Later on in the story, he steals money from where he works to support a short escapade in [[New York City]]. Once he exhausts his funds and his father catches wind of what has happened, he commits suicide rather than allow his father to take him back to Pittsburgh.\n\nPaul's teachers and father refer to Paul's \"case\", representing him at a distance and as an example of someone to be studied, handled, and managed. The term enables Cather to adopt \"the voice of medical authority\".<ref name=WK>{{cite book|first= Wayne |last= Koestenbaum | title=The Queen's Throat: Opera, Homosexuality and the Mystery of Desire |publisher =Gay Men's Press | date=1994 |pages= 28\u201329|title-link= The Queen's Throat }}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe short story \u201cPaul\u2019s Case\u201d is about a young man who struggles to fit in at home, school and in the world. At the start of the story, Paul is suspended from his high school in Pittsburgh for a week. He meets with his principal and teachers who complain about Paul's \"defiant manner\" in class and the \"physical aversion\" he exhibits toward his teachers. One of Paul's teachers also mentions that Paul's mother died back when he was a child in Colorado, which is later shown to be of importance. He then goes to work at [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh|Carnegie Hall]] in Pittsburgh. Here he works as an usher and can be himself by serving those in his section with grand enthusiasm. He stays for the concert and enjoys the social scene while losing himself in the music. After the concert, Paul follows the soloist and imagines life inside her hotel room. Unfortunately, the audience learns that Paul and his father have a poor relationship. Upon returning home very late one night, Paul enters through the basement to avoid a confrontation with his father. Paul's relationship with his father is one of abuse, so much so that while in the basement, Paul gets nervous that his father will come downstairs with a shotgun and kill him. Paul stays awake all night imagining what would happen if his father mistook him for a burglar and shot him, or if his dad would recognize him in time. Not only does Paul wonder if his father will recognize him in time, but he also entertains the idea of his father possibly regretting not shooting him when he had the chance to do so.   \n\nPaul despises the people on Cordelia street as they serve to remind him of his own lackluster life. Although his father considers him a role model for Paul, Paul is unimpressed by a plodding young man who works for an iron company and is married with four lovely children. While Paul longs to be wealthy, cultivated, and powerful, he lacks the stamina and ambition to attempt to change his condition. Instead, Paul escapes his monotonous life by visiting Charley Edwards, a young actor. Later on, Paul makes it clear to one of his teachers that his job ushering is more important than his schoolwork, causing his father to prevent him from continuing to work as an usher.\n\nPaul takes a train to New York City after stealing over $2000 from his new job at Denny & Carson's to finance a new life. He buys an expensive wardrobe, rents a room at the [[Waldorf-Astoria Hotel]], and walks around the city. He also meets a young boy from [[San Francisco]] who takes him on an all-night tour of the city's lively social scene. His few days of impersonating a rich, privileged young man, brought him more contentment than he had ever known because living a prosperous life is Paul's only hope and dream.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.fju.edu.tw/lctd/asp/works/51/study.htm#03|title=Paul's Case|website=english.fju.edu.tw|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref> However, on the eighth day, after spending most of his money, Paul read from a Pittsburgh newspaper that his theft has been made public. His father has returned the money and is en route to New York City to bring Paul back home to Pittsburgh. Paul then reveals that he had bought a gun on his first day in New York City, and briefly considers shooting himself to avoid returning to his old life in Pittsburgh. Eventually, he decides against it and instead commits suicide by jumping in front of a train. Paul made the ultimate decision of taking his own life because the thought of returning to his old one was too much for him to handle.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burke|first=Gerald T.|date=July 2003|title=The Willa Cather Electronic Archive2003395The Willa Cather Electronic Archive. Lincoln, NE: The Cather Project, University of Nebraska\u2010Lincoln 2001 to date.  Gratis URL: www.unl.edu/Cather/. Last visited May 2003|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1108/09504120310498059|journal=Reference Reviews|volume=17|issue=7|pages=44\u201345|doi=10.1108/09504120310498059|issn=0950-4125}}</ref>\n\n== Symbolism ==\n'''Flowers'''- Flowers, such as a red carnation and violets, appear many times throughout the story. Since Paul sees everything as dull and boring, the flowers represent the desire that he has to find the beauty in life.<ref name=\":1\">Cather, Willa, and Karl Schlenk. ''Paul's case''. Westermann, 1963.</ref>\n\n'''Embroidered hanging done by Paul's mother'''- This is thought to represent Paul's yearning for love in his life since both love and his mother are absent from his life.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n'''Paul's suicide'''- Paul's decision to end his life by jumping in front of a train is thought to represent the impact that commercialization and industrialization have on Paul, who would rather lose himself in theater and music.<ref name=\":1\" /> Paul's choice to get hit by a train as his method of suicide also reflects his relationship with his father. Paul has the opportunity to use a gun to end his life. However, the gun belongs to his father. Paul had always feared his father. His choice to not use the gun shows that Paul doesn't want to give his father any more power over his life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Obertino|first=James|date=May 21, 2012|title='Paul's Case' and Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder|journal=[[The Explicator]]|volume=70|issue=1|pages=49\u201352|doi=10.1080/00144940.2012.663009}}</ref>\n\n'''Snowfall''' - Cather utilizes extensive imagery related to snowfall throughout Paul's case in order to represent the coming of a richer lifestyle. The \"whirling\" motions of said snowfall occur several times; as Paul gazes out of the train window on his way to New York, as well as consistently throughout the time he is actually in the city. It's almost as if we as readers are as much in a fantasy world as Paul is himself. Note that on his way back from New York, he gazes out of the train window to see nothing of the sort besides the snow that has already fallen - A depressing representation that Paul's fantasy has come to an end.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Czernicki |first1=Martha |title=Fantasy and Reality in Willa Cather's PAUL'S CASE |journal=The Explicator |date=2017 |volume=75 |issue=4 |page=242|doi=10.1080/00144940.2017.1379466 }}</ref>\n\n'''Paul's Smile''' - There are several instances where Paul's smile is brought up in the story and a few different interpretations of what his smile symbolizes. When Paul has a meeting with his instructors and the principal, he puts on a smile. The narrator notes that other boys would be more afraid than Paul was and would most likely have given in to an emotional and remorseful response about their disruptive behaviors. Paul's smile in this circumstance displays his cocky attitude and shows that he doesn't care about what the authorities have to say to him.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://englishivbl2b.pbworks.com/w/page/19070348/%22Paul%27s%20Case%22%20--%20Cork%20Terborg,%20Payton%20Laczynski,%20Katie%20Erickson|title=English / \"Paul's Case\" -- Cork Terborg, Payton Laczynski, Katie Erickson|website=englishivbl2b.pbworks.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> A different interpretation of Paul's smile arises from the detail where Paul's drawing master claimed there was, \"something sort of haunted about [his smile],\" which is a detail that is often used to support the idea that Paul's smile refers to him having a disability.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Foreshadowing==\nThe foreshadowing demonstrated in \"Paul's Case\" is seen in the carnations that Paul wears. Immediately, before Paul kills himself, the carnations were \"drooping with the cold...their red glory all over\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cather|first1=Willa|title=Paul's Case|journal=McClure's Magazine|date=May 1905|volume=25|pages=74\u201383|url=https://cather.unl.edu/ss006.html}}</ref> The carnations symbolize Paul, so when the flowers die and are buried in the snow, it is hinting to the reader that Paul is about to die.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul's Case|url=http://iblog.stjschool.org/stories/files/2008/01/Pauls_Case_eNotes.pdf|website=eNotes|publisher=Gale Cengage|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref>{{POV|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Literary criticism and significance==\n\"Paul's Case\" has been called a \"gay suicide\" for multiple reasons, including Paul's lack of a relationship with his father and the absence of a mother figure.<ref>Eric Haralson, ''Henry James and Queer Modernity'', Cambridge University Press, 2003, p. 137</ref>  Many critics have attributed his suicide to the forces of alienation and stigmatization facing a young homosexual man in early 20th-century America.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moore|first=William Thomas|year=2014|title=The Execution of a Homosexual in Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|url=http://knight.as.cornell.edu/publicationsprizes/discoveries/discoveriesspring2014/10.%20Moore.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=103|via=}}</ref> In 1975, Larry Rubin wrote ''The Homosexual Motif'' which includes the reinterpretation of the story since the stigma on sex has eased. He identifies the hints dropped throughout the story that would lead the reader to believe Paul was homosexual.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rubin|first1=Larry|date=March 1, 1975|title=The Homosexual Motif in Willa Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|url=https://search-ebscohost-com.unh-proxy01.newhaven.edu/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=7135831&site=ehost-live&scope=site|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=12|issue=2|page=127|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> Jane Nardin also explores the possibility that Paul's character is gay, and that this is a metaphor for a general feeling of being an outsider or not fitting in with a specific group of people.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nardin|first=Jane|year=2008|title=Homosexual Identities in Willa Cather's 'Paul's Case'|url=|journal=Literature & History|volume=17|issue=2|pages=31\u201346|via=Academic Search Premier|doi=10.7227/LH.17.2.3}}</ref> Author Roger Austen states that Paul might be portrayed as a homosexual character because of the \"depiction of a sensitive young man stifled by the drab ugliness of his environment and places the protagonist in an American literary tradition of \"village sissies.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Summers|first=Claude J.|date=January 1, 2009|title=\"A Losing Game in the End\": Aestheticism and Homosexuality in Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|journal=MFS Modern Fiction Studies|volume=36|issue=1|pages=103\u2013119|doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0369}}</ref>\n\n[[Wayne Koestenbaum]] reads the story as a possible portrait of Willa Cather's \"own desire for aesthetic fulfillment and sexual nonconformity.\"<ref name=\"Koestenbaum 1994 28\u201329\">{{cite book|first= Wayne |last= Koestenbaum | title=The Queen's Throat: Opera, Homosexuality and the Mystery of Desire |publisher =Gay Men's Press | date=1994 |pages= 28\u201329|title-link= The Queen's Throat }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/893531808 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/893530206 cite #7 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> He also identifies the [[literary topos]] of [[Queen (slang)#Opera queen|opera queendom]], commingled here as it often is with a suicidal sense of self-loss.<ref name=\"Koestenbaum 1994 28\u201329\"/> Another critic, Tom Quirk, reads it as an exploration of Cather's belief in the \"irreconcilable opposition\" between art and life.<ref>{{cite book|last=Quirk |first= Tom |title=Bergson and American Culture: The Worlds of Willa Cather and Wallace Stevens |url=https://archive.org/details/bergsonamericanc0000quir |url-access=registration |location= Chapel Hill |publisher= University of North Carolina Press |date= 1990 |page= [https://archive.org/details/bergsonamericanc0000quir/page/109 109]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/893531808 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/893530206 cite #16 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref>\n\nJames Obertino of the [[University of Central Missouri]] and Rob Saari suggest that Paul displays several characteristics that suggest symptoms of [[narcissistic personality disorder]]  according to the ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders|DSM-IV]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saari|first=Rob|date=Summer 1997|title='Paul's Case': A Narcissistic Personality Disorder, 301.81.|url=|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=34|pages=|via=Academic search premier}}</ref> Obertino also suggests that Paul may suffer from [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress disorder]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHayley Wilhelm of the [[University of New Haven]]  suggests the possibility that Paul has [[autism]] due to certain signs and symptoms he displays throughout the story.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last1=Wilhelm|first1=Hayley|title=Signs and Symptoms of Autism in Willa Cather's PAUL'S CASE|journal=The Explicator|date=August 3, 2017|volume=75|issue=3|pages=194\u2013199|doi=10.1080/00144940.2017.1346579}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/893531808 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/893530206 cite #19 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> She claims that Paul's mannerisms and actions show signs that he may have autism, such as his ease with lying, his motor tics (twitching lips, raised eyebrows), and his sensitivity to touch.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn [[Modern Fiction Studies]], writer [[Claude J. Summers]] suggests that Cather, herself being homosexual, chose to depict Paul as being homosexual due to her relationship with author [[Oscar Wilde]].<ref name=\"jstor.org\">{{cite journal |last1=Summers |first1=Claude J. |title=A LOSING GAME IN THE END': AESTHETICISM AND HOMOSEXUALITY IN CATHER'S 'PAUL'S CASE. |journal=Modern Fiction Studies |date=1990 |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages= 103\u2013119 |jstor=26283357 |doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0369 }}</ref> Wilde, an early critic of Cather's work, inspired several aspects of Cather's work on \"Paul's Case\".<ref name=\"jstor.org\"/>\n\n==Adaptations==\nThe story was the basis for a [[chamber opera]] in two acts with music by [[Gregory Spears]] to a libretto by Spears and Kathryn Walat. It premiered in April 2013 at the [[Artisphere]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/skillful-singers-bring-a-short-story-to-life-in-urbanarias-pauls-case/2013/04/22/691a33de-aab8-11e2-b6fd-ba6f5f26d70e_story.html | title=Skillful singers bring a short story to life in UrbanArias ''Paul's Case''| first= Roger |last= Catlin |work=Washington Post |date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> and was then performed for the PROTOTYPE opera festival in New York City, performed at HERE, 145 [[Sixth Avenue (Manhattan)|6th Avenue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://observer.com/2014/01/new-and-improved-in-pauls-case-a-young-opera-festival-yields-its-first-masterpiece/#ixzz2qRUZ7pJ3 |title=New\u2014And Improved: In ''Paul's Case'', a Young Opera Festival Yields Its First Masterpiece |first=James | last=Jorden |author-link =James Jorden |work = [[The New York Observer]] |date=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Paul's Case'' was adapted into a TV movie in 1980 directed by [[Lamont Johnson]], starring [[Eric Roberts]].<ref>{{cite book| last1=Zucker| first1=Carole|title=Figures of Light: Actors and Directors Illuminate the Art of Film Acting| date=1995| publisher= Springer Science+Business Media|pages=181\u20132|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YU72BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181|accessdate=June 22, 2016| isbn=9781489961181}}</ref>\n\n''Paul's Case'' was also released as a book-on-tape by HarperCollins in 1981.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.bookrags.com/studyguide-paulscase/adaptations.html#gsc.tab=0|title=Paul's Case Movies & Media Adaptations {{!}} BookRags.com|website=www.bookrags.com|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, ''Paul's Case'' was released as an [[audiobook]] by [[Caedmon Audio|Caedmon Audio Cassette]] <ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.bookrags.com/studyguide-paulscase/adaptations.html#gsc.tab=0|title=Paul's Case Movies & Media Adaptations|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Literature}}\n*[[1905 in literature]]\n*[[List of suicides in fiction]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource}}\n* [http://cather.unl.edu/ss006.html Full text] at the Willa Cather Archive\n* [http://litmed.med.nyu.edu/Annotation?action=view&annid=1227 \"Paul's Case\" in: ''Literature Annotations'']\n* {{cite journal|last1=Nardin|first1=Jane|title=Homosexual Identities in Willa Cather's 'Paul's Case'|journal=Literature & History|volume=17|issue=2|pages=31\u201346|doi=10.7227/LH.17.2.3|year=2008}}\n\n{{Cather|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1905 short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Willa Cather]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in McClure's]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox short story <!--See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]]-->\n| name                = Paul's Case\n| author              = [[Willa Cather]]\n| country             = United States\n| language            = English\n| genre               = Fiction\n| publihing_date       = 1905\n| published_in           = ''[[McClure's Magazine]]''\n| english_pub_date    = 1905\n}}\n\"'''Paul's Case\"''' is a short story by [[Willa Cather]]. It was first published in ''[[McClure's Magazine]]'' in 1905 under the title \"Paul's Case: A Study in Temperament\" and was later shortened.<ref>''Willa Cather's Collected Short Fiction'', University of Nebraska Press; revised edition, November 1, 1970, p. 261</ref> It also appeared in a collection of Cather's stories, ''[[The Troll Garden]]'' (1905).  For many years \"Paul's Case\" was the only one of her stories that Cather allowed to be [[anthologized]].<ref>Acocella, Joan. ''Willa Cather and the Politics of Criticism''. Lincoln, NE.: University of Nebraska Press, 2000, p. 27.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[New York City]] was known to be a place that one can escape to. It was the center of fine living and society, and \u201cthe symbol of ultimate glamour and cosmopolitan sophistication at that time.\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rubin|first=Larry|year=1975|title=The Homosexual Motif in Willa Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|url=|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=12|pages=5|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe symbol of the [[New York City|New York]] lifestyle in \"Paul's Case\" is the luxurious [[Waldorf Astoria Hotel]]. The descriptions of New York City contrast the descriptions of Paul's home, [[Pittsburgh]], which he despises.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Summers|first=Claude J.|date=2009-01-01|title=\"A Losing Game in the End\": Aestheticism and Homosexuality in Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|journal=MFS Modern Fiction Studies|volume=36|issue=1|pages=103\u2013119|doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0369|issn=1080-658X}}</ref>\n\nPaul, a [[Pittsburgh]] high school student, is frustrated with his mundane, middle-class life. This frustration mixed with a desire of luxury makes Paul anxious to make a perfect way of living. This causes him to purposely separate himself from everyone else leading to feelings of isolation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sirridge|first1=Marjorie|title=Paul's Case|url=http://medhum.med.nyu.edu/view/1227|website=NYU School of Medicine|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> While his appreciation of the arts is more social and superficial than aesthetic, he dreams of another life in which he would attend concerts and theater. For example, he enjoys a symphony concert not so much for the music, but for the atmosphere: \"the lights danced before his eyes and the concert hall blazed into unimaginable splendor.\" Later on in the story, he steals money from where he works to support a short escapade in [[New York City]]. Once he exhausts his funds and his father catches wind of what has happened, he commits suicide rather than allow his father to take him back to Pittsburgh.\n\nPaul's teachers and father refer to Paul's \"case\", representing him at a distance and as an example of someone to be studied, handled, and managed. The term enables Cather to adopt \"the voice of medical authority\".<ref name=WK>{{cite book|first= Wayne |last= Koestenbaum | title=The Queen's Throat: Opera, Homosexuality and the Mystery of Desire |publisher =Gay Men's Press | date=1994 |pages= 28\u201329|title-link= The Queen's Throat }}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe short story \u201cPaul\u2019s Case\u201d is about a young man who struggles to fit in at home, school and in the world. At the start of the story, Paul is suspended from his high school in Pittsburgh for a week. He meets with his principal and teachers who complain about Paul's \"defiant manner\" in class and the \"physical aversion\" he exhibits toward his teachers. One of Paul's teachers also mentions that Paul's mother died back when he was a child in Colorado, which is later shown to be of importance. He then goes to work at [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh|Carnegie Hall]] in Pittsburgh. Here he works as an usher and can be himself by serving those in his section with grand enthusiasm. He stays for the concert and enjoys the social scene while losing himself in the music. After the concert, Paul follows the soloist and imagines life inside her hotel room. Unfortunately, the audience learns that Paul and his father have a poor relationship. Upon returning home very late one night, Paul enters through the basement to avoid a confrontation with his father. Paul's relationship with his father is one of abuse, so much so that while in the basement, Paul gets nervous that his father will come downstairs with a shotgun and kill him. Paul stays awake all night imagining what would happen if his father mistook him for a burglar and shot him, or if his dad would recognize him in time. Not only does Paul wonder if his father will recognize him in time, but he also entertains the idea of his father possibly regretting not shooting him when he had the chance to do so.   \n\nPaul despises the people on Cordelia street as they serve to remind him of his own lackluster life. Although his father considers him a role model for Paul, Paul is unimpressed by a plodding young man who works for an iron company and is married with four lovely children. While Paul longs to be wealthy, cultivated, and powerful, he lacks the stamina and ambition to attempt to change his condition. Instead, Paul escapes his monotonous life by visiting Charley Edwards, a young actor. Later on, Paul makes it clear to one of his teachers that his job ushering is more important than his schoolwork, causing his father to prevent him from continuing to work as an usher.\n\nPaul takes a train to New York City after stealing over $2000 from his new job at Denny & Carson's to finance a new life. He buys an expensive wardrobe, rents a room at the [[Waldorf-Astoria Hotel]], and walks around the city. He also meets a young boy from [[San Francisco]] who takes him on an all-night tour of the city's lively social scene. His few days of impersonating a rich, privileged young man, brought him more contentment than he had ever known because living a prosperous life is Paul's only hope and dream.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.fju.edu.tw/lctd/asp/works/51/study.htm#03|title=Paul's Case|website=english.fju.edu.tw|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref> However, on the eighth day, after spending most of his money, Paul read from a Pittsburgh newspaper that his theft has been made public. His father has returned the money and is en route to New York City to bring Paul back home to Pittsburgh. Paul then reveals that he had bought a gun on his first day in New York City, and briefly considers shooting himself to avoid returning to his old life in Pittsburgh. Eventually, he decides against it and instead commits suicide by jumping in front of a train. Paul made the ultimate decision of taking his own life because the thought of returning to his old one was too much for him to handle.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burke|first=Gerald T.|date=July 2003|title=The Willa Cather Electronic Archive2003395The Willa Cather Electronic Archive. Lincoln, NE: The Cather Project, University of Nebraska\u2010Lincoln 2001 to date.  Gratis URL: www.unl.edu/Cather/. Last visited May 2003|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1108/09504120310498059|journal=Reference Reviews|volume=17|issue=7|pages=44\u201345|doi=10.1108/09504120310498059|issn=0950-4125}}</ref>\n\n== Symbolism ==\n'''Flowers'''- Flowers, such as a red carnation and violets, appear many times throughout the story. Since Paul sees everything as dull and boring, the flowers represent the desire that he has to find the beauty in life.<ref name=\":1\">Cather, Willa, and Karl Schlenk. ''Paul's case''. Westermann, 1963.</ref>\n\n'''Embroidered hanging done by Paul's mother'''- This is thought to represent Paul's yearning for love in his life since both love and his mother are absent from his life.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n'''Paul's suicide'''- Paul's decision to end his life by jumping in front of a train is thought to represent the impact that commercialization and industrialization have on Paul, who would rather lose himself in theater and music.<ref name=\":1\" /> Paul's choice to get hit by a train as his method of suicide also reflects his relationship with his father. Paul has the opportunity to use a gun to end his life. However, the gun belongs to his father. Paul had always feared his father. His choice to not use the gun shows that Paul doesn't want to give his father any more power over his life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Obertino|first=James|date=May 21, 2012|title='Paul's Case' and Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder|journal=[[The Explicator]]|volume=70|issue=1|pages=49\u201352|doi=10.1080/00144940.2012.663009}}</ref>\n\n'''Snowfall''' - Cather utilizes extensive imagery related to snowfall throughout Paul's case in order to represent the coming of a richer lifestyle. The \"whirling\" motions of said snowfall occur several times; as Paul gazes out of the train window on his way to New York, as well as consistently throughout the time he is actually in the city. It's almost as if we as readers are as much in a fantasy world as Paul is himself. Note that on his way back from New York, he gazes out of the train window to see nothing of the sort besides the snow that has already fallen - A depressing representation that Paul's fantasy has come to an end.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Czernicki |first1=Martha |title=Fantasy and Reality in Willa Cather's PAUL'S CASE |journal=The Explicator |date=2017 |volume=75 |issue=4 |page=242|doi=10.1080/00144940.2017.1379466 }}</ref>\n\n'''Paul's Smile''' - There are several instances where Paul's smile is brought up in the story and a few different interpretations of what his smile symbolizes. When Paul has a meeting with his instructors and the principal, he puts on a smile. The narrator notes that other boys would be more afraid than Paul was and would most likely have given in to an emotional and remorseful response about their disruptive behaviors. Paul's smile in this circumstance displays his cocky attitude and shows that he doesn't care about what the authorities have to say to him.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://englishivbl2b.pbworks.com/w/page/19070348/%22Paul%27s%20Case%22%20--%20Cork%20Terborg,%20Payton%20Laczynski,%20Katie%20Erickson|title=English / \"Paul's Case\" -- Cork Terborg, Payton Laczynski, Katie Erickson|website=englishivbl2b.pbworks.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> A different interpretation of Paul's smile arises from the detail where Paul's drawing master claimed there was, \"something sort of haunted about [his smile],\" which is a detail that is often used to support the idea that Paul's smile refers to him having a disability.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Foreshadowing==\nThe foreshadowing demonstrated in \"Paul's Case\" is seen in the carnations that Paul wears. Immediately, before Paul kills himself, the carnations were \"drooping with the cold...their red glory all over\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cather|first1=Willa|title=Paul's Case|journal=McClure's Magazine|date=May 1905|volume=25|pages=74\u201383|url=https://cather.unl.edu/ss006.html}}</ref> The carnations symbolize Paul, so when the flowers die and are buried in the snow, it is hinting to the reader that Paul is about to die.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul's Case|url=http://iblog.stjschool.org/stories/files/2008/01/Pauls_Case_eNotes.pdf|website=eNotes|publisher=Gale Cengage|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref>{{POV|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Literary criticism and significance==\n\"Paul's Case\" has been called a \"gay suicide\" for multiple reasons, including Paul's lack of a relationship with his father and the absence of a mother figure.<ref>Eric Haralson, ''Henry James and Queer Modernity'', Cambridge University Press, 2003, p. 137</ref>  Many critics have attributed his suicide to the forces of alienation and stigmatization facing a young homosexual man in early 20th-century America.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moore|first=William Thomas|year=2014|title=The Execution of a Homosexual in Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|url=http://knight.as.cornell.edu/publicationsprizes/discoveries/discoveriesspring2014/10.%20Moore.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=103|via=}}</ref> In 1975, Larry Rubin wrote ''The Homosexual Motif'' which includes the reinterpretation of the story since the stigma on sex has eased. He identifies the hints dropped throughout the story that would lead the reader to believe Paul was homosexual.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rubin|first1=Larry|date=March 1, 1975|title=The Homosexual Motif in Willa Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|url=https://search-ebscohost-com.unh-proxy01.newhaven.edu/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=7135831&site=ehost-live&scope=site|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=12|issue=2|page=127|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> Jane Nardin also explores the possibility that Paul's character is gay, and that this is a metaphor for a general feeling of being an outsider or not fitting in with a specific group of people.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nardin|first=Jane|year=2008|title=Homosexual Identities in Willa Cather's 'Paul's Case'|url=|journal=Literature & History|volume=17|issue=2|pages=31\u201346|via=Academic Search Premier|doi=10.7227/LH.17.2.3}}</ref> Author Roger Austen states that Paul might be portrayed as a homosexual character because of the \"depiction of a sensitive young man stifled by the drab ugliness of his environment and places the protagonist in an American literary tradition of \"village sissies\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Summers|first=Claude J.|date=January 1, 2009|title=\"A Losing Game in the End\": Aestheticism and Homosexuality in Cather's \"Paul's Case\"|journal=MFS Modern Fiction Studies|volume=36|issue=1|pages=103\u2013119|doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0369}}</ref>\n\n[[Wayne Koestenbaum]] reads the story as a possible portrait of Willa Cather's \"own desire for aesthetic fulfillment and sexual nonconformity.\"<ref name=\"Koestenbaum 1994 28\u201329\">{{cite book|first= Wayne |last= Koestenbaum | title=The Queen's Throat: Opera, Homosexuality and the Mystery of Desire |publisher =Gay Men's Press | date=1994 |pages= 28\u201329|title-link= The Queen's Throat }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/893531808 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/893530206 cite #7 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> He also identifies the [[literary topos]] of [[Queen (slang)#Opera queen|opera queendom]], commingled here as it often is with a suicidal sense of self-loss.<ref name=\"Koestenbaum 1994 28\u201329\"/> Another critic, Tom Quirk, reads it as an exploration of Cather's belief in the \"irreconcilable opposition\" between art and life.<ref>{{cite book|last=Quirk |first= Tom |title=Bergson and American Culture: The Worlds of Willa Cather and Wallace Stevens |url=https://archive.org/details/bergsonamericanc0000quir |url-access=registration |location= Chapel Hill |publisher= University of North Carolina Press |date= 1990 |page= [https://archive.org/details/bergsonamericanc0000quir/page/109 109]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/893531808 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/893530206 cite #16 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref>\n\nJames Obertino of the [[University of Central Missouri]] and Rob Saari suggest that Paul displays several characteristics that suggest symptoms of [[narcissistic personality disorder]]  according to the ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders|DSM-IV]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saari|first=Rob|date=Summer 1997|title='Paul's Case': A Narcissistic Personality Disorder, 301.81.|url=|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=34|pages=|via=Academic search premier}}</ref> Obertino also suggests that Paul may suffer from [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress disorder]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHayley Wilhelm of the [[University of New Haven]]  suggests the possibility that Paul has [[autism]] due to certain signs and symptoms he displays throughout the story.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last1=Wilhelm|first1=Hayley|title=Signs and Symptoms of Autism in Willa Cather's PAUL'S CASE|journal=The Explicator|date=August 3, 2017|volume=75|issue=3|pages=194\u2013199|doi=10.1080/00144940.2017.1346579}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/893531808 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/893530206 cite #19 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> She claims that Paul's mannerisms and actions show signs that he may have autism, such as his ease with lying, his motor tics (twitching lips, raised eyebrows), and his sensitivity to touch.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn [[Modern Fiction Studies]], writer [[Claude J. Summers]] suggests that Cather, herself being homosexual, chose to depict Paul as being homosexual due to her relationship with author [[Oscar Wilde]].<ref name=\"jstor.org\">{{cite journal |last1=Summers |first1=Claude J. |title=A LOSING GAME IN THE END': AESTHETICISM AND HOMOSEXUALITY IN CATHER'S 'PAUL'S CASE. |journal=Modern Fiction Studies |date=1990 |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages= 103\u2013119 |jstor=26283357 |doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0369 }}</ref> Wilde, an early critic of Cather's work, inspired several aspects of Cather's work on \"Paul's Case\".<ref name=\"jstor.org\"/>\n\n==Adaptations==\nThe story was the basis for a [[chamber opera]] in two acts with music by [[Gregory Spears]] to a libretto by Spears and Kathryn Walat. It premiered in April 2013 at the [[Artisphere]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/skillful-singers-bring-a-short-story-to-life-in-urbanarias-pauls-case/2013/04/22/691a33de-aab8-11e2-b6fd-ba6f5f26d70e_story.html | title=Skillful singers bring a short story to life in UrbanArias ''Paul's Case''| first= Roger |last= Catlin |work=Washington Post |date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> and was then performed for the PROTOTYPE opera festival in New York City, performed at HERE, 145 [[Sixth Avenue (Manhattan)|6th Avenue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://observer.com/2014/01/new-and-improved-in-pauls-case-a-young-opera-festival-yields-its-first-masterpiece/#ixzz2qRUZ7pJ3 |title=New\u2014And Improved: In ''Paul's Case'', a Young Opera Festival Yields Its First Masterpiece |first=James | last=Jorden |author-link =James Jorden |work = [[The New York Observer]] |date=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Paul's Case'' was adapted into a TV movie in 1980 directed by [[Lamont Johnson]], starring [[Eric Roberts]].<ref>{{cite book| last1=Zucker| first1=Carole|title=Figures of Light: Actors and Directors Illuminate the Art of Film Acting| date=1995| publisher= Springer Science+Business Media|pages=181\u20132|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YU72BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181|accessdate=June 22, 2016| isbn=9781489961181}}</ref>\n\n''Paul's Case'' was also released as a book-on-tape by HarperCollins in 1981.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.bookrags.com/studyguide-paulscase/adaptations.html#gsc.tab=0|title=Paul's Case Movies & Media Adaptations {{!}} BookRags.com|website=www.bookrags.com|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, ''Paul's Case'' was released as an [[audiobook]] by [[Caedmon Audio|Caedmon Audio Cassette]] <ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.bookrags.com/studyguide-paulscase/adaptations.html#gsc.tab=0|title=Paul's Case Movies & Media Adaptations|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Literature}}\n*[[1905 in literature]]\n*[[List of suicides in fiction]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource}}\n* [http://cather.unl.edu/ss006.html Full text] at the Willa Cather Archive\n* [http://litmed.med.nyu.edu/Annotation?action=view&annid=1227 \"Paul's Case\" in: ''Literature Annotations'']\n* {{cite journal|last1=Nardin|first1=Jane|title=Homosexual Identities in Willa Cather's 'Paul's Case'|journal=Literature & History|volume=17|issue=2|pages=31\u201346|doi=10.7227/LH.17.2.3|year=2008}}\n\n{{Cather|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1905 short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Willa Cather]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in McClure's]]\n", "name_user": "JuliannaS27", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLiterary criticism and significance:punction inside quoation marks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul%27s_Case"}
{"title_page": "Unconditionally", "text_new": "{{See Wiktionary|the Katy Perry song|unconditionally|term}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Unconditionally\n| cover      = Katy Perry - \"Unconditionally\".png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Katy Perry]]\n| album      = [[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]\n| released   = {{start date|2013|10|16}}\n| format     = {{Flat list|\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[Music download|digital download]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     = {{hlist|Luke's in the Boo ([[Malibu, California]])|[[Conway Recording Studios]] ([[Hollywood, California]])|[[Maratone Studios|MXM Studios]] ([[Stockholm, Sweden]])|Secret Garden Studios ([[Montecito, California]])}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"digitalspyrc\"/>\n| length     = 3:48\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = {{Flat list|\n*[[Katy Perry]]\n*[[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]\n*[[Max Martin]]\n*[[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{Flat list|\n*[[Dr. Luke]]\n*Max Martin\n*[[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Who You Love]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Dark Horse (Katy Perry song)|Dark Horse]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|XjwZAa2EjKA|\"Unconditionally\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Unconditionally'''\" is a song by American singer [[Katy Perry]]. It was released as the second single from her fourth studio album ''[[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]'' (2013) on October 16, 2013. Inspiration for the song came primarily from a humanitarian trip to [[Madagascar]] that Perry made in partnership with [[UNICEF]]. Having been surrounded by what she described as [[unconditional love]], she co-wrote it with the song's producers [[Dr. Luke]], [[Max Martin]] and [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]] to reflect that feeling.\n\n\"Unconditionally\" is a [[power ballad]] styled in [[Rock music|rock]], backed against a [[bassline]] and [[percussion]]. Commercially, it peaked within the top ten in Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Italy, Lebanon, and South Africa as well as the top twenty in Australia, Austria, Canada, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia, and the United States.\n\nThe single release was promoted with an [[Instagram]]-based campaign, a lyric video directed by [[Aya Tanimura]] and live performances\u2014one of the latter, at the [[American Music Awards of 2013]], was the center of controversy due to accusations of [[cultural appropriation]] and [[racism]]. Brent Benacorso served as the director for the track's [[music video]], which adopts the theme of love and uses a series of metaphors to enrich its concept.\n\n==Writing and production==\n\"Unconditionally\" was written by Perry alongside its producers [[Dr. Luke]], [[Max Martin]], and [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]. Perry denoted the song as her favorite within the record. She also mentioned that she wrote the song bearing in mind the sentiments she had felt during her [[UNICEF]] humanitarian trip to [[Madagascar]] in April 2013. Such sentiments inspired her to delve into the theme of [[unconditional love]]. She stated that, while on that voyage, Perry and her team would \"go in cruisers up the mountain\" to see newly constructed schools. After observing a group of children, she realized that even without social networking, they felt \"pure\" [[unconditional love]] towards each other.<ref name=Goosebump>{{cite web|last=Montgomery|first=James|title=Katy Perry Reveals Secret Formula For Single Success: 'The Goose Bump Test'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717816/katy-perry-unconditionally-goosebumps.jhtml|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom Media Networks]].|date=November 20, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nInspired by that situation, the song was described by Perry as approaching all forms of [[love]]. \"I love this song because not only can it be a romantic, intimate song\", she expounded. \"But it can be about the type of love that a mother has when she sees her first child, or best friends [...] It is a transcendent love, not just relationship status.\"<ref name=Goosebump /> \"Unconditionally\" was also inspired by the acceptance of one's flaws in a relationship, which Perry believed was relatable to listeners.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MTV UK. Viacom Media Networks.|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=October 24, 2013|title=Katy Perry 'Was Scared To Be Accepted in Relationships'|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/katy-perry/news/katy-perry-was-scared-to-be-accepted-in-relationships}}</ref> It was engineered by Peter Carlsson, Clint Gibbs, Sam Holland, and Michael Illbert, with assistance by Eric Eylands, Rachael Findlen, Justin Fox, and Cory Bice, at the MXM Studios in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]] and Conway Recording Studios in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]. Perry also handled vocal production. Engineering for mix was carried out by John Hanes and final mixing was helmed by Serban Ghenea at the MixStar Studios in [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Prism |titlelink=Prism (Katy Perry album) |others=Katy Perry |year=2013 |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Capitol Records]] |location=United States}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nAt a length of three minutes and forty-eight seconds (3:48), \"Unconditionally\" is a [[pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"digitalspyrc\">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/feature/a525129/playlist-10-tracks-you-need-to-hear/|title=Playlist: 10 tracks you need to hear|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> [[power ballad]], which is styled in the genre of [[rock music|rock]].<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/prism-deluxe-version/id690928033 |title=Prism (Deluxe) \u2013 Katy Perry|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]. [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014 |date=October 22, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Fuse\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fuse.tv/2013/10/katy-perry-unconditionally |title=Listen: Katy Perry Wails on New Single 'Unconditionally' |first=Jeff |last=Benjamin |publisher=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]. [[The Madison Square Garden Company]]. |accessdate=March 8, 2014 |date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref> According to the sheet music published by Kobalt Music Publishing America, Inc. at Musicnotes.com, it is written in the key of [[G major]]. It paces at a moderately fast [[metronome]], at approximately 129 beats per minute, while it is set at a [[Common time|4/4]] [[time signature]], following a chord progression of Em\u2013C\u2013G\u2013D. Perry's vocals in the track span from G{{sub|3}} to E{{sub|5}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally \u2013 By Katy Perry \u2013 Digital Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0126609|publisher=Musicnotes.com.|accessdate=March 8, 2014|date = 2013-10-30}}</ref> The track's \"uncluttered\" instrumentation features woodblock percussion and a \"dramatic\" bass line. Lyrically, Jason Lipshutz from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' deemed it the \"most mature offering\" on ''Prism'', claiming it served as a \"predicate\" to Perry's 2010 single \"[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]\".<ref name=\"BB1\">{{cite news|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=Katy Perry's 'Prism' Album Preview: 10 Things You Need To Know|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5687099/katy-perrys-prism-album-preview-10-things-you-need-to-know|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 6, 2013| accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\nIn September 2013, Perry teased the release of the song as the second single from ''Prism'', without revealing its title or date. However, MTV concluded that such song was \"Unconditionally\", which she discussed during a listening party for the record.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|publisher=MTV. Viacom Media Networks.|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=September 23, 2013|title=What's Katy Perry's Next Single? She Gives Us Some Clues|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1714463/katy-perry-next-single-unconditionally.jhtml|author=Garibaldi, Christina}}</ref> The release was confirmed by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=September 27, 2013|author=Lipshutz, Jason|title=Katy Perry Confirms Next 'PRISM' Single|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5740589/katy-perry-confirms-next-prism-single}}</ref> The track debuted on October 16, 2013<ref name=\"Fuse\" /> and was serviced by [[Capitol Records]] to [[contemporary hit radio]] stations in the United States on October 22.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=October 16, 2013|title=Katy Perry's New 'Prism' Song 'Unconditionally' Gets First Play on Capital FM \u2013 Audio|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/katy-perry/news/unconditionally-first-play/}}</ref><ref name=MainstreamRelease /> The next day, it was sent to Australian radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joy.org.au/music/2013/10/24/new-music-to-weekdays-october-23-2013/|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=October 24, 2013|title=New music to weekdays (October 23, 2013)|publisher=[[Joy 94.9]]}}</ref> A [[CD single]] was released in Germany on November 22\u2014 the same date it was serviced to radios in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|date=November 22, 2013|accessdate=March 9, 2014|publisher=[[Amazon.de]]|title=Unconditionally (2-Track)|url=https://www.amazon.de/Unconditionally-2-Track-Katy-Perry/dp/B00GBJVJ86/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally \u2013 Katy Perry|url=http://www.radioairplay.fm/RadioDate/PublicDetails/41552|accessdate=March 21, 2014|date=November 22, 2013|publisher=RadioAirplay|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204071315/http://www.radioairplay.fm/RadioDate/PublicDetails/41552|archive-date=December 4, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In France, imports of the CD started being sold on December 3.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally [CD Single, Import]|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Unconditionally-Katy-Perry/dp/B00GBJVJ86/|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=December 3, 2013|publisher=[[Amazon.fr]]}}</ref> A remix version of the song by Johnson Somerset was featured on a [[compilation album]] entitled ''Songs for the Philippines'' benefiting those affected by [[Typhoon Haiyan]] in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/beatles-eminem-u2-set-for-philippines-benefit-album-20131126|title=Beatles, Eminem, U2 Set for Philippines Benefit Album|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|first=Kory|last=Grow|date=November 26, 2013|accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Music video#Lyric video|lyric video]] for \"Unconditionally\", directed by [[Aya Tanimura]], was released on October 18, 2013.<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/19/katy-perry-pays-homage-to-dangerous-liaisons-anna-karenina-the-great-gatsby-in-unconditionally-music-video|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 19, 2013|author=Camp, Alexa|title=Katy Perry Pays Homage to Dangerous Liaisons, Anna Karenina, & The Great Gatsby in \"Unconditionally\" Music Video}}</ref><ref name=VEVO>{{cite video|format=Lyric video|title=Unconditionally|url=http://www.vevo.com/watch/katy-perry/unconditionally-lyric-video/USUV71302466|publisher=[[Vevo]]|accessdate=October 18, 2013|people=Tanimura, Aya}}</ref> Set in a [[Monochrome|monochromatic]] pattern, it features actresses Janell Shirtcliff and [[Erika Linder]], who appear naked. As Shirtcliff mouths the song's lyrics, which appear in white and fade slowly, Linder looks \"painful[ly]\" into the camera. They are only shown together by the end of the video, in which scene they look into each other's eyes.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=[[Spin Media]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014|date=October 20, 2013|title=Katy Perry's 'Unconditionally' Lyric Video Could Be A Real Music Video|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/katy-perrys-unconditionally-lyric-video-could-be-real-music-video}}</ref> The video is different in style and approach from the song's official music video, which is retro-styled.<ref name=slant /> Fans were invited to participate in an [[Instagram]]-based campaign, in which they could upload a photo of \"what unconditional love meant to them\", along with their story and location in order for it to appear on a \"''Prism'' map of the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/Digital-Music-Report-2014.pdf|title=Digital Music Report 2014|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nJason Lipshutz from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' deemed the song a \"visceral ballad\" capable of conveying its theme of relationships.<ref name=\"billboardreview\">{{cite web|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 21, 2013|title=Katy Perry's 'PRISM': Track-By-Track Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5763162/katy-perrys-prism-track-by-track-review|author=Lipshutz, Jason}}</ref> John Walker from [[MTV]] praised the track and felt that the song could be written from the perspective of [[Jesus]] and denoted possible Christian undertones lying.<ref name=\"mtvbuzzworthy\">{{cite web|publisher=[[MTV Buzzworthy]]. [[MTV]].|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 22, 2013|author=Walker, John|title=Katy Perry's 'Prism': A Track-By-Track Review..... In Cat GIFs!|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2013/10/22/katy-perry-prism-review-cat-gifs/}}</ref> Kitty Empire of ''[[The Guardian]]'' reckoned the track was \"ungainly\" and \"adverbial\";<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 20, 2013|title=Katy Perry: Prism \u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/20/katy-perry-prism-review|author=Empire, Kitty}}</ref> Helen Brown of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote that its lyrics had \"self-help lingo\", although she remarked that \"Perry's genuine faith in it, along with her wit and sense of fun, powers her through\".<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 17, 2013|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopreviews/10386191/Katy-Perry-Prism-review.html|title=Katy Perry, Prism, review|author=Brown, Helen}}</ref> Kevin Fallon from [[The Daily Beast]] regarded it as adequate for a [[Nicholas Sparks]]-adapted movie, however, he noted that Perry's vocal delivery saved the song of being \"schmaltzy\".<ref name=\"thedailybeast\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Daily Beast]]. [[The Newsweek Daily Beast Company]].|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 22, 2013|last=Fallon|first=Kevin|title='Prism' Review: Katy Perry Perfects the Pop Blockbuster|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/10/22/prism-review-katy-perry-perfects-the-pop-blockbuster.html|newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\n[[HitFix]]'s Melinda Newman graded the track with a 'B'\u2014she felt Perry's voice sounded \"soaring\", and opined that the theme of the song resonated due to Perry's vocal and overall delivery.<ref name=\"hitfix\">{{cite web|publisher=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 21, 2013|title=Katy Perry's 'Prism' reflects her heart and soul set to a beat: Review|url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/katy-perrys-prism-reflects-her-heart-and-soul-set-to-a-beat-review|author=Newman, Melinda}}</ref> Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsday]]'' thought Perry \"ruined\" the track, which she deemed \"decent\", for pronouncing the song title as \"uncondiSHUNally\".<ref name=\"newsday\">{{cite web|work=[[Newsday]]|publisher=[[Cablevision]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 18, 2013|title='Prism' review: Katy Perry is all over the place|author=Gamboa, Glenn|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/prism-review-katy-perry-is-all-over-the-place-1.6280564}}</ref> In his review for ''Prism'', Jon Dolan from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that the song \"set stark revelations to torrential Euro splendor\".<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Wenner Media LLC]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|author=Dolan, Jon|date=October 16, 2013|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/prism-20131016|title=Katy Perry \u2013 Prism}}</ref> Katie Woodard from ''[[Nouse]]'' said the song's \"power ballad approach\" highlights Perry's vocal performance.<ref name=\"nouse\">{{cite web|title=Album Review: Katy Perry \u2013 Prism|url=http://www.nouse.co.uk/2013/10/28/album-review-katy-perry-prism/|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=March 5, 2014|author=Woodard, Katie|work=[[Nouse]]|publisher=[[University of York Students' Union]]}}</ref> Trent Wolfe of [[The Verge]], however, thought the song was part of the group of the ''Prism'' tracks that could \"benefit from a preciously strummed six-string\" instead of \"beats and synths\".<ref name=\"theverge\">{{cite web|publisher=[[The Verge]]. [[Vox Media]].|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 23, 2013|title=Get real: Katy Perry lets go of the teenage dream with 'Prism'|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/23/4877672/get-real-katy-perry-lets-go-of-the-teenage-dream-with-prism|author=Wolfe, Trent}}</ref> [[Digital Spy]]'s Robert Copsey awarded the song with a four out of five points rating, writing that Perry sounded \"effortless\" as compared to her peers.<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|title= Katy Perry 'Unconditionally' single review: Soaring, effortless ballad|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=March 7, 2014|author=Copsey, Robert|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/review/a536157/katy-perry-unconditionally-single-review-soaring-effortless-ballad.html}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Unconditionally\" debuted on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 30.<ref>{{cite web|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|title=Lorde's 'Royals' Crowns Hot 100 For Fifth Week|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5770722/lordes-royals-crowns-hot-100-for-fifth-week|author=Trust, Gary|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=October 30, 2013}}</ref> The next week, it moved five spots up to number 25;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5778259/lordes-royals-rules-hot-100-for-sixth-week|title=Lorde's 'Royals' Rules Hot 100 for Sixth Week|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 6, 2013|author=Trust, Gary|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> it further moved three spots the following week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lorde's 'Royals' Leads Hot 100, Lady Gaga's 'Dope' Debuts at No. 8|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5785931/lordes-royals-leads-hot-100-lady-gagas-dope-debuts-at-no-8|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 13, 2013|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|author=Trust, Gary}}</ref> On its fourth week, the track went to number 16 and one week later it rose one spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5812407/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-swings-back-to-no-1-on-hot-100|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=December 4, 2013|author=Trust, Gary|title=Miley Cyrus' 'Wrecking Ball' Swings Back To No. 1 on Hot 100}}</ref> It later peaked at number 14 on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=December 18, 2013|title=Eminem, Rihanna Remain Atop Hot 100 With 'The Monster'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5840334/eminem-rihanna-remain-atop-hot-100-with-the-monster|author=Trust, Gary|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> In doing so, it was Perry's second single to miss peaking within the top 10 of the chart.<ref name=\"US\" /> On the component charts of ''Billboard'', \"Unconditionally\" enjoyed success\u2014it peaked atop the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]], while reaching number seven on the [[Adult Top 40]] and number 16 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] charts.<ref name=\"dance\" /><ref name=\"adult1\" /><ref name=\"adult2\" /> On the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Pop Songs]] chart, it peaked at number 8.<ref name=pop /> The song has sold more than 1,000,000 copies in the United States; consequently it was certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).{{Certification Cite Ref|relyear=2013|artist=Katy Perry|title=Unconditionally|region=United States|number=1|award=Platinum|certyear=2014}}\n\n\"Unconditionally\" achieved moderate success in Oceanic regions. The song debuted and peaked at 11 on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]]. It then gradually descended down the charts and has spent a total of 13 weeks, marking it as Perry's lowest spanning single in Australia. The song however received a platinum certification by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA), denoting more than 70,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"aria\" /> In New Zealand, the song entered at 26, where it ultimately peaked. Unable to peak higher, the song spent 10 weeks on the singles chart. It subsequently became Perry's lowest spanning and peaking single in New Zealand.<ref name=\"nz\" />\n\nIn Europe, the song performed moderately as well. It reached its highest position of number 5 in Bulgaria while having its lowest peak in Russia, at number 69.<ref name=\"bulgaria\" /><ref name=\"russia\" /> It reached number 16 on the [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]]\u2014where it spent 12 weeks.<ref name=\"austria\" /> On the Italian, German and Czech single charts, it was able to peak within the top 10, at number 6 for the first two and number 8 on the latter.<ref name=\"italy\" /> In Italy, it sold more than 50,000 copies and was certified Platinum by the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] (FIMI).{{Certification Cite Ref|artist=Katy Perry|title=Unconditionally|relyear=2013|certyear=2014|region=Italy|autocat=yes|type=single|award=Platinum}} On the French [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]] chart, it peaked at number 38, and was Perry's third single to miss the top 20 there.<ref name=\"france\" /> In the United Kingdom, \"Unconditionally\" reached number 25; while in Ireland it peaked at number 27.<ref name=\"uk\" /><ref name=\"irish\" /> It fared better in Slovakia where it charted at number 11; in Belgium it reached numbers 49 and 26 in Flanders and Wallonia, respectively.<ref name=\"slovakia\" /><ref name=\"flanders\" /><ref name=\"wallonia\" /> In the Mexican [[Monitor Latino]] and Poland single chart, it managed to peak at 17<ref name=\"mexico\" /><ref name=\"poland\" /> while in Netherlands, it reached number 32. The track charted at numbers 26 and 27 in Spain.<ref name=\"spain\" />\n\n==Music video==\n===Production and release===\nThe [[music video]] for \"Unconditionally\", directed by Brent Bonacorso, was filmed in London during October 2013.<ref name=\"slant\" /><ref name=MusicVideo>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry Confirms She Filmed 'Unconditionally' Music Video in London Last Week|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/katy-perry/news/unconditionally-music-video-london/|publisher=Capital FM|accessdate=October 23, 2013|date=October 23, 2013}}</ref> It was partly inspired by the [[historical drama|costume drama]] films ''[[Dangerous Liaisons]]'' and ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|title=Was Katy Perry Tempted To Write Any 'Screw You' Anthems on Prism?|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717767/katy-perry-prism-songwriting.jhtml|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom Media Networks]].|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> During an interview with [[MTV]], Bonacorso talked about the concept for the video. He stressed that he wanted to match the song's tone with its visual, explaining that he wanted to depict a \"more mysterious, elegant and sophisticated world to live in..... less about a time period and more about creating an impression and a feeling.\" As the song essentially discusses the feeling of love, the video itself sees Perry amidst scenarios which indirectly refer to the power of it.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry's Bed Is on Fire: Her 'Unconditionally' Director Explains Why|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717850/katy-perry-unconditionally-video-director-explains.jhtml|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 21, 2013|author=Vena, Jocelyn|publisher=MTV. Viacom Media Networks}}</ref> The video is set in two different spaces, as Perry is found both in a snowy background and in a ballroom surrounded by dancers, which are mostly dressed in black apparel.<ref name=\"uncon\">{{cite video|title=Unconditionally|date=2013|people=Bonacorso, Bren|medium=music video|publisher=Capitol Records|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> Those settings were used to represent \"different part[s] of the subconscious\".<ref name=\"mtv\" /> The video premiered through MTV on November 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MTV. Viacom Media Networks.|accessdate=March 22, 2014|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717761/katy-perry-unconditionally-video-premiere.jhtml|author=Montgomery, James|title=Katy Perry's 'Unconditionally' Video: Watch It Now}}</ref>\n\n===Synopsis===\nIt begins with Perry, sitting on the ground while mouthing the lyrics of the song and staring at the viewer. As she finishes the first verse, the camera shifts to a ballroom, in which elegantly-dressed dancers start to dance. The song's chorus kicks in, and Perry is now found in the ballroom, in the middle of all the dancers. As the second verse begins, she has an [[owl]] on her arm, which she lets go and flies. The bird represents \"something strong, free [and] powerful\", according to Bonacorso, who added: \"She lets it go into the world[,] and that literally [means] letting this force within her go wild. That's an important part of love[,] is that you have to let it go.\" The video also shows Perry, with a golden dress and cross-shaped earrings, with flames on her body. By the second repetition of the chorus, a bed gets lit on fire, which the director included to refer to love that \"can burn you like an inferno\". As the song reaches its climax, Perry gets hit by a car, with tiny broken debris from it shattering behind her, while she remains stationary and unharmed. This scene symbolizes the experience of true love, that changes \"your world\" and \"hits you out of the blue\". This scene cuts back to the ballroom, where Perry is surrounded by a similar explosion of \"colorful\" flowers, which is used to contrast the more violent nature of falling in love and the softer part of it, the \"joyful and wonderful\" feelings.\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:Katy Perry - The Prismatic 16.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Perry performing \"Unconditionally\" on her Prismatic World Tour.]]\nOn October 22, 2013, Perry first performed \"Unconditionally\" along with her other ''Prism'' tracks at the [[iHeartRadio]] Theater in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\"ReleaseParty\">{{cite web|last=Gundersen|first=Edna|title=Live stream: Katy Perry's 'Prism' album release party|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/10/22/katy-perry-prism-album-party-stream/3153989/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=October 22, 2013|accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref> She also performed these songs the next day when hosting the \"We Can Survive\" concert along with friends [[Bonnie McKee]], [[Kacey Musgraves]], [[Sara Bareilles]], [[Ellie Goulding]], and duo [[Tegan and Sara]] at the Hollywood Bowl in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Hollywood Bowl\">{{cite web|last=Aguila|first=Justino|title=Katy Perry Hosts Famous Friends, Previews Next Tour at Hollywood Bowl: Live Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5770379/katy-perry-hosts-famous-friends-previews-next-tour-at-hollywood|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref> Perry also performed the song on [[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|the Australian version of ''The X Factor'']] on October 28, 2013 alongside \"Roar\"<ref name=XFactorPrismSongs>{{cite web|first=Carl|last=Williott|title=Watch Katy Perry Perform \"Unconditionally\" & \"Roar\" On 'The X Factor Australia'|url=http://www.idolator.com/7490750/katy-perry-x-factor-australia|publisher=Idolator|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> and also performed it on the Australian breakfast program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' that day.<ref name=SydneyShow>{{cite news|title=Katy Perry shines at Sydney Opera House performance on Sunrise |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/katy-perry-shines-at-sydney-opera-house-performance-on-sunrise/story-fni0cvc9-1226748691445|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> On November 10, 2013, she performed \"Unconditionally\" at the [[2013 MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref name=KatyEMAUnconditionally>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Katy Perry Gets 'Unconditionally' High For EMA|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717178/katy-perry-2013-ema-performance.jhtml|publisher=MTV|date=10 November 2013}}</ref> She also opened the [[American Music Awards of 2013]] on November 24, 2013 with a [[geisha]]-inspired performance of the song.<ref name=OpenAMA2013>{{cite web|last=Talbott|first=Chris|title=Katy Perry Kicks off AMAs With Beautiful Moment |publisher=ABC News|date=November 24, 2013|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/katy-perry-miley-cyrus-book-end-amas-20995268}}</ref> On December 5, 2013, Perry performed the song on the Italian ''[[The X Factor (Italy)|X Factor]]''.<ref name=ItalyXFactor>{{cite web |last=Fowler|first=Brandi |title=Katy Perry Rocks Flower-Covered Sheer Dress at X Factor Italy Show |publisher=E! Online |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/488077/katy-perry-rocks-flower-covered-sheer-dress-at-x-factor-italy-show|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> On December 13, 2013, Perry also performed the song on ''[[The Voice of Germany]]'' together with four contestants of the show.<ref>{{cite web |title=Katy Perry Performs 'Dark Horse' & 'Unconditionally' on 'The Voice of Germany'|url=http://www.directlyrics.com/watch-katy-perry-performs-dark-horse-unconditionally-on-the-voice-of-germany-news.html| publisher=directlyrics.com |date=December 14, 2013}}</ref> On December 14, 2013, Perry performed \"Unconditionally\" at the [[NRJ Music Awards]] 2014.<ref name=\"nrj\">{{cite web |url=http://nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr/videos-4523/media/video/765497-katy-perry-unconditionaly-live-15th-edition.html|title=Katy Perry \"Unconditionaly\" Live 15th edition |language= |last=|first=|publisher=nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr|date=December 14, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> She also performed \"Unconditionally\" on the season 10 finale of [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|''The X Factor'' (UK)]] on December 15, 2013.<ref name=XFactorFinal>{{cite web|title='Tuneless Car Crash': Katy Perry Bombs on the X Factor Final |publisher=Entertainmentwise |date=December 15, 2013|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/135823/Tuneless-Car-Crash-Katy-Perry-Bombs-On-The-X-Factor-Final|last=Kitchener |first=Shaun}}</ref> Perry performed a stripped-down version of the song on the December 20, 2013 episodes of ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' and ''[[Alan Carr: Chatty Man]]''.<ref name=Ellen>{{cite web|last=Degeneres |first=Ellen |title=Day 12 of 12 Days, Katy Perry|url=http://www.ellentv.com/episodes/day-12-of-12-days-katy-perry/|publisher=EllenTV.com|date=December 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nThe performance of \"Unconditionally\" at the American Music Awards led to accusations of [[cultural appropriation]] and [[racism]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Gibson|first=Megan|title=American Music Awards: Katy Perry Performance, Racist or Not?|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/11/25/how-offensive-was-katy-perrys-ama-performance/|publisher=TIME|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Patricia|title=Why all the fuss over Katy Perry's geisha performance at the AMAs?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/26/katy-perry-geisha-performance-american-music-awards-fuss|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> from Asian-American groups and media outlets from the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' to ''[[Psychology Today]]'' for Perry dressing up as a geisha during the performance.<ref>*{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/11/awards-racism-spot-check-katy-perry-edition.html|title=Music Awards Racism Spot-Check: Katy Perry Edition|newspaper=New York}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-pacific-heart/201311/yes-katy-perry-s-performance-was-racist-here-s-why?quicktabs_5=0|title=Yes, Katy Perry's Performance Was Racist, Here's Why|newspaper=Psychology Today}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/scene/2013/11/26/memories-of-a-geisha-katy-perrys-amas-performance-stirs-debate/?KEYWORDS=Jeff+Yang|title=Geisha A-Go-Go: Katy Perry's AMAs Performance Stirs Debate|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> Her stylist and ''[[America's Next Top Model]]'' creative director Johnny Wujek explained later \"Katy and I both love Japan..... The people are so kind, there's so much there visually\" then described his process of finding authentic kimonos then cutting them up according to his own inspirations.<ref name=\"eon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/484980/katy-perry-s-stylist-explains-geisha-inspired-outfit-at-amas-we-love-japan|title=Katy Perry's Stylist Explains Geisha-Inspired Outfit at AMAs: We Love Japan!|publisher=Eonline.com}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] defended her, stating: \"I think people are generally too sensitive and they should just leave her be\".<ref name=GagaDefense>{{cite web|title=Lady Gaga Teases 'ARTPOP' Tour, Defends Katy Perry Amidst AMAs Controversy |url=http://news.radio.com/2013/11/25/lady-gaga-teases-artpop-tour-defends-katy-perry-amidst-amas-controversy/|publisher=radio.com |date=November 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Credits and Personnel==\n*Vocals: [[Katy Perry]]\n*Songwriting: Katy Perry, Lukasz Gottwald, Max Martin, Henry Walter\n*Production: Dr. Luke, Max Martin, Cirkut\nCredits adapted from ''Prism'' album liner notes.<ref name=\"Notes\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''CD single'''<ref name=AmazonCD>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally|url=https://www.amazon.de/Unconditionally-2-Track-Katy-Perry/dp/B00GBJVJ86/|publisher=Amazon.de|date=November 22, 2013}}</ref>\n#\"Unconditionally\" \u2013 3:48\n#\"Unconditionally\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:48\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2013\u201314)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|11|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=aria|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|16|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=austria|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|49|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=flanders|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|3|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=flanders2|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|26|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=wallonia|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|1|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=wallonia2|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Bulgaria|5|url=http://www.bamp-bg.org/2009-07-08-09-48-53/nielsen/439-25112013-01122013.html|urltitle=25.11.2013-01.12.2013 \u2013 IFPI at bamp-br.org|rowheader=true|refname=bulgaria|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadianhot10