dance singles of 2014 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Katy Perry}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Katy Perry]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Dr. Luke]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Katy Perry songs]]\n[[Category:2013 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Cirkut (record producer)]]\n[[Category:2013 singles]]\n[[Category:2010s ballads]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{See Wiktionary|the Katy Perry song|unconditionally|term}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Unconditionally\n| cover      = Katy Perry - \"Unconditionally\".png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Katy Perry]]\n| album      = [[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]\n| released   = {{start date|2013|10|16}}\n| format     = {{Flat list|\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[Music download|digital download]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     = {{hlist|Luke's in the Boo ([[Malibu, California]])|[[Conway Recording Studios]] ([[Hollywood, California]])|[[Maratone Studios|MXM Studios]] ([[Stockholm, Sweden]])|Secret Garden Studios ([[Montecito, California]])}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"digitalspyrc\"/>\n| length     = 3:48\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = {{Flat list|\n*[[Katy Perry]]\n*[[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]\n*[[Max Martin]]\n*[[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{Flat list|\n*[[Dr. Luke]]\n*Max Martin\n*[[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Who You Love]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Dark Horse (Katy Perry song)|Dark Horse]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|XjwZAa2EjKA|\"Unconditionally\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Unconditionally'''\" is a song by American singer [[Katy Perry]]. It was released as the second single from her fourth studio album ''[[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]'' (2013) on October 16, 2013. Inspiration for the song came primarily from a humanitarian trip to [[Madagascar]] that Perry made in partnership with [[UNICEF]]. Having been surrounded by what she described as [[unconditional love]], she co-wrote it with the song's producers [[Dr. Luke]], [[Max Martin]] and [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]] to reflect that feeling.\n\n\"Unconditionally\" is a [[power ballad]] styled in [[Rock music|rock]], backed against a [[bassline]] and [[percussion]]. Commercially, it peaked within the top ten in Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Italy, Lebanon, and South Africa as well as the top twenty in Australia, Austria, Canada, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia, and the United States.\n\nThe single release was promoted with an [[Instagram]]-based campaign, a lyric video directed by [[Aya Tanimura]] and live performances\u2014one of the latter, at the [[American Music Awards of 2013]], was the center of controversy due to accusations of [[cultural appropriation]] and [[racism]]. Brent Benacorso served as the director for the track's [[music video]], which adopts the theme of love and uses a series of metaphors to enrich its concept.\n\n==Writing and production==\n\"Unconditionally\" was written by Perry alongside its producers [[Dr. Luke]], [[Max Martin]], and [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]. Perry denoted the song as her favorite within the record. She also mentioned that she wrote the song bearing in mind the sentiments she had felt during her [[UNICEF]] humanitarian trip to [[Madagascar]] in April 2013. Such sentiments inspired her to delve into the theme of [[unconditional love]]. She stated that, while on that voyage, Perry and her team would \"go in cruisers up the mountain\" to see newly constructed schools. After observing a group of children, she realized that even without social networking, they felt \"pure\" [[unconditional love]] towards each other.<ref name=Goosebump>{{cite web|last=Montgomery|first=James|title=Katy Perry Reveals Secret Formula For Single Success: 'The Goose Bump Test'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717816/katy-perry-unconditionally-goosebumps.jhtml|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom Media Networks]].|date=November 20, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nInspired by that situation, the song was described by Perry as approaching all forms of [[love]]. \"I love this song because not only can it be a romantic, intimate song\", she expounded. \"But it can be about the type of love that a mother has when she sees her first child, or best friends [...] It is a transcendent love, not just relationship status.\"<ref name=Goosebump /> \"Unconditionally\" was also inspired by the acceptance of one's flaws in a relationship, which Perry believed was relatable to listeners.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MTV UK. Viacom Media Networks.|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=October 24, 2013|title=Katy Perry 'Was Scared To Be Accepted in Relationships'|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/katy-perry/news/katy-perry-was-scared-to-be-accepted-in-relationships}}</ref> It was engineered by Peter Carlsson, Clint Gibbs, Sam Holland, and Michael Illbert, with assistance by Eric Eylands, Rachael Findlen, Justin Fox, and Cory Bice, at the MXM Studios in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]] and Conway Recording Studios in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]. Perry also handled vocal production. Engineering for mix was carried out by John Hanes and final mixing was helmed by Serban Ghenea at the MixStar Studios in [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Prism |titlelink=Prism (Katy Perry album) |others=Katy Perry |year=2013 |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Capitol Records]] |location=United States}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nAt a length of three minutes and forty-eight seconds (3:48), \"Unconditionally\" is a [[pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"digitalspyrc\">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/feature/a525129/playlist-10-tracks-you-need-to-hear/|title=Playlist: 10 tracks you need to hear|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> [[power ballad]], which is styled in the genre of [[rock music|rock]].<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/prism-deluxe-version/id690928033 |title=Prism (Deluxe) \u2013 Katy Perry|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]. [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014 |date=October 22, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Fuse\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fuse.tv/2013/10/katy-perry-unconditionally |title=Listen: Katy Perry Wails on New Single 'Unconditionally' |first=Jeff |last=Benjamin |publisher=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]. [[The Madison Square Garden Company]]. |accessdate=March 8, 2014 |date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref> According to the sheet music published by Kobalt Music Publishing America, Inc. at Musicnotes.com, it is written in the key of [[G major]]. It paces at a moderately fast [[metronome]], at approximately 129 beats per minute, while it is set at a [[Common time|4/4]] [[time signature]], following a chord progression of Em\u2013C\u2013G\u2013D. Perry's vocals in the track span from G{{sub|3}} to E{{sub|5}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally \u2013 By Katy Perry \u2013 Digital Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0126609|publisher=Musicnotes.com.|accessdate=March 8, 2014|date = 2013-10-30}}</ref> The track's \"uncluttered\" instrumentation features woodblock percussion and a \"dramatic\" bass line. Lyrically, Jason Lipshutz from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' deemed it the \"most mature offering\" on ''Prism'', claiming it served as a \"predicate\" to Perry's 2010 single \"[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry song)|Teenage Dream]]\".<ref name=\"BB1\">{{cite news|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=Katy Perry's 'Prism' Album Preview: 10 Things You Need To Know|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5687099/katy-perrys-prism-album-preview-10-things-you-need-to-know|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 6, 2013| accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\nIn September 2013, Perry teased the release of the song as the second single from ''Prism'', without revealing its title or date. However, MTV concluded that such song was \"Unconditionally\", which she discussed during a listening party for the record.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|publisher=MTV. Viacom Media Networks.|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=September 23, 2013|title=What's Katy Perry's Next Single? She Gives Us Some Clues|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1714463/katy-perry-next-single-unconditionally.jhtml|author=Garibaldi, Christina}}</ref> The release was confirmed by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=September 27, 2013|author=Lipshutz, Jason|title=Katy Perry Confirms Next 'PRISM' Single|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5740589/katy-perry-confirms-next-prism-single}}</ref> The track debuted on October 16, 2013<ref name=\"Fuse\" /> and was serviced by [[Capitol Records]] to [[contemporary hit radio]] stations in the United States on October 22.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=October 16, 2013|title=Katy Perry's New 'Prism' Song 'Unconditionally' Gets First Play on Capital FM \u2013 Audio|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/katy-perry/news/unconditionally-first-play/}}</ref><ref name=MainstreamRelease /> The next day, it was sent to Australian radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joy.org.au/music/2013/10/24/new-music-to-weekdays-october-23-2013/|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=October 24, 2013|title=New music to weekdays (October 23, 2013)|publisher=[[Joy 94.9]]}}</ref> A [[CD single]] was released in Germany on November 22\u2014 the same date it was serviced to radios in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|date=November 22, 2013|accessdate=March 9, 2014|publisher=[[Amazon.de]]|title=Unconditionally (2-Track)|url=https://www.amazon.de/Unconditionally-2-Track-Katy-Perry/dp/B00GBJVJ86/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally \u2013 Katy Perry|url=http://www.radioairplay.fm/RadioDate/PublicDetails/41552|accessdate=March 21, 2014|date=November 22, 2013|publisher=RadioAirplay|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204071315/http://www.radioairplay.fm/RadioDate/PublicDetails/41552|archive-date=December 4, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In France, imports of the CD started being sold on December 3.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally [CD Single, Import]|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Unconditionally-Katy-Perry/dp/B00GBJVJ86/|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=December 3, 2013|publisher=[[Amazon.fr]]}}</ref> A remix version of the song by Johnson Somerset was featured on a [[compilation album]] entitled ''Songs for the Philippines'' benefiting those affected by [[Typhoon Haiyan]] in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/beatles-eminem-u2-set-for-philippines-benefit-album-20131126|title=Beatles, Eminem, U2 Set for Philippines Benefit Album|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|first=Kory|last=Grow|date=November 26, 2013|accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Music video#Lyric video|lyric video]] for \"Unconditionally\", directed by [[Aya Tanimura]], was released on October 18, 2013.<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/19/katy-perry-pays-homage-to-dangerous-liaisons-anna-karenina-the-great-gatsby-in-unconditionally-music-video|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 19, 2013|author=Camp, Alexa|title=Katy Perry Pays Homage to Dangerous Liaisons, Anna Karenina, & The Great Gatsby in \"Unconditionally\" Music Video}}</ref><ref name=VEVO>{{cite video|format=Lyric video|title=Unconditionally|url=http://www.vevo.com/watch/katy-perry/unconditionally-lyric-video/USUV71302466|publisher=[[Vevo]]|accessdate=October 18, 2013|people=Tanimura, Aya}}</ref> Set in a [[Monochrome|monochromatic]] pattern, it features actresses Janell Shirtcliff and [[Erika Linder]], who appear naked. As Shirtcliff mouths the song's lyrics, which appear in white and fade slowly, Linder looks \"painful[ly]\" into the camera. They are only shown together by the end of the video, in which scene they look into each other's eyes.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=[[Spin Media]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014|date=October 20, 2013|title=Katy Perry's 'Unconditionally' Lyric Video Could Be A Real Music Video|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/katy-perrys-unconditionally-lyric-video-could-be-real-music-video}}</ref> The video is different in style and approach from the song's official music video, which is retro-styled.<ref name=slant /> Fans were invited to participate in an [[Instagram]]-based campaign, in which they could upload a photo of \"what unconditional love meant to them\", along with their story and location in order for it to appear on a \"''Prism'' map of the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/Digital-Music-Report-2014.pdf|title=Digital Music Report 2014|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nJason Lipshutz from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' deemed the song a \"visceral ballad\" capable of conveying its theme of relationships.<ref name=\"billboardreview\">{{cite web|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 21, 2013|title=Katy Perry's 'PRISM': Track-By-Track Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5763162/katy-perrys-prism-track-by-track-review|author=Lipshutz, Jason}}</ref> John Walker from [[MTV]] praised the track and felt that the song could be written from the perspective of [[Jesus]] and denoted possible Christian undertones lying.<ref name=\"mtvbuzzworthy\">{{cite web|publisher=[[MTV Buzzworthy]]. [[MTV]].|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 22, 2013|author=Walker, John|title=Katy Perry's 'Prism': A Track-By-Track Review..... In Cat GIFs!|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2013/10/22/katy-perry-prism-review-cat-gifs/}}</ref> Kitty Empire of ''[[The Guardian]]'' reckoned the track was \"ungainly\" and \"adverbial\";<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 20, 2013|title=Katy Perry: Prism \u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/20/katy-perry-prism-review|author=Empire, Kitty}}</ref> Helen Brown of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote that its lyrics had \"self-help lingo\", although she remarked that \"Perry's genuine faith in it, along with her wit and sense of fun, powers her through\".<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 17, 2013|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopreviews/10386191/Katy-Perry-Prism-review.html|title=Katy Perry, Prism, review|author=Brown, Helen}}</ref> Kevin Fallon from [[The Daily Beast]] regarded it as adequate for a [[Nicholas Sparks]]-adapted movie, however, he noted that Perry's vocal delivery saved the song of being \"schmaltzy\".<ref name=\"thedailybeast\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Daily Beast]]. [[The Newsweek Daily Beast Company]].|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 22, 2013|last=Fallon|first=Kevin|title='Prism' Review: Katy Perry Perfects the Pop Blockbuster|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/10/22/prism-review-katy-perry-perfects-the-pop-blockbuster.html|newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\n[[HitFix]]'s Melinda Newman graded the track with a 'B'\u2014she felt Perry's voice sounded \"soaring\", and opined that the theme of the song resonated due to Perry's vocal and overall delivery.<ref name=\"hitfix\">{{cite web|publisher=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 21, 2013|title=Katy Perry's 'Prism' reflects her heart and soul set to a beat: Review|url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/katy-perrys-prism-reflects-her-heart-and-soul-set-to-a-beat-review|author=Newman, Melinda}}</ref> Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsday]]'' thought Perry \"ruined\" the track, which she deemed \"decent\", for pronouncing the song title as \"uncondiSHUNally\".<ref name=\"newsday\">{{cite web|work=[[Newsday]]|publisher=[[Cablevision]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 18, 2013|title='Prism' review: Katy Perry is all over the place|author=Gamboa, Glenn|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/prism-review-katy-perry-is-all-over-the-place-1.6280564}}</ref> In his review for ''Prism'', Jon Dolan from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that the song \"set stark revelations to torrential Euro splendor\".<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Wenner Media LLC]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|author=Dolan, Jon|date=October 16, 2013|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/prism-20131016|title=Katy Perry \u2013 Prism}}</ref> Katie Woodard from ''[[Nouse]]'' said the song's \"power ballad approach\" highlights Perry's vocal performance.<ref name=\"nouse\">{{cite web|title=Album Review: Katy Perry \u2013 Prism|url=http://www.nouse.co.uk/2013/10/28/album-review-katy-perry-prism/|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=March 5, 2014|author=Woodard, Katie|work=[[Nouse]]|publisher=[[University of York Students' Union]]}}</ref> Trent Wolfe of [[The Verge]], however, thought the song was part of the group of the ''Prism'' tracks that could \"benefit from a preciously strummed six-string\" instead of \"beats and synths\".<ref name=\"theverge\">{{cite web|publisher=[[The Verge]]. [[Vox Media]].|accessdate=March 5, 2014|date=October 23, 2013|title=Get real: Katy Perry lets go of the teenage dream with 'Prism'|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/23/4877672/get-real-katy-perry-lets-go-of-the-teenage-dream-with-prism|author=Wolfe, Trent}}</ref> [[Digital Spy]]'s Robert Copsey awarded the song with a four out of five points rating, writing that Perry sounded \"effortless\" as compared to her peers.<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|title= Katy Perry 'Unconditionally' single review: Soaring, effortless ballad|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=March 7, 2014|author=Copsey, Robert|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/review/a536157/katy-perry-unconditionally-single-review-soaring-effortless-ballad.html}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Unconditionally\" debuted on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 30.<ref>{{cite web|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|title=Lorde's 'Royals' Crowns Hot 100 For Fifth Week|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5770722/lordes-royals-crowns-hot-100-for-fifth-week|author=Trust, Gary|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=October 30, 2013}}</ref> The next week, it moved five spots up to number 25;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5778259/lordes-royals-rules-hot-100-for-sixth-week|title=Lorde's 'Royals' Rules Hot 100 for Sixth Week|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 6, 2013|author=Trust, Gary|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> it further moved three spots the following week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lorde's 'Royals' Leads Hot 100, Lady Gaga's 'Dope' Debuts at No. 8|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5785931/lordes-royals-leads-hot-100-lady-gagas-dope-debuts-at-no-8|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 13, 2013|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|author=Trust, Gary}}</ref> On its fourth week, the track went to number 16 and one week later it rose one spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5812407/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-swings-back-to-no-1-on-hot-100|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=December 4, 2013|author=Trust, Gary|title=Miley Cyrus' 'Wrecking Ball' Swings Back To No. 1 on Hot 100}}</ref> It later peaked at number 14 on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=December 18, 2013|title=Eminem, Rihanna Remain Atop Hot 100 With 'The Monster'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5840334/eminem-rihanna-remain-atop-hot-100-with-the-monster|author=Trust, Gary|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> In doing so, it was Perry's second single to miss peaking within the top 10 of the chart.<ref name=\"US\" /> On the component charts of ''Billboard'', \"Unconditionally\" enjoyed success\u2014it peaked atop the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]], while reaching number seven on the [[Adult Top 40]] and number 16 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] charts.<ref name=\"dance\" /><ref name=\"adult1\" /><ref name=\"adult2\" /> On the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Pop Songs]] chart, it peaked at number 8.<ref name=pop /> The song has sold more than 1,000,000 copies in the United States; consequently it was certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).{{Certification Cite Ref|relyear=2013|artist=Katy Perry|title=Unconditionally|region=United States|number=1|award=Platinum|certyear=2014}}\n\n\"Unconditionally\" achieved moderate success in Oceanic regions. The song debuted and peaked at 11 on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]]. It then gradually descended down the charts and has spent a total of 13 weeks, marking it as Perry's lowest spanning single in Australia. The song however received a platinum certification by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA), denoting more than 70,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"aria\" /> In New Zealand, the song entered at 26, where it ultimately peaked. Unable to peak higher, the song spent 10 weeks on the singles chart. It subsequently became Perry's lowest spanning and peaking single in New Zealand.<ref name=\"nz\" />\n\nIn Europe, the song performed moderately as well. It reached its highest position of number 5 in Bulgaria while having its lowest peak in Russia, at number 69.<ref name=\"bulgaria\" /><ref name=\"russia\" /> It reached number 16 on the [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]]\u2014where it spent 12 weeks.<ref name=\"austria\" /> On the Italian, German and Czech single charts, it was able to peak within the top 10, at number 6 for the first two and number 8 on the latter.<ref name=\"italy\" /> In Italy, it sold more than 50,000 copies and was certified Platinum by the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] (FIMI).{{Certification Cite Ref|artist=Katy Perry|title=Unconditionally|relyear=2013|certyear=2014|region=Italy|autocat=yes|type=single|award=Platinum}} On the French [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]] chart, it peaked at number 38, and was Perry's third single to miss the top 20 there.<ref name=\"france\" /> In the United Kingdom, \"Unconditionally\" reached number 25; while in Ireland it peaked at number 27.<ref name=\"uk\" /><ref name=\"irish\" /> It fared better in Slovakia where it charted at number 11; in Belgium it reached numbers 49 and 26 in Flanders and Wallonia, respectively.<ref name=\"slovakia\" /><ref name=\"flanders\" /><ref name=\"wallonia\" /> In the Mexican [[Monitor Latino]] and Poland single chart, it managed to peak at 17<ref name=\"mexico\" /><ref name=\"poland\" /> while in Netherlands, it reached number 32. The track charted at numbers 26 and 27 in Spain.<ref name=\"spain\" />\n\n==Music video==\n===Production and release===\nThe [[music video]] for \"Unconditionally\", directed by Brent Bonacorso, was filmed in London during October 2013.<ref name=\"slant\" /><ref name=MusicVideo>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry Confirms She Filmed 'Unconditionally' Music Video in London Last Week|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/katy-perry/news/unconditionally-music-video-london/|publisher=Capital FM|accessdate=October 23, 2013|date=October 23, 2013}}</ref> It was partly inspired by the [[Historical period drama|costume drama]] films ''[[Dangerous Liaisons]]'' and ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|title=Was Katy Perry Tempted To Write Any 'Screw You' Anthems on Prism?|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717767/katy-perry-prism-songwriting.jhtml|publisher=MTV. [[Viacom Media Networks]].|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> During an interview with [[MTV]], Bonacorso talked about the concept for the video. He stressed that he wanted to match the song's tone with its visual, explaining that he wanted to depict a \"more mysterious, elegant and sophisticated world to live in..... less about a time period and more about creating an impression and a feeling.\" As the song essentially discusses the feeling of love, the video itself sees Perry amidst scenarios which indirectly refer to the power of it.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry's Bed Is on Fire: Her 'Unconditionally' Director Explains Why|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717850/katy-perry-unconditionally-video-director-explains.jhtml|accessdate=March 22, 2014|date=November 21, 2013|author=Vena, Jocelyn|publisher=MTV. Viacom Media Networks}}</ref> The video is set in two different spaces, as Perry is found both in a snowy background and in a ballroom surrounded by dancers, which are mostly dressed in black apparel.<ref name=\"uncon\">{{cite video|title=Unconditionally|date=2013|people=Bonacorso, Bren|medium=music video|publisher=Capitol Records|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> Those settings were used to represent \"different part[s] of the subconscious\".<ref name=\"mtv\" /> The video premiered through MTV on November 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MTV. Viacom Media Networks.|accessdate=March 22, 2014|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717761/katy-perry-unconditionally-video-premiere.jhtml|author=Montgomery, James|title=Katy Perry's 'Unconditionally' Video: Watch It Now}}</ref>\n\n===Synopsis===\nIt begins with Perry, sitting on the ground while mouthing the lyrics of the song and staring at the viewer. As she finishes the first verse, the camera shifts to a ballroom, in which elegantly-dressed dancers start to dance. The song's chorus kicks in, and Perry is now found in the ballroom, in the middle of all the dancers. As the second verse begins, she has an [[owl]] on her arm, which she lets go and flies. The bird represents \"something strong, free [and] powerful\", according to Bonacorso, who added: \"She lets it go into the world[,] and that literally [means] letting this force within her go wild. That's an important part of love[,] is that you have to let it go.\" The video also shows Perry, with a golden dress and cross-shaped earrings, with flames on her body. By the second repetition of the chorus, a bed gets lit on fire, which the director included to refer to love that \"can burn you like an inferno\". As the song reaches its climax, Perry gets hit by a car, with tiny broken debris from it shattering behind her, while she remains stationary and unharmed. This scene symbolizes the experience of true love, that changes \"your world\" and \"hits you out of the blue\". This scene cuts back to the ballroom, where Perry is surrounded by a similar explosion of \"colorful\" flowers, which is used to contrast the more violent nature of falling in love and the softer part of it, the \"joyful and wonderful\" feelings.\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:Katy Perry - The Prismatic 16.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Perry performing \"Unconditionally\" on her Prismatic World Tour.]]\nOn October 22, 2013, Perry first performed \"Unconditionally\" along with her other ''Prism'' tracks at the [[iHeartRadio]] Theater in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\"ReleaseParty\">{{cite web|last=Gundersen|first=Edna|title=Live stream: Katy Perry's 'Prism' album release party|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/10/22/katy-perry-prism-album-party-stream/3153989/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=October 22, 2013|accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref> She also performed these songs the next day when hosting the \"We Can Survive\" concert along with friends [[Bonnie McKee]], [[Kacey Musgraves]], [[Sara Bareilles]], [[Ellie Goulding]], and duo [[Tegan and Sara]] at the Hollywood Bowl in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Hollywood Bowl\">{{cite web|last=Aguila|first=Justino|title=Katy Perry Hosts Famous Friends, Previews Next Tour at Hollywood Bowl: Live Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5770379/katy-perry-hosts-famous-friends-previews-next-tour-at-hollywood|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref> Perry also performed the song on [[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|the Australian version of ''The X Factor'']] on October 28, 2013 alongside \"Roar\"<ref name=XFactorPrismSongs>{{cite web|first=Carl|last=Williott|title=Watch Katy Perry Perform \"Unconditionally\" & \"Roar\" On 'The X Factor Australia'|url=http://www.idolator.com/7490750/katy-perry-x-factor-australia|publisher=Idolator|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> and also performed it on the Australian breakfast program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' that day.<ref name=SydneyShow>{{cite news|title=Katy Perry shines at Sydney Opera House performance on Sunrise |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/katy-perry-shines-at-sydney-opera-house-performance-on-sunrise/story-fni0cvc9-1226748691445|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> On November 10, 2013, she performed \"Unconditionally\" at the [[2013 MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref name=KatyEMAUnconditionally>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Katy Perry Gets 'Unconditionally' High For EMA|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1717178/katy-perry-2013-ema-performance.jhtml|publisher=MTV|date=10 November 2013}}</ref> She also opened the [[American Music Awards of 2013]] on November 24, 2013 with a [[geisha]]-inspired performance of the song.<ref name=OpenAMA2013>{{cite web|last=Talbott|first=Chris|title=Katy Perry Kicks off AMAs With Beautiful Moment |publisher=ABC News|date=November 24, 2013|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/katy-perry-miley-cyrus-book-end-amas-20995268}}</ref> On December 5, 2013, Perry performed the song on the Italian ''[[The X Factor (Italy)|X Factor]]''.<ref name=ItalyXFactor>{{cite web |last=Fowler|first=Brandi |title=Katy Perry Rocks Flower-Covered Sheer Dress at X Factor Italy Show |publisher=E! Online |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/488077/katy-perry-rocks-flower-covered-sheer-dress-at-x-factor-italy-show|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> On December 13, 2013, Perry also performed the song on ''[[The Voice of Germany]]'' together with four contestants of the show.<ref>{{cite web |title=Katy Perry Performs 'Dark Horse' & 'Unconditionally' on 'The Voice of Germany'|url=http://www.directlyrics.com/watch-katy-perry-performs-dark-horse-unconditionally-on-the-voice-of-germany-news.html| publisher=directlyrics.com |date=December 14, 2013}}</ref> On December 14, 2013, Perry performed \"Unconditionally\" at the [[NRJ Music Awards]] 2014.<ref name=\"nrj\">{{cite web |url=http://nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr/videos-4523/media/video/765497-katy-perry-unconditionaly-live-15th-edition.html|title=Katy Perry \"Unconditionaly\" Live 15th edition |language= |last=|first=|publisher=nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr|date=December 14, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> She also performed \"Unconditionally\" on the season 10 finale of [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|''The X Factor'' (UK)]] on December 15, 2013.<ref name=XFactorFinal>{{cite web|title='Tuneless Car Crash': Katy Perry Bombs on the X Factor Final |publisher=Entertainmentwise |date=December 15, 2013|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/135823/Tuneless-Car-Crash-Katy-Perry-Bombs-On-The-X-Factor-Final|last=Kitchener |first=Shaun}}</ref> Perry performed a stripped-down version of the song on the December 20, 2013 episodes of ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' and ''[[Alan Carr: Chatty Man]]''.<ref name=Ellen>{{cite web|last=Degeneres |first=Ellen |title=Day 12 of 12 Days, Katy Perry|url=http://www.ellentv.com/episodes/day-12-of-12-days-katy-perry/|publisher=EllenTV.com|date=December 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nThe performance of \"Unconditionally\" at the American Music Awards led to accusations of [[cultural appropriation]] and [[racism]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Gibson|first=Megan|title=American Music Awards: Katy Perry Performance, Racist or Not?|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/11/25/how-offensive-was-katy-perrys-ama-performance/|publisher=TIME|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Patricia|title=Why all the fuss over Katy Perry's geisha performance at the AMAs?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/26/katy-perry-geisha-performance-american-music-awards-fuss|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> from Asian-American groups and media outlets from the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' to ''[[Psychology Today]]'' for Perry dressing up as a geisha during the performance.<ref>*{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/11/awards-racism-spot-check-katy-perry-edition.html|title=Music Awards Racism Spot-Check: Katy Perry Edition|newspaper=New York}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-pacific-heart/201311/yes-katy-perry-s-performance-was-racist-here-s-why?quicktabs_5=0|title=Yes, Katy Perry's Performance Was Racist, Here's Why|newspaper=Psychology Today}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/scene/2013/11/26/memories-of-a-geisha-katy-perrys-amas-performance-stirs-debate/?KEYWORDS=Jeff+Yang|title=Geisha A-Go-Go: Katy Perry's AMAs Performance Stirs Debate|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> Her stylist and ''[[America's Next Top Model]]'' creative director Johnny Wujek explained later \"Katy and I both love Japan..... The people are so kind, there's so much there visually\" then described his process of finding authentic kimonos then cutting them up according to his own inspirations.<ref name=\"eon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/484980/katy-perry-s-stylist-explains-geisha-inspired-outfit-at-amas-we-love-japan|title=Katy Perry's Stylist Explains Geisha-Inspired Outfit at AMAs: We Love Japan!|publisher=Eonline.com}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] defended her, stating: \"I think people are generally too sensitive and they should just leave her be\".<ref name=GagaDefense>{{cite web|title=Lady Gaga Teases 'ARTPOP' Tour, Defends Katy Perry Amidst AMAs Controversy |url=http://news.radio.com/2013/11/25/lady-gaga-teases-artpop-tour-defends-katy-perry-amidst-amas-controversy/|publisher=radio.com |date=November 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Credits and Personnel==\n*Vocals: [[Katy Perry]]\n*Songwriting: Katy Perry, Lukasz Gottwald, Max Martin, Henry Walter\n*Production: Dr. Luke, Max Martin, Cirkut\nCredits adapted from ''Prism'' album liner notes.<ref name=\"Notes\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''CD single'''<ref name=AmazonCD>{{cite web|title=Unconditionally|url=https://www.amazon.de/Unconditionally-2-Track-Katy-Perry/dp/B00GBJVJ86/|publisher=Amazon.de|date=November 22, 2013}}</ref>\n#\"Unconditionally\" \u2013 3:48\n#\"Unconditionally\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:48\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2013\u201314)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|11|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=aria|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|16|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=austria|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|49|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=flanders|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|3|artist=Katy Perry|song=Unconditionally|rowheader=true|refname=flanders2|accessdate=March 23, 201