 comic book conventions|Comic Con]] Cape Town, postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/whats-on/cape-town/comic-con-cape-town-postponed-to-2021-45138721|title=Comic Con Cape Town postponed to 2021|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Agricultural events such as the [[Pietermaritzburg]] Royal Show, SA Cheese Festival, Qualit\u00e9 Awards Dinner, and Agri-Expo Western Cape Youth Show, cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodformzansi.co.za/covid-19-farmers-urged-to-protect-themselves-workers/|title=COVID-19: Farmers urged to protect themselves, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than {{val|7500}} MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer \u2013 here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months' imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" />\n\nThe arrival of the COVID-19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\"MaverickFake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>   \n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \"nothing called corona here\".<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a COVID-19 \"vaccine\" in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\" /> \n\nFake news that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of COVID-19 symptoms also spread in the country during this period as it also did in other countries around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says '5G causing Covid-19 deaths' is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 South African government statements]\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/media/ NICD media]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Official government website for information about Coronavirus in South Africa]\n*[https://t.me/CoronaZABot Corona Telegram Bot for South Africa]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jeandr\u00e9 du Toit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:lockdown +14 and c1934 better ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "2020 LFF I Lyga", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| logo               = \n| pixels             = \n| caption            = \n| competition        = [[I Lyga]]\n| season             = 2020\n| winners            = \n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = \n| matches            = \n| total goals        = \n| league topscorer   = \n| biggest home win   = \n| biggest away win   = \n| highest scoring    = \n| longest wins       = \n| longest unbeaten   = \n| longest winless    = \n| longest losses     = \n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| attendance         = \n| average attendance = \n| updated            = \n| prevseason         = [[2019 LFF I Lyga|2019]]\n| nextseason         = 2021\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 LFF I Lyga''' is the 31st season of the [[I Lyga]], the second tier [[association football|football]] league of [[Lithuania]]. The season begins in March and finishes in October.\n\n==Teams==\nThe last-placed [[A Lyga]] team is normally relegated to I Lyga. Since [[FC Stumbras]] had gone out of business in July 2019, no team was relegated from A Lyga in 2019. The 7th placed team in A Lyga contests a play-off match with 2nd placed I Lyga team. In this play-off match [[FK Banga Garg\u017edai]] beat A Lyga side [[FC Palanga]] to claim a spot in the A Lyga.\n\nTwo teams from the [[II Lyga]] are promoted to I Lyga, the winners of each of the two II Lyga groups. Last season's winners were [[Kauno \u017dalgiris B]] and [[FSK Radvili\u0161kis]].\n\nIn Lithuanian football, ultimately the licensing process determines clubs eligibility to contest in the respective league.\n\n===Licensing Process===\nAt the end of [[2019 A Lyga]] season, a match fixing investigation was launched after irregular betting patterns were reported. In December 2019 the results of the investigation were published, resulting expulsion of [[FK Atlantas]] and [[FC Palanga]] from A Lyga, and their demotion to II Lyga. The clubs appealed, but their appeals were rejected. The clubs attempted to license to I Lyga, but the decision to demote the clubs to II Lyga stood ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9442/2020-m-sezono-i-lygos-licenciju-sieks-14-futbolo-klubu-ir-komandu/\n|website=LFF\n|title=2020 m. sezono I lygos licencij\u0173 sieks 14 futbolo klub\u0173 ir komand\u0173\n|date=2020-02-19\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9419/fk-atlantas-ir-fk-palanga-del-manipuliavimo-rezultatais-yra-salinami-is-a-lygos/\n|website=LFF\n|title=FK \"Atlantas\" ir FK \"Palanga\" d\u0117l manipuliavimo rezultatais yra \u0161alinami i\u0161 A lygos\n|date=2019-12-05\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nWith reduction of numbers in A Lyga, several I Lyga clubs attempted to leapfrog into promotion to A Lyga. [[DFK Dainava]], [[Vilniaus Vytis]] and [[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] have applied for A Lyga license. [[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] later withdrew their application, while [[DFK Dainava]] and [[Vilniaus Vytis]] had their applications rejected. [[FC D\u017eiugas]], last season's I Lyga winners application was also rejected failing to meet several criteria. [[FK Banga Garg\u017edai]] was the only I Lyga club that successfully licensed to A Lyga. Three of the four other applicants, [[FC D\u017eiugas]], [[DFK Dainava]] and [[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] I Lyga licenses were automatically approved. [[Vilniaus Vytis]] failed to meet I Lyga licensing criteria, and license was not issued even after the appeal. However, the club was granted an exception with a condition that the club reaches certain milestones by 9 March. Vytis will start the season with 3 point penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9466/isibegeja-a-ir-i-lygos-klubu-licencijavimo-sezonas/\n|website=LFF\n|title=\u012esib\u0117g\u0117ja A ir I lygos klub\u0173 licencijavimo sezonas\n|date=2020-01-13\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9582/licencijavimo-komitetas-isdave-i-lygos-licencijas-13ai-klubu-ir-komandu/\n|website=LFF\n|title=Licencijavimo komitetas i\u0161dav\u0117 I lygos licencijas 13 klub\u0173 ir komand\u0173\n|date=2020-02-19\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 further match fixing investigation results were published. As a result, [[FC Kupi\u0161kis]] was fined and expelled from I Lyga.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9546/del-manipuliavimo-rezultatais-fc-kupiskis-salinamas-is-i-lygos/\n|website=LFF\n|title=D\u0117l manipuliavimo rezultatais FC Kupi\u0161kis \u0161alinamas i\u0161 I lygos\n|date=2020-02-11\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nOther I Lyga teams [[FK Nev\u0117\u017eis]], [[FA \u0160iauliai]], [[Baltijos Futbolo Akademija]] (which split up from partnership with [[FK Vilnius (2019)]]), [[FK Minija (2017)]], [[FK Jonava]] , [[FK Riteriai#Riteriai B|Riteriai B]] renewed their licenses successfully, although [[FK Nev\u0117\u017eis]] needed to go through the appeal process. Successful licensing to I Lyga was awarded to [[FK Atmosfera (2012)]] and [[FK \u017dalgiris#\u017dalgiris B|\u017dalgiris B]] as well, despite their results suggesting relegation to II Lyga.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9595/apeliacinio-licencijavimo-komiteto-sprendimai-del-i-lygos-licencijos-pareiskeju-apeliaciju/\n|website=LFF\n|title=Apeliacinio licencijavimo komiteto sprendimai d\u0117l I lygos licencijos parei\u0161k\u0117j\u0173 apeliacij\u0173\n|date=2020-02-25\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nThree [[II Lyga]] teams licensed successfully to I Lyga - II Lyga Southern Group winners [[Kauno \u017dalgiris B]], as well as 4th placed [[Panev\u0117\u017eys B]] and 13th placed [[S\u016bduva B]]. Other II Lyga teams that sought I Lyga licenses were [[FK Auk\u0161taitija]] and the II Lyga Western Group winners [[FSK Radvili\u0161kis]]. The licensing criteria were not met and the promotion was not granted. [[FK Auk\u0161taitija]] asked to grant an exception to participate without a license, but this request was rejected as well.\n\n[[III Lyga]] ''([[Klaip\u0117da]]`s zone)'' side [[FC Sakuona Plikiai]] have also attempted to license, but later withdrew their application.\n\nOnly [[FC Pakruojis]] have dropped out of the I Lyga, along with [[FC Stumbras#Stumbras B|Stumbras B]] which had gone out of business.\n\n===Participants===\n\n{{Location map+ |Lithuania |width=600 |float=right|caption= Home towns of the 2020 I Lyga teams|places=\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=right |label='''[[\u017dalgiris B]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=top |label='''[[Baltijos Futbolo Akademija|BFA]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=left|label='''[[Riteriai B]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=bottom|label='''[[Vilniaus Vytis]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=23|lon_deg=24|lon_min=03|position=bottom |label='''[[DFK Dainava|Dainava]]''' }}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=55|lat_min=59|lon_deg=22|lon_min=15|position=right |label='''[[FC D\u017eiugas Tel\u0161iai|D\u017eiugas]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=55|lat_min=53|lon_deg=21|lon_min=14|position=right |label='''[[FK Minija (2017)|Minija]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=53|lon_deg=23|lon_min=56|position=left  |label='''[[FC Hegelmann Litauen|Hegelmann Litauen]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=55|lat_min=17|lon_deg=23|lon_min=59|position=right |label='''[[FK Nev\u0117\u017eis K\u0117dainiai|Nev\u0117\u017eis]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=55|lat_min=55|lon_deg=23|lon_min=19|position=bottom|label='''[[FA \u0160iauliai|\u0160iauliai]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=55|lat_min=04|lon_deg=24|lon_min=16|position=right |label='''[[FK Jonava|Jonava]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=56|lat_min=18|lon_deg=22|lon_min=20|position=bottom|label='''[[FK Atmosfera (2012)|Atmosfera]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=53|lon_deg=23|lon_min=56|position=right |label='''[[Kauno \u017dalgiris B]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat=55.739178|long=24.359505|position=right |label='''[[Panev\u0117\u017eys B]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat=54.574305|long=23.364513|position=right |label='''[[S\u016bduva B]]'''}}\n}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n!  Team  || Town || Stadium || Capacity  \n|-\n|[[FK Atmosfera (2012)]] || [[Ma\u017eeikiai]] || Ma\u017eeiki\u0173 miesto stadionas || 2,500 \n|-\n|[[Baltijos Futbolo Akademija]] || [[Vilnius]] || Fabijoni\u0161ki\u0173 stadionas || 340  \n|-\n|[[DFK Dainava]] || [[Alytus]] || Alytaus miesto stadionas || 4,000 \n|-\n|[[FC D\u017eiugas]] || [[Tel\u0161iai]] || Tel\u0161i\u0173 miesto centrinis stadionas || 3,000 \n|-\n|[[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] || [[Kaunas]] || NFA stadionas || 1,000 \n|-\n|[[FK Jonava]] || [[Jonava]] || Jonavos miesto stadionas || 1,400 \n|-\n|[[FK Kauno \u017dalgiris#Kauno \u017dalgiris B|Kauno \u017dalgiris B]] || [[Kaunas]] || [[SM Tauras Stadium]] || 500 \n|-\n|[[FK Minija (2017)]] || [[Kretinga]] || Kretingos miesto stadionas || 1,000 \n|-\n|[[FK Nev\u0117\u017eis]] || [[K\u0117dainiai]] || K\u0117daini\u0173 miesto centrinis stadionas || 3,000 \n|-\n|[[FK Panev\u0117\u017eys#Panev\u0117\u017eys B|Panev\u0117\u017eys B]] || [[Panev\u0117\u017eys]] || [[Auk\u0161taitija Stadium]] || 6,600 \n|-\n|[[FK Riteriai#Riteriai B|Riteriai B]] || [[Vilnius]] || [[LFF Stadium]] || 5,400 \n|-\n|[[FK S\u016bduva#S\u016bduva B|S\u016bduva B]] || [[Marijampol\u0117]] || [[ARVI Football Arena]] || 6,250 \n|-\n|[[FA \u0160iauliai]] || [[\u0160iauliai]] || Savivaldyb\u0117s stadionas || 9,125 \n|-\n|[[Vilniaus Vytis]] || [[Vilnius]] || [[LFF Stadium]] || 5,400\n|-\n|[[FK \u017dalgiris#\u017dalgiris B|\u017dalgiris B]] || [[Vilnius]] ||  [[LFF Stadium]]  || 5,400 \n|}\n\n==Season progress==\nThe [[Lithuanian Football Federation]] announced that top four teams will qualify for promotion to A Lyga next season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9599/vykdomojo-komiteto-posedzio-metu-patvirtintas-i-ir-a-lygu-komandu-skaicius/\n|website=LFF\n|title=Vykdomojo komiteto pos\u0117d\u017eio metu patvirtintas I ir A lyg\u0173 komand\u0173 skai\u010dius\n|date=2020-02-26\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\n===Results===\n{{Inprogress}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 A Lyga]]\n* [[Football in Lithuania]]\n* [[2020 Lithuanian Football Cup]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://lietuvosfutbolas.lt/varzybos/vyru/i-lyga/ Official I Lyga results] {{in lang|lt}}\n{{Template:2020 in Lithuanian football}}\n[[Category:I Lyga seasons]]\n[[Category:2020 in Lithuanian football]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 in European second tier association football leagues|Lith]]\n[[Category:2020\u201321 in European second tier association football leagues|Lith]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football league season\n| logo               = \n| pixels             = \n| caption            = \n| competition        = [[I Lyga]]\n| season             = 2020\n| winners            = \n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = \n| matches            = \n| total goals        = \n| league topscorer   = \n| biggest home win   = \n| biggest away win   = \n| highest scoring    = \n| longest wins       = \n| longest unbeaten   = \n| longest winless    = \n| longest losses     = \n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| attendance         = \n| average attendance = \n| updated            = \n| prevseason         = [[2019 LFF I Lyga|2019]]\n| nextseason         = 2021\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 LFF I Lyga''' is the 31st season of the [[I Lyga]], the second tier [[association football|football]] league of [[Lithuania]]. The season begins in March and finishes in October.\n\n==Teams==\nThe last-placed [[A Lyga]] team is normally relegated to I Lyga. Since [[FC Stumbras]] had gone out of business in July 2019, no team was relegated from A Lyga in 2019. The 7th placed team in A Lyga contests a play-off match with 2nd placed I Lyga team. In this play-off match [[FK Banga Garg\u017edai]] beat A Lyga side [[FC Palanga]] to claim a spot in the A Lyga.\n\nTwo teams from the [[II Lyga]] are promoted to I Lyga, the winners of each of the two II Lyga groups. Last season's winners were [[Kauno \u017dalgiris B]] and [[FSK Radvili\u0161kis]].\n\nIn Lithuanian football, ultimately the licensing process determines clubs eligibility to contest in the respective league.\n\n===Licensing Process===\nAt the end of [[2019 A Lyga]] season, a match fixing investigation was launched after irregular betting patterns were reported. In December 2019 the results of the investigation were published, resulting expulsion of [[FK Atlantas]] and [[FC Palanga]] from A Lyga, and their demotion to II Lyga. The clubs appealed, but their appeals were rejected. The clubs attempted to license to I Lyga, but the decision to demote the clubs to II Lyga stood ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9442/2020-m-sezono-i-lygos-licenciju-sieks-14-futbolo-klubu-ir-komandu/\n|website=LFF\n|title=2020 m. sezono I lygos licencij\u0173 sieks 14 futbolo klub\u0173 ir komand\u0173\n|date=2020-02-19\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9419/fk-atlantas-ir-fk-palanga-del-manipuliavimo-rezultatais-yra-salinami-is-a-lygos/\n|website=LFF\n|title=FK \"Atlantas\" ir FK \"Palanga\" d\u0117l manipuliavimo rezultatais yra \u0161alinami i\u0161 A lygos\n|date=2019-12-05\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nWith reduction of numbers in A Lyga, several I Lyga clubs attempted to leapfrog into promotion to A Lyga. [[DFK Dainava]], [[Vilniaus Vytis]] and [[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] have applied for A Lyga license. [[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] later withdrew their application, while [[DFK Dainava]] and [[Vilniaus Vytis]] had their applications rejected. [[FC D\u017eiugas]], last season's I Lyga winners application was also rejected failing to meet several criteria. [[FK Banga Garg\u017edai]] was the only I Lyga club that successfully licensed to A Lyga. Three of the four other applicants, [[FC D\u017eiugas]], [[DFK Dainava]] and [[FC Hegelmann Litauen]] I Lyga licenses were automatically approved. [[Vilniaus Vytis]] failed to meet I Lyga licensing criteria, and license was not issued even after the appeal. However, the club was granted an exception with a condition that the club reaches certain milestones by 9 March. Vytis will start the season with 3 point penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9466/isibegeja-a-ir-i-lygos-klubu-licencijavimo-sezonas/\n|website=LFF\n|title=\u012esib\u0117g\u0117ja A ir I lygos klub\u0173 licencijavimo sezonas\n|date=2020-01-13\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9582/licencijavimo-komitetas-isdave-i-lygos-licencijas-13ai-klubu-ir-komandu/\n|website=LFF\n|title=Licencijavimo komitetas i\u0161dav\u0117 I lygos licencijas 13 klub\u0173 ir komand\u0173\n|date=2020-02-19\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 further match fixing investigation results were published. As a result, [[FC Kupi\u0161kis]] was fined and expelled from I Lyga.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9546/del-manipuliavimo-rezultatais-fc-kupiskis-salinamas-is-i-lygos/\n|website=LFF\n|title=D\u0117l manipuliavimo rezultatais FC Kupi\u0161kis \u0161alinamas i\u0161 I lygos\n|date=2020-02-11\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nOther I Lyga teams [[FK Nev\u0117\u017eis]], [[FA \u0160iauliai]], [[Baltijos Futbolo Akademija]] (which split up from partnership with [[FK Vilnius (2019)]]), [[FK Minija (2017)]], [[FK Jonava]] , [[FK Riteriai#Riteriai B|Riteriai B]] renewed their licenses successfully, although [[FK Nev\u0117\u017eis]] needed to go through the appeal process. Successful licensing to I Lyga was awarded to [[FK Atmosfera (2012)]] and [[FK \u017dalgiris#\u017dalgiris B|\u017dalgiris B]] as well, despite their results suggesting relegation to II Lyga.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lff.lt/news/9595/apeliacinio-licencijavimo-komiteto-sprendimai-del-i-lygos-licencijos-pareiskeju-apeliaciju/\n|website=LFF\n|title=Apeliacinio licencijavimo komiteto sprendimai d\u0117l I lygos licencijos parei\u0161k\u0117j\u0173 apeliacij\u0173\n|date=2020-02-25\n|accessdate=2020-02-26\n}}</ref>\n\nThree [[II Lyga]] teams licensed successfully to I Lyga - II Lyga Southern Group winners [[Kauno \u017dalgiris B]], as well as 4th placed [[Panev\u0117\u017eys B]] and 13th placed [[S\u016bduva B]]. Other II Lyga teams that sought I Lyga licenses were [[FK Auk\u0161taitija]] and the II Lyga Western Group winners [[FSK Radvili\u0161kis]]. The licensing criteria were not met and the promotion was not granted. [[FK Auk\u0161taitija]] asked to grant an exception to participate without a license, but this request was rejected as well.\n\n[[III Lyga]] ''([[Klaip\u0117da]]`s zone)'' side [[FC Sakuona Plikiai]] have also attempted to license, but later withdrew their application.\n\nOnly [[FC Pakruojis]] have dropped out of the I Lyga, along with [[FC Stumbras#Stumbras B|Stumbras B]] which had gone out of business.\n\n===Participants===\n\n{{Location map+ |Lithuania |width=600 |float=right|caption= Home towns of the 2020 I Lyga teams|places=\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=right |label='''[[\u017dalgiris B]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=top |label='''[[BFA]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=left|label='''[[Riteriai B]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=39|lon_deg=25|lon_min=18|position=bottom|label='''[[Vilniaus Vytis]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=54|lat_min=23|lon_deg=24|lon_min=03|position=bottom |label='''[[DFK Dainava|Dainava]]''' }}\n{{Location map~ |Lithuania |lat_deg=55|lat_min=59|lon_deg=22|lon_min=15|position