FF_I_Lyga"}
{"title_page": "Julia Azari", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Julia Azari\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]|[[Yale University]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Marquette University]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Best Public-Facing Scholarship Award, [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]|Founder's Best Paper Award, APSA}}\n}}\n'''Julia R. Azari''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]]. She is a professor of political science at [[Marquette University]], where she is also the Assistant Chair of the Department of Political Science. Azari studies the [[President of the United States|American Presidency]] and [[Political parties in the United States]], with particular attention to [[Partisan (politics)#United States|partisanship in the United States]] and how these systems have changed since the early 20th century. Azari also engages in public communication about political science, including as a frequent contributor to the politics coverage of the data journalism website ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'', a writer of the ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' blog ''Mischiefs of Faction'', and a host of the political science podcast ''Politics in Question''.\n\n==Education and early work==\nAzari attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/political-science/directory/julia-azari.php |title=Julia Azari, PhD |publisher=Marquette University |date= |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She originally intended to become a [[Political journalism|political journalist]], but realized that she enjoyed academic political science.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pol.illinois.edu/spotlight/alumni/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari |publisher=University of Illinois |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She graduated with a B.A. degree in political science in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uofi150.news-gazette.com/people/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari Profile |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |work=University of Illinois News-Gazette |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She then received an M.Phil, an M.A., and a Ph.D. in political science at [[Yale University]].<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\n===Research===\nIn 2014 Azari published the book ''Delivering the People's Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate'', which studies the history of the idea of a [[Mandate (politics)|political mandate]] for the President of the United States, from [[Herbert Hoover]] in 1928 to the election of [[Barack Obama]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Gemma |last=Horton |title=Delivering the People\u2019s Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate |journal=Information, Communication & Society |volume=21 |issue=12 |date=23 February 2018 |pages=1836\u20131838 |doi=10.1080/1369118X.2018.1442490}}</ref> Azari uses [[content analysis]] on presidents' communications to analyze how presidents have used the idea of a presidential mandate, showing that over the last several decades presidents have increasingly invoked the idea of a mandate to defend the legitimacy of the office.<ref>{{cite journal |first=R.P |last=Seyb |title=Azari, Julia R. Delivering the people's message: the changing politics of the presidential mandate. Cornell, 2014. 206p index afp ISBN 9780801452246 cloth, $39.95 |journal=CHOICE: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries |volume=52 |issue=4 |date=1 December 2014 |pages=701}}</ref>\n\nTogether with William D. Adler, Azari won the 2019 Founder's Best Paper Award from the American Political Science Association for their working paper \"The Party Decides (Who the Vice President Will Be)\". The Founder's Award \"is given for the best paper on executive politics authored by a PhD-holding scholar at the previous year's\" meeting of the American Political Science Association.<ref name=found>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/ps-political-science-and-politics/article/2019-apsa-organized-section-awards/0AB2943B3604C9CAD07DB2B194BC3B4C/core-reader |title=Founder's Best Paper Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/political-science/news-archive.php |title=2019-20 Academic Year News |publisher=Marquette University |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of Azari's work in science communication, including posts on the ''Mischiefs of Faction'' blog, have also in turn been cited in academic literature.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Christopher M Federico |author2=Agnieszka Golec de Zavala |title=Collective Narcissism and the 2016 US Presidential Vote |journal=Public Opinion Quarterly |volume=82 |issue=1 |date=21 February 2018 |pages=110\u2013121 |doi=10.1093/poq/nfx048}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Peter Buisseret |author2=Richard Van Weelden |title=American Journal of Political Science |journal=American Journal of Political Science |doi=10.1111/ajps.12457}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1=Frances E. Lee |editor2=Nolan McCarty |author1=Daniel Schlozman |author2=Sam Rosenfeld |title=The Hollow Parties |page=353}}</ref>\n\n===Science communication===\nAzari has been a frequent contributor to the data journalism website ''FiveThirtyEight'' since 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/contributors/julia-azari/page/11/ |title=All posts by Julia Azari |publisher=FiveThirthyEight |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> both as an author of articles and as a guest on the ''FiveThirtyEight Politics Podcast''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/politics-podcast-will-trump-face-a-primary-challenge/ |title=Politics Podcast: Will Trump Face A Primary Challenge? |publisher=FiveThirtyEight |date=10 January 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/politics-podcast-what-does-it-mean-to-be-electable/ |title=Politics Podcast: What Does It Mean To Be 'Electable'? |publisher=FiveThirtyEight |date=10 January 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Azari also regularly writes for ''Mischiefs of Faction'', which was founded as an independent political science blog in 2012, and in 2015 was incorporated into ''Vox''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/mischiefs-of-faction/2015/9/9/9280495/mischiefs-of-faction |title=Mischiefs of Faction, now on Vox |date=9 September 2015 |work=Vox |last=Azari |first=Julia |display-authors=1 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Azari has also appeared as an expert on television panels and interviews, including appearances on [[C-SPAN]] dating back to 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.c-span.org/search/?searchtype=Videos&sort=Newest&personid[]=9266357 |title=Julia Azari |publisher=C-SPAN |year=2018 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> as well as on radio stations like [[Wisconsin Public Radio]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wpr.org/people/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari |publisher=Wisconsin Public Radio |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> and [[KCRW]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kcrw.com/people/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari |publisher=KCRW Radio |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She has also directed or engaged in public events about politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://resources.twc.edu/articles/introducing-campaign-2020-dnc-faculty-director-julia-azari |title=Introducing Campaign 2020 Faculty Director for the DNC, Dr. Julia Azari |publisher=The Washington Center |date=13 June 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Azari was the recipient of the inaugural Best Public-Facing Scholarship Award from the [[American Political Science Association]], which recognizes the \"best public-facing scholarship published in the previous calendar year\", including \"blog posts and popular press publications intended for a broad public audience\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/ps-political-science-and-politics/article/2019-apsa-organized-section-awards/0AB2943B3604C9CAD07DB2B194BC3B4C/core-reader |title=Best Public-Facing Scholarship |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Azari has also been recognized for her public discussions of the role and value of political science communication, and the undervaluing of communication work by some universities.<ref name=bps>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@nberlat/we-need-more-support-for-public-facing-scholarship-b706b85862b7 |title=We Need More Support For Public Facing Scholarship |last=Berlatsky |first=Noah |date=25 March 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://marquettewire.org/4014420/news/mu-omits-woman-professors-title-but-not-mens/ |title=MU omits woman professor\u2019s title, but not men's |date=17 July 2019 |work=Marquette Wire |author1=Sydney Czyzon |author2=Sarah Lipo |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"Unwritten rules: Informal institutions in established democracies\", ''Perspectives on Politics'' 10 (1), 37\u201355, with Jennifer K. Smith (2012)<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Julia Azari |author2=Jennifer K. Smith |title=Unwritten rules: Informal institutions in established democracies |journal=Perspectives on Politics |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2012 |pages=37\u201355}}</ref>\n*''Delivering the People's Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate'' (2014)<ref>{{cite book |first=Julia |last=Azari |title=Delivering the People's Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate |year=2014}}</ref>\n*\"How the news media helped to nominate Trump\", ''Political Communication'' 33 (4), 677\u2013680 (2016)<ref>{{cite journal |first=Julia |last=Azari |title=How the news media helped to nominate Trump |journal=Political Communication |volume=33 |issue=4 |year=2016 |pages=677\u2013680}}</ref>\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Best Public-Facing Scholarship Award, American Political Science Association (2019)<ref name=bps/>\n*Founder's Best Paper Award, American Political Science Association (2019)<ref name=found/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azari, Julia}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Marquette University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Julia Azari\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]|[[Yale University]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Marquette University]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Best Public-Facing Scholarship Award, [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]|Founder's Best Paper Award, APSA}}\n}}\n'''Julia R. Azari''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]]. She is a professor of political science at [[Marquette University]], where she is also the Assistant Chair of the Department of Political Science. Azari studies the [[President of the United States|American Presidency]] and [[Political parties in the United States]], with particular attention to [[Partisan (politics)#United States|partisanship in the United States]] and how these systems have changed since the early 20th century. Azari also engages in public communication about political science, including as a frequent contributor to the politics coverage of the data journalism website ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'', a writer of the ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' blog ''Mischiefs of Faction'', and a host of the political science podcast ''Politics in Question''.\n\n==Education and early work==\nAzari attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/political-science/directory/julia-azari.php |title=Julia Azari, PhD |publisher=Marquette University |date= |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She originally intended to become a [[Political journalism|political journalist]], but realized that she enjoyed academic political science.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pol.illinois.edu/spotlight/alumni/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari |publisher=University of Illinois |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She graduated with a B.A. degree in political science in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uofi150.news-gazette.com/people/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari Profile |publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |work=University of Illinois News-Gazette |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She then received an M.Phil, an M.A., and a Ph.D. at [[Yale University]].<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\n===Research===\nIn 2014 Azari published the book ''Delivering the People's Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate'', which studies the history of the idea of a [[Mandate (politics)|political mandate]] for the President of the United States, from [[Herbert Hoover]] in 1928 to the election of [[Barack Obama]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Gemma |last=Horton |title=Delivering the People\u2019s Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate |journal=Information, Communication & Society |volume=21 |issue=12 |date=23 February 2018 |pages=1836\u20131838 |doi=10.1080/1369118X.2018.1442490}}</ref> Azari uses [[content analysis]] on presidents' communications to analyze how presidents have used the idea of a presidential mandate, showing that over the last several decades presidents have increasingly invoked the idea of a mandate to defend the legitimacy of the office.<ref>{{cite journal |first=R.P |last=Seyb |title=Azari, Julia R. Delivering the people's message: the changing politics of the presidential mandate. Cornell, 2014. 206p index afp ISBN 9780801452246 cloth, $39.95 |journal=CHOICE: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries |volume=52 |issue=4 |date=1 December 2014 |pages=701}}</ref>\n\nTogether with William D. Adler, Azari won the 2019 Founder's Best Paper Award from the American Political Science Association for their working paper \"The Party Decides (Who the Vice President Will Be)\". The Founder's Award \"is given for the best paper on executive politics authored by a PhD-holding scholar at the previous year's\" meeting of the American Political Science Association.<ref name=found>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/ps-political-science-and-politics/article/2019-apsa-organized-section-awards/0AB2943B3604C9CAD07DB2B194BC3B4C/core-reader |title=Founder's Best Paper Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/political-science/news-archive.php |title=2019-20 Academic Year News |publisher=Marquette University |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of Azari's work in science communication, including posts on the ''Mischiefs of Faction'' blog, have also in turn been cited in academic literature.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Christopher M Federico |author2=Agnieszka Golec de Zavala |title=Collective Narcissism and the 2016 US Presidential Vote |journal=Public Opinion Quarterly |volume=82 |issue=1 |date=21 February 2018 |pages=110\u2013121 |doi=10.1093/poq/nfx048}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Peter Buisseret |author2=Richard Van Weelden |title=American Journal of Political Science |journal=American Journal of Political Science |doi=10.1111/ajps.12457}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1=Frances E. Lee |editor2=Nolan McCarty |author1=Daniel Schlozman |author2=Sam Rosenfeld |title=The Hollow Parties |page=353}}</ref>\n\n===Science communication===\nAzari has been a frequent contributor to the data journalism website ''FiveThirtyEight'' since 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/contributors/julia-azari/page/11/ |title=All posts by Julia Azari |publisher=FiveThirthyEight |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> both as an author of articles and as a guest on the ''FiveThirtyEight Politics Podcast''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/politics-podcast-will-trump-face-a-primary-challenge/ |title=Politics Podcast: Will Trump Face A Primary Challenge? |publisher=FiveThirtyEight |date=10 January 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/politics-podcast-what-does-it-mean-to-be-electable/ |title=Politics Podcast: What Does It Mean To Be 'Electable'? |publisher=FiveThirtyEight |date=10 January 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Azari also regularly writes for ''Mischiefs of Faction'', which was founded as an independent political science blog in 2012, and in 2015 was incorporated into ''Vox''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/mischiefs-of-faction/2015/9/9/9280495/mischiefs-of-faction |title=Mischiefs of Faction, now on Vox |date=9 September 2015 |work=Vox |last=Azari |first=Julia |display-authors=1 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Azari has also appeared as an expert on television panels and interviews, including appearances on [[C-SPAN]] dating back to 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.c-span.org/search/?searchtype=Videos&sort=Newest&personid[]=9266357 |title=Julia Azari |publisher=C-SPAN |year=2018 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> as well as on radio stations like [[Wisconsin Public Radio]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wpr.org/people/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari |publisher=Wisconsin Public Radio |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> and [[KCRW]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kcrw.com/people/julia-azari |title=Julia Azari |publisher=KCRW Radio |year=2020 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> She has also directed or engaged in public events about politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://resources.twc.edu/articles/introducing-campaign-2020-dnc-faculty-director-julia-azari |title=Introducing Campaign 2020 Faculty Director for the DNC, Dr. Julia Azari |publisher=The Washington Center |date=13 June 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Azari was the recipient of the inaugural Best Public-Facing Scholarship Award from the [[American Political Science Association]], which recognizes the \"best public-facing scholarship published in the previous calendar year\", including \"blog posts and popular press publications intended for a broad public audience\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/ps-political-science-and-politics/article/2019-apsa-organized-section-awards/0AB2943B3604C9CAD07DB2B194BC3B4C/core-reader |title=Best Public-Facing Scholarship |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Azari has also been recognized for her public discussions of the role and value of political science communication, and the undervaluing of communication work by some universities.<ref name=bps>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@nberlat/we-need-more-support-for-public-facing-scholarship-b706b85862b7 |title=We Need More Support For Public Facing Scholarship |last=Berlatsky |first=Noah |date=25 March 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://marquettewire.org/4014420/news/mu-omits-woman-professors-title-but-not-mens/ |title=MU omits woman professor\u2019s title, but not men's |date=17 July 2019 |work=Marquette Wire |author1=Sydney Czyzon |author2=Sarah Lipo |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"Unwritten rules: Informal institutions in established democracies\", ''Perspectives on Politics'' 10 (1), 37\u201355, with Jennifer K. Smith (2012)<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Julia Azari |author2=Jennifer K. Smith |title=Unwritten rules: Informal institutions in established democracies |journal=Perspectives on Politics |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2012 |pages=37\u201355}}</ref>\n*''Delivering the People's Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate'' (2014)<ref>{{cite book |first=Julia |last=Azari |title=Delivering the People's Message: The Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate |year=2014}}</ref>\n*\"How the news media helped to nominate Trump\", ''Political Communication'' 33 (4), 677\u2013680 (2016)<ref>{{cite journal |first=Julia |last=Azari |title=How the news media helped to nominate Trump |journal=Political Communication |volume=33 |issue=4 |year=2016 |pages=677\u2013680}}</ref>\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Best Public-Facing Scholarship Award, American Political Science Association (2019)<ref name=bps/>\n*Founder's Best Paper Award, American Political Science Association (2019)<ref name=found/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azari, Julia}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Marquette University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation and early work:defs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julia_Azari"}
{"title_page": "1911 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=drop caps as per [[MOS:HEADINGS]]|date=April 2020}}\nThe 1911 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was the second full organised club season in Auckland following the [[1910 Auckland Rugby League season]]. It featured a representative program in August and September where [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] went undefeated. The season commenced on 20 May, with the start of the competition for the Myers Cup.\n\nUnlike in 1910 when only two venues were used, there were 5 venues used. They were [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]], Takapuna Racecourse, 'Avondale', [[Auckland Domain]], and [[Eden Park]] (which was the venue for the club final between [[City Rovers]] and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]].\n\n==Eden Ramblers Formed==\nThe senior competition saw the addition of the Eden Ramblers who had been formed in April. A meeting was held at the Avondale Public Hall on Wednesday 26 April with Mr [[John Bollard (politician)|John Bollard, MP]] presiding over it. He was elected president and chairman, and the name Eden Ramblers was chosen along with the colours or green and gold. The following officers were selected: Hon Secretary, Mr B Boone; Management Committee, W. A. Cummings, J Eddoes, W Fairweather, M Morrow, and J Denyer. The membership was close to 50 and they were to begin their training for the season ahead on 29 April with a join practice with Ponsonby at Victoria Park.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Eden Ramblers Club\n| page = 4\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume XLVIII, Issue 14666\n| date = 1911-04-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19110428.2.10\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n        {{s-bef|before=[[1910 Auckland Rugby League season|1910]]}}\n        {{s-ttl|title=3rd [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n        |years=\t1911}}\n        {{s-aft|after=[[1912 Auckland Rugby League season|1912]]}}\n        {{end}}\n\n==Myers Cup==\nEighteen regular season matches were played before the final on 16 September where [[City Rovers]] defeated [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] 36 to 15 to retain the title which they had won in 1910.\n\n===Final Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|8||7||0||1||164||70||'''14'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|9||7||0||2||205||117||'''14'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|7||3||0||4||80||68||'''6'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|7||1||0||6||51||138||'''2'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Eden Ramblers]]\n|7||1||0||6||42||149||'''2'''\n|-\n|}\nThe second round did not feature the final round of matches hence [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]] playing an extra match (when they were due to have a bye), while the table also includes the final played between [[City Rovers|City]] and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]].\n\n==Myers Cup Fixtures and Results==\n===Round 1===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 May\n| time =\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 19\u20133\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ponsonby v Newton\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume XLII, Issue 120\n| date = 1911-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19110522.2.65\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = Newton\n| try1 = [[Charlie Savory]], S Cole, C Dillamore, Syd Riley 2\n| con1 = S Cole 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Sainsbury\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria park\n| attendance =\n| referee = Jaggs\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 May\n| time =\n| home = City\n| score = 13\u20133\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title 